92def _single_replace(self, to_replace, method, inplace, limit): 

93 """ 

94 Replaces values in a Series using the fill method specified when no 

95 replacement value is given in the replace method 

96 """ 

97 if self.ndim != 1: 

98 raise TypeError( 

99 "cannot replace {0} with method {1} on a {2}".format( 

100 to_replace, method, type(self).__name__ 

101 ) 

102 ) 

103 

104 orig_dtype = self.dtype 

105 result = self if inplace else self.copy() 

106 fill_f = missing.get_fill_func(method) 

107 

108 mask = missing.mask_missing(result.values, to_replace) 

109 values = fill_f(result.values, limit=limit, mask=mask) 

110 

111 if values.dtype == orig_dtype and inplace: 

112 return 

113 

114 result = pd.Series(values, index=self.index, dtype=self.dtype).__finalize__(self) 

115 

116 if inplace: 

117 self._update_inplace(result._data) 

118 return 

119 

120 return result

123class NDFrame(PandasObject, SelectionMixin): 

124 """ 

125 N-dimensional analogue of DataFrame. Store multi-dimensional in a 

126 size-mutable, labeled data structure 

127 

128 Parameters 

129 ---------- 

130 data : BlockManager 

131 axes : list 

132 copy : boolean, default False 

133 """ 

134 

135 _internal_names = [ 

136 "_data", 

137 "_cacher", 

138 "_item_cache", 

139 "_cache", 

140 "_is_copy", 

141 "_subtyp", 

142 "_name", 

143 "_index", 

144 "_default_kind", 

145 "_default_fill_value", 

146 "_metadata", 

147 "__array_struct__", 

148 "__array_interface__", 

149 ] # type: List[str] 

150 _internal_names_set = set(_internal_names) # type: Set[str] 

151 _accessors = set() # type: Set[str] 

152 _deprecations = frozenset( 

153 ["as_blocks", "blocks", "is_copy", "ftypes", "ix"] 

154 ) # type: FrozenSet[str] 

155 _metadata = [] # type: List[str] 

156 _is_copy = None 

157 _data = None # type: BlockManager

159 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

160 # Constructors 

161 

162 def __init__( 

163 self, 

164 data: BlockManager, 

165 axes: Optional[List[Index]] = None, 

166 copy: bool = False, 

167 dtype: Optional[Dtype] = None, 

168 fastpath: bool = False, 

169 ): 

170 

171 if not fastpath: 

172 if dtype is not None: 

173 data = data.astype(dtype) 

174 elif copy: 

175 data = data.copy() 

176 

177 if axes is not None: 

178 for i, ax in enumerate(axes): 

179 data = data.reindex_axis(ax, axis=i) 

180 

181 object.__setattr__(self, "_is_copy", None) 

182 object.__setattr__(self, "_data", data) 

183 object.__setattr__(self, "_item_cache", {}) 

184 

185 def _init_mgr(self, mgr, axes=None, dtype=None, copy=False): 

186 """ passed a manager and a axes dict """ 

187 for a, axe in axes.items(): 

188 if axe is not None: 

189 mgr = mgr.reindex_axis( 

190 axe, axis=self._get_block_manager_axis(a), copy=False 

191 ) 

192 

193 # make a copy if explicitly requested 

194 if copy: 

195 mgr = mgr.copy() 

196 if dtype is not None: 

197 # avoid further copies if we can 

198 if len(mgr.blocks) > 1 or mgr.blocks[0].values.dtype != dtype: 

199 mgr = mgr.astype(dtype=dtype) 

200 return mgr

227 def _validate_dtype(self, dtype): 

228 """ validate the passed dtype """ 

229 

230 if dtype is not None: 

231 dtype = pandas_dtype(dtype) 

232 

233 # a compound dtype 

234 if dtype.kind == "V": 

235 raise NotImplementedError( 

236 "compound dtypes are not implemented" 

237 " in the {0} constructor".format(self.__class__.__name__) 

238 ) 

239 

240 return dtype

269 @classmethod 

270 def _setup_axes( 

271 cls, 

272 axes, 

273 info_axis=None, 

274 stat_axis=None, 

275 aliases=None, 

276 axes_are_reversed=False, 

277 build_axes=True, 

278 ns=None, 

279 docs=None, 

280 ): 

281 """Provide axes setup for the major PandasObjects. 

282 

283 Parameters 

284 ---------- 

285 axes : the names of the axes in order (lowest to highest) 

286 info_axis_num : the axis of the selector dimension (int) 

287 stat_axis_num : the number of axis for the default stats (int) 

288 aliases : other names for a single axis (dict) 

289 axes_are_reversed : boolean whether to treat passed axes as 

290 reversed (DataFrame) 

291 build_axes : setup the axis properties (default True) 

292 """ 

293 

294 cls._AXIS_ORDERS = axes 

295 cls._AXIS_NUMBERS = {a: i for i, a in enumerate(axes)} 

296 cls._AXIS_LEN = len(axes) 

297 cls._AXIS_ALIASES = aliases or dict() 

298 cls._AXIS_IALIASES = {v: k for k, v in cls._AXIS_ALIASES.items()} 

299 cls._AXIS_NAMES = dict(enumerate(axes)) 

300 cls._AXIS_REVERSED = axes_are_reversed 

301 

302 # typ 

303 setattr(cls, "_typ", cls.__name__.lower()) 

304 

305 # indexing support 

306 cls._ix = None 

307 

308 if info_axis is not None: 

309 cls._info_axis_number = info_axis 

310 cls._info_axis_name = axes[info_axis] 

311 

312 if stat_axis is not None: 

313 cls._stat_axis_number = stat_axis 

314 cls._stat_axis_name = axes[stat_axis] 

315 

316 # setup the actual axis 

317 if build_axes: 

318 

319 def set_axis(a, i): 

320 setattr(cls, a, properties.AxisProperty(i, docs.get(a, a))) 

321 cls._internal_names_set.add(a) 

322 

323 if axes_are_reversed: 

324 m = cls._AXIS_LEN - 1 

325 for i, a in cls._AXIS_NAMES.items(): 

326 set_axis(a, m - i) 

327 else: 

328 for i, a in cls._AXIS_NAMES.items(): 

329 set_axis(a, i) 

330 

331 assert not isinstance(ns, dict) 

332 

333 def _construct_axes_dict(self, axes=None, **kwargs): 

334 """Return an axes dictionary for myself.""" 

335 d = {a: self._get_axis(a) for a in (axes or self._AXIS_ORDERS)} 

336 d.update(kwargs) 

337 return d 

338 

339 @staticmethod 

340 def _construct_axes_dict_from(self, axes, **kwargs): 

341 """Return an axes dictionary for the passed axes.""" 

342 d = {a: ax for a, ax in zip(self._AXIS_ORDERS, axes)} 

343 d.update(kwargs) 

344 return d 

345 

346 def _construct_axes_from_arguments( 

347 self, args, kwargs, require_all=False, sentinel=None 

348 ): 

349 """Construct and returns axes if supplied in args/kwargs. 

350 

351 If require_all, raise if all axis arguments are not supplied 

352 return a tuple of (axes, kwargs). 

353 

354 sentinel specifies the default parameter when an axis is not 

355 supplied; useful to distinguish when a user explicitly passes None 

356 in scenarios where None has special meaning. 

357 """ 

358 

359 # construct the args 

360 args = list(args) 

361 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS: 

362 

363 # if we have an alias for this axis 

364 alias = self._AXIS_IALIASES.get(a) 

365 if alias is not None: 

366 if a in kwargs: 

367 if alias in kwargs: 

368 raise TypeError( 

369 "arguments are mutually exclusive " 

370 "for [%s,%s]" % (a, alias) 

371 ) 

372 continue 

373 if alias in kwargs: 

374 kwargs[a] = kwargs.pop(alias) 

375 continue 

376 

377 # look for a argument by position 

378 if a not in kwargs: 

379 try: 

380 kwargs[a] = args.pop(0) 

381 except IndexError: 

382 if require_all: 

383 raise TypeError("not enough/duplicate arguments " "specified!") 

384 

385 axes = {a: kwargs.pop(a, sentinel) for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS} 

386 return axes, kwargs 

387 

388 @classmethod 

389 def _from_axes(cls, data, axes, **kwargs): 

390 # for construction from BlockManager 

391 if isinstance(data, BlockManager): 

392 return cls(data, **kwargs) 

393 else: 

394 if cls._AXIS_REVERSED: 

395 axes = axes[::-1] 

396 d = cls._construct_axes_dict_from(cls, axes, copy=False) 

397 d.update(kwargs) 

398 return cls(data, **d) 

399 

400 @classmethod 

401 def _get_axis_number(cls, axis): 

402 axis = cls._AXIS_ALIASES.get(axis, axis) 

403 if is_integer(axis): 

404 if axis in cls._AXIS_NAMES: 

405 return axis 

406 else: 

407 try: 

408 return cls._AXIS_NUMBERS[axis] 

409 except KeyError: 

410 pass 

411 raise ValueError("No axis named {0} for object type {1}".format(axis, cls)) 

412 

413 @classmethod 

414 def _get_axis_name(cls, axis): 

415 axis = cls._AXIS_ALIASES.get(axis, axis) 

416 if isinstance(axis, str): 

417 if axis in cls._AXIS_NUMBERS: 

418 return axis 

419 else: 

420 try: 

421 return cls._AXIS_NAMES[axis] 

422 except KeyError: 

423 pass 

424 raise ValueError("No axis named {0} for object type {1}".format(axis, cls)) 

425 

426 def _get_axis(self, axis): 

427 name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

428 return getattr(self, name) 

429 

430 @classmethod 

431 def _get_block_manager_axis(cls, axis): 

432 """Map the axis to the block_manager axis.""" 

433 axis = cls._get_axis_number(axis) 

434 if cls._AXIS_REVERSED: 

435 m = cls._AXIS_LEN - 1 

436 return m - axis 

437 return axis 

438 

439 def _get_axis_resolvers(self, axis): 

440 # index or columns 

441 axis_index = getattr(self, axis) 

442 d = dict() 

443 prefix = axis[0] 

444 

445 for i, name in enumerate(axis_index.names): 

446 if name is not None: 

447 key = level = name 

448 else: 

449 # prefix with 'i' or 'c' depending on the input axis 

450 # e.g., you must do ilevel_0 for the 0th level of an unnamed 

451 # multiiindex 

452 key = "{prefix}level_{i}".format(prefix=prefix, i=i) 

453 level = i 

454 

455 level_values = axis_index.get_level_values(level) 

456 s = level_values.to_series() 

457 s.index = axis_index 

458 d[key] = s 

459 

460 # put the index/columns itself in the dict 

461 if isinstance(axis_index, MultiIndex): 

462 dindex = axis_index 

463 else: 

464 dindex = axis_index.to_series() 

465 

466 d[axis] = dindex 

467 return d 

468 

469 def _get_index_resolvers(self): 

470 d = {} 

471 for axis_name in self._AXIS_ORDERS: 

472 d.update(self._get_axis_resolvers(axis_name)) 

473 return d

567 def set_axis(self, labels, axis=0, inplace=None): 

568 """ 

569 Assign desired index to given axis. 

570 

571 Indexes for column or row labels can be changed by assigning 

572 a list-like or Index. 

573 

574 .. versionchanged:: 0.21.0 

575 

576 The signature is now `labels` and `axis`, consistent with 

577 the rest of pandas API. Previously, the `axis` and `labels` 

578 arguments were respectively the first and second positional 

579 arguments. 

580 

581 Parameters 

582 ---------- 

583 labels : list-like, Index 

584 The values for the new index. 

585 

586 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

587 The axis to update. The value 0 identifies the rows, and 1 

588 identifies the columns. 

589 

590 inplace : bool, default None 

591 Whether to return a new %(klass)s instance. 

592 

593 .. warning:: 

594 

595 ``inplace=None`` currently falls back to to True, but in a 

596 future version, will default to False. Use inplace=True 

597 explicitly rather than relying on the default. 

598 

599 Returns 

600 ------- 

601 renamed : %(klass)s or None 

602 An object of same type as caller if inplace=False, None otherwise. 

603 

604 See Also 

605 -------- 

606 DataFrame.rename_axis : Alter the name of the index or columns. 

607 

608 Examples 

609 -------- 

610 **Series** 

611 

612 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3]) 

613 >>> s 

614 0 1 

615 1 2 

616 2 3 

617 dtype: int64 

618 

619 >>> s.set_axis(['a', 'b', 'c'], axis=0, inplace=False) 

620 a 1 

621 b 2 

622 c 3 

623 dtype: int64 

624 

625 The original object is not modified. 

626 

627 >>> s 

628 0 1 

629 1 2 

630 2 3 

631 dtype: int64 

632 

633 **DataFrame** 

634 

635 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2, 3], "B": [4, 5, 6]}) 

636 

637 Change the row labels. 

638 

639 >>> df.set_axis(['a', 'b', 'c'], axis='index', inplace=False) 

640 A B 

641 a 1 4 

642 b 2 5 

643 c 3 6 

644 

645 Change the column labels. 

646 

647 >>> df.set_axis(['I', 'II'], axis='columns', inplace=False) 

648 I II 

649 0 1 4 

650 1 2 5 

651 2 3 6 

652 

653 Now, update the labels inplace. 

654 

655 >>> df.set_axis(['i', 'ii'], axis='columns', inplace=True) 

656 >>> df 

657 i ii 

658 0 1 4 

659 1 2 5 

660 2 3 6 

661 """ 

662 if is_scalar(labels): 

663 warnings.warn( 

664 'set_axis now takes "labels" as first argument, and ' 

665 '"axis" as named parameter. The old form, with "axis" as ' 

666 'first parameter and "labels" as second, is still supported ' 

667 "but will be deprecated in a future version of pandas.", 

668 FutureWarning, 

669 stacklevel=2, 

670 ) 

671 labels, axis = axis, labels 

672 

673 if inplace is None: 

674 warnings.warn( 

675 "set_axis currently defaults to operating inplace.\nThis " 

676 "will change in a future version of pandas, use " 

677 "inplace=True to avoid this warning.", 

678 FutureWarning, 

679 stacklevel=2, 

680 ) 

681 inplace = True 

682 if inplace: 

683 setattr(self, self._get_axis_name(axis), labels) 

684 else: 

685 obj = self.copy() 

686 obj.set_axis(labels, axis=axis, inplace=True) 

687 return obj 

688 

689 def _set_axis(self, axis, labels): 

690 self._data.set_axis(axis, labels) 

691 self._clear_item_cache()

693 def transpose(self, *args, **kwargs): 

694 """ 

695 Permute the dimensions of the %(klass)s 

696 

697 Parameters 

698 ---------- 

699 args : %(args_transpose)s 

700 copy : boolean, default False 

701 Make a copy of the underlying data. Mixed-dtype data will 

702 always result in a copy 

703 **kwargs 

704 Additional keyword arguments will be passed to the function. 

705 

706 Returns 

707 ------- 

708 y : same as input 

709 

710 Examples 

711 -------- 

712 >>> p.transpose(2, 0, 1) 

713 >>> p.transpose(2, 0, 1, copy=True) 

714 """ 

715 

716 # construct the args 

717 axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments( 

718 args, kwargs, require_all=True 

719 ) 

720 axes_names = tuple(self._get_axis_name(axes[a]) for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS) 

721 axes_numbers = tuple(self._get_axis_number(axes[a]) for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS) 

722 

723 # we must have unique axes 

724 if len(axes) != len(set(axes)): 

725 raise ValueError("Must specify %s unique axes" % self._AXIS_LEN) 

726 

727 new_axes = self._construct_axes_dict_from( 

728 self, [self._get_axis(x) for x in axes_names] 

729 ) 

730 new_values = self.values.transpose(axes_numbers) 

731 if kwargs.pop("copy", None) or (len(args) and args[-1]): 

732 new_values = new_values.copy() 

733 

734 nv.validate_transpose(tuple(), kwargs) 

735 return self._constructor(new_values, **new_axes).__finalize__(self) 

736 

737 def swapaxes(self, axis1, axis2, copy=True): 

738 """ 

739 Interchange axes and swap values axes appropriately. 

740 

741 Returns 

742 ------- 

743 y : same as input 

744 """ 

745 i = self._get_axis_number(axis1) 

746 j = self._get_axis_number(axis2) 

747 

748 if i == j: 

749 if copy: 

750 return self.copy() 

751 return self 

752 

753 mapping = {i: j, j: i} 

754 

755 new_axes = (self._get_axis(mapping.get(k, k)) for k in range(self._AXIS_LEN)) 

756 new_values = self.values.swapaxes(i, j) 

757 if copy: 

758 new_values = new_values.copy() 

759 

760 return self._constructor(new_values, *new_axes).__finalize__(self) 

761 

762 def droplevel(self, level, axis=0): 

763 """ 

764 Return DataFrame with requested index / column level(s) removed. 

765 

766 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

767 

768 Parameters 

769 ---------- 

770 level : int, str, or list-like 

771 If a string is given, must be the name of a level 

772 If list-like, elements must be names or positional indexes 

773 of levels. 

774 

775 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

776 

777 Returns 

778 ------- 

779 DataFrame.droplevel() 

780 

781 Examples 

782 -------- 

783 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([ 

784 ... [1, 2, 3, 4], 

785 ... [5, 6, 7, 8], 

786 ... [9, 10, 11, 12] 

787 ... ]).set_index([0, 1]).rename_axis(['a', 'b']) 

788 

789 >>> df.columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([ 

790 ... ('c', 'e'), ('d', 'f') 

791 ... ], names=['level_1', 'level_2']) 

792 

793 >>> df 

794 level_1 c d 

795 level_2 e f 

796 a b 

797 1 2 3 4 

798 5 6 7 8 

799 9 10 11 12 

800 

801 >>> df.droplevel('a') 

802 level_1 c d 

803 level_2 e f 

804 b 

805 2 3 4 

806 6 7 8 

807 10 11 12 

808 

809 >>> df.droplevel('level2', axis=1) 

810 level_1 c d 

811 a b 

812 1 2 3 4 

813 5 6 7 8 

814 9 10 11 12 

815 """ 

816 labels = self._get_axis(axis) 

817 new_labels = labels.droplevel(level) 

818 result = self.set_axis(new_labels, axis=axis, inplace=False) 

819 return result 

820 

821 def pop(self, item): 

822 """ 

823 Return item and drop from frame. Raise KeyError if not found. 

824 

825 Parameters 

826 ---------- 

827 item : str 

828 Label of column to be popped. 

829 

830 Returns 

831 ------- 

832 Series 

833 

834 Examples 

835 -------- 

836 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([('falcon', 'bird', 389.0), 

837 ... ('parrot', 'bird', 24.0), 

838 ... ('lion', 'mammal', 80.5), 

839 ... ('monkey','mammal', np.nan)], 

840 ... columns=('name', 'class', 'max_speed')) 

841 >>> df 

842 name class max_speed 

843 0 falcon bird 389.0 

844 1 parrot bird 24.0 

845 2 lion mammal 80.5 

846 3 monkey mammal NaN 

847 

848 >>> df.pop('class') 

849 0 bird 

850 1 bird 

851 2 mammal 

852 3 mammal 

853 Name: class, dtype: object 

854 

855 >>> df 

856 name max_speed 

857 0 falcon 389.0 

858 1 parrot 24.0 

859 2 lion 80.5 

860 3 monkey NaN 

861 """ 

862 result = self[item] 

863 del self[item] 

864 try: 

865 result._reset_cacher() 

866 except AttributeError: 

867 pass 

868 

869 return result 

870 

871 def squeeze(self, axis=None): 

872 """ 

873 Squeeze 1 dimensional axis objects into scalars. 

874 

875 Series or DataFrames with a single element are squeezed to a scalar. 

876 DataFrames with a single column or a single row are squeezed to a 

877 Series. Otherwise the object is unchanged. 

878 

879 This method is most useful when you don't know if your 

880 object is a Series or DataFrame, but you do know it has just a single 

881 column. In that case you can safely call `squeeze` to ensure you have a 

882 Series. 

883 

884 Parameters 

885 ---------- 

886 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default None 

887 A specific axis to squeeze. By default, all length-1 axes are 

888 squeezed. 

889 

890 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

891 

892 Returns 

893 ------- 

894 DataFrame, Series, or scalar 

895 The projection after squeezing `axis` or all the axes. 

896 

897 See Also 

898 -------- 

899 Series.iloc : Integer-location based indexing for selecting scalars. 

900 DataFrame.iloc : Integer-location based indexing for selecting Series. 

901 Series.to_frame : Inverse of DataFrame.squeeze for a 

902 single-column DataFrame. 

903 

904 Examples 

905 -------- 

906 >>> primes = pd.Series([2, 3, 5, 7]) 

907 

908 Slicing might produce a Series with a single value: 

909 

910 >>> even_primes = primes[primes % 2 == 0] 

911 >>> even_primes 

912 0 2 

913 dtype: int64 

914 

915 >>> even_primes.squeeze() 

916 2 

917 

918 Squeezing objects with more than one value in every axis does nothing: 

919 

920 >>> odd_primes = primes[primes % 2 == 1] 

921 >>> odd_primes 

922 1 3 

923 2 5 

924 3 7 

925 dtype: int64 

926 

927 >>> odd_primes.squeeze() 

928 1 3 

929 2 5 

930 3 7 

931 dtype: int64 

932 

933 Squeezing is even more effective when used with DataFrames. 

934 

935 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2], [3, 4]], columns=['a', 'b']) 

936 >>> df 

937 a b 

938 0 1 2 

939 1 3 4 

940 

941 Slicing a single column will produce a DataFrame with the columns 

942 having only one value: 

943 

944 >>> df_a = df[['a']] 

945 >>> df_a 

946 a 

947 0 1 

948 1 3 

949 

950 So the columns can be squeezed down, resulting in a Series: 

951 

952 >>> df_a.squeeze('columns') 

953 0 1 

954 1 3 

955 Name: a, dtype: int64 

956 

957 Slicing a single row from a single column will produce a single 

958 scalar DataFrame: 

959 

960 >>> df_0a = df.loc[df.index < 1, ['a']] 

961 >>> df_0a 

962 a 

963 0 1 

964 

965 Squeezing the rows produces a single scalar Series: 

966 

967 >>> df_0a.squeeze('rows') 

968 a 1 

969 Name: 0, dtype: int64 

970 

971 Squeezing all axes will project directly into a scalar: 

972 

973 >>> df_0a.squeeze() 

974 1 

975 """ 

976 axis = self._AXIS_NAMES if axis is None else (self._get_axis_number(axis),) 

977 try: 

978 return self.iloc[ 

979 tuple( 

980 0 if i in axis and len(a) == 1 else slice(None) 

981 for i, a in enumerate(self.axes) 

982 ) 

983 ] 

984 except Exception: 

985 return self 

986 

987 def swaplevel(self, i=-2, j=-1, axis=0): 

988 """ 

989 Swap levels i and j in a MultiIndex on a particular axis 

990 

991 Parameters 

992 ---------- 

993 i, j : int, str (can be mixed) 

994 Level of index to be swapped. Can pass level name as string. 

995 

996 Returns 

997 ------- 

998 swapped : same type as caller (new object) 

999 

1000 .. versionchanged:: 0.18.1 

1001 

1002 The indexes ``i`` and ``j`` are now optional, and default to 

1003 the two innermost levels of the index. 

1004 """ 

1005 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1006 result = self.copy() 

1007 labels = result._data.axes[axis] 

1008 result._data.set_axis(axis, labels.swaplevel(i, j)) 

1009 return result 

1010 

1011 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

1012 # Rename 

1013 

1014 def rename(self, *args, **kwargs): 

1015 """ 

1016 Alter axes input function or functions. Function / dict values must be 

1017 unique (1-to-1). Labels not contained in a dict / Series will be left 

1018 as-is. Extra labels listed don't throw an error. Alternatively, change 

1019 ``Series.name`` with a scalar value (Series only). 

1020 

1021 Parameters 

1022 ---------- 

1023 %(axes)s : scalar, list-like, dict-like or function, optional 

1024 Scalar or list-like will alter the ``Series.name`` attribute, 

1025 and raise on DataFrame. 

1026 dict-like or functions are transformations to apply to 

1027 that axis' values 

1028 copy : bool, default True 

1029 Also copy underlying data. 

1030 inplace : bool, default False 

1031 Whether to return a new %(klass)s. If True then value of copy is 

1032 ignored. 

1033 level : int or level name, default None 

1034 In case of a MultiIndex, only rename labels in the specified 

1035 level. 

1036 errors : {'ignore', 'raise'}, default 'ignore' 

1037 If 'raise', raise a `KeyError` when a dict-like `mapper`, `index`, 

1038 or `columns` contains labels that are not present in the Index 

1039 being transformed. 

1040 If 'ignore', existing keys will be renamed and extra keys will be 

1041 ignored. 

1042 

1043 Returns 

1044 ------- 

1045 renamed : %(klass)s (new object) 

1046 

1047 Raises 

1048 ------ 

1049 KeyError 

1050 If any of the labels is not found in the selected axis and 

1051 "errors='raise'". 

1052 

1053 See Also 

1054 -------- 

1055 NDFrame.rename_axis 

1056 

1057 Examples 

1058 -------- 

1059 

1060 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3]) 

1061 >>> s 

1062 0 1 

1063 1 2 

1064 2 3 

1065 dtype: int64 

1066 >>> s.rename("my_name") # scalar, changes Series.name 

1067 0 1 

1068 1 2 

1069 2 3 

1070 Name: my_name, dtype: int64 

1071 >>> s.rename(lambda x: x ** 2) # function, changes labels 

1072 0 1 

1073 1 2 

1074 4 3 

1075 dtype: int64 

1076 >>> s.rename({1: 3, 2: 5}) # mapping, changes labels 

1077 0 1 

1078 3 2 

1079 5 3 

1080 dtype: int64 

1081 

1082 Since ``DataFrame`` doesn't have a ``.name`` attribute, 

1083 only mapping-type arguments are allowed. 

1084 

1085 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2, 3], "B": [4, 5, 6]}) 

1086 >>> df.rename(2) 

1087 Traceback (most recent call last): 

1088 ... 

1089 TypeError: 'int' object is not callable 

1090 

1091 ``DataFrame.rename`` supports two calling conventions 

1092 

1093 * ``(index=index_mapper, columns=columns_mapper, ...)`` 

1094 * ``(mapper, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)`` 

1095 

1096 We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your 

1097 intent. 

1098 

1099 >>> df.rename(index=str, columns={"A": "a", "B": "c"}) 

1100 a c 

1101 0 1 4 

1102 1 2 5 

1103 2 3 6 

1104 

1105 >>> df.rename(index=str, columns={"A": "a", "C": "c"}) 

1106 a B 

1107 0 1 4 

1108 1 2 5 

1109 2 3 6 

1110 

1111 Using axis-style parameters 

1112 

1113 >>> df.rename(str.lower, axis='columns') 

1114 a b 

1115 0 1 4 

1116 1 2 5 

1117 2 3 6 

1118 

1119 >>> df.rename({1: 2, 2: 4}, axis='index') 

1120 A B 

1121 0 1 4 

1122 2 2 5 

1123 4 3 6 

1124 

1125 See the :ref:`user guide <basics.rename>` for more. 

1126 """ 

1127 axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments(args, kwargs) 

1128 copy = kwargs.pop("copy", True) 

1129 inplace = kwargs.pop("inplace", False) 

1130 level = kwargs.pop("level", None) 

1131 axis = kwargs.pop("axis", None) 

1132 errors = kwargs.pop("errors", "ignore") 

1133 if axis is not None: 

1134 # Validate the axis 

1135 self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1136 

1137 if kwargs: 

1138 raise TypeError( 

1139 "rename() got an unexpected keyword " 

1140 'argument "{0}"'.format(list(kwargs.keys())[0]) 

1141 ) 

1142 

1143 if com.count_not_none(*axes.values()) == 0: 

1144 raise TypeError("must pass an index to rename") 

1145 

1146 self._consolidate_inplace() 

1147 result = self if inplace else self.copy(deep=copy) 

1148 

1149 # start in the axis order to eliminate too many copies 

1150 for axis in range(self._AXIS_LEN): 

1151 v = axes.get(self._AXIS_NAMES[axis]) 

1152 if v is None: 

1153 continue 

1154 f = com._get_rename_function(v) 

1155 baxis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

1156 if level is not None: 

1157 level = self.axes[axis]._get_level_number(level) 

1158 

1159 # GH 13473 

1160 if not callable(v): 

1161 indexer = self.axes[axis].get_indexer_for(v) 

1162 if errors == "raise" and len(indexer[indexer == -1]): 

1163 missing_labels = [ 

1164 label for index, label in enumerate(v) if indexer[index] == -1 

1165 ] 

1166 raise KeyError("{} not found in axis".format(missing_labels)) 

1167 

1168 result._data = result._data.rename_axis( 

1169 f, axis=baxis, copy=copy, level=level 

1170 ) 

1171 result._clear_item_cache() 

1172 

1173 if inplace: 

1174 self._update_inplace(result._data) 

1175 else: 

1176 return result.__finalize__(self) 

1177 

1178 @rewrite_axis_style_signature("mapper", [("copy", True), ("inplace", False)]) 

1179 def rename_axis(self, mapper=sentinel, **kwargs): 

1180 """ 

1181 Set the name of the axis for the index or columns. 

1182 

1183 Parameters 

1184 ---------- 

1185 mapper : scalar, list-like, optional 

1186 Value to set the axis name attribute. 

1187 index, columns : scalar, list-like, dict-like or function, optional 

1188 A scalar, list-like, dict-like or functions transformations to 

1189 apply to that axis' values. 

1190 

1191 Use either ``mapper`` and ``axis`` to 

1192 specify the axis to target with ``mapper``, or ``index`` 

1193 and/or ``columns``. 

1194 

1195 .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0 

1196 

1197 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

1198 The axis to rename. 

1199 copy : bool, default True 

1200 Also copy underlying data. 

1201 inplace : bool, default False 

1202 Modifies the object directly, instead of creating a new Series 

1203 or DataFrame. 

1204 

1205 Returns 

1206 ------- 

1207 Series, DataFrame, or None 

1208 The same type as the caller or None if `inplace` is True. 

1209 

1210 See Also 

1211 -------- 

1212 Series.rename : Alter Series index labels or name. 

1213 DataFrame.rename : Alter DataFrame index labels or name. 

1214 Index.rename : Set new names on index. 

1215 

1216 Notes 

1217 ----- 

1218 ``DataFrame.rename_axis`` supports two calling conventions 

1219 

1220 * ``(index=index_mapper, columns=columns_mapper, ...)`` 

1221 * ``(mapper, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)`` 

1222 

1223 The first calling convention will only modify the names of 

1224 the index and/or the names of the Index object that is the columns. 

1225 In this case, the parameter ``copy`` is ignored. 

1226 

1227 The second calling convention will modify the names of the 

1228 the corresponding index if mapper is a list or a scalar. 

1229 However, if mapper is dict-like or a function, it will use the 

1230 deprecated behavior of modifying the axis *labels*. 

1231 

1232 We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your 

1233 intent. 

1234 

1235 Examples 

1236 -------- 

1237 **Series** 

1238 

1239 >>> s = pd.Series(["dog", "cat", "monkey"]) 

1240 >>> s 

1241 0 dog 

1242 1 cat 

1243 2 monkey 

1244 dtype: object 

1245 >>> s.rename_axis("animal") 

1246 animal 

1247 0 dog 

1248 1 cat 

1249 2 monkey 

1250 dtype: object 

1251 

1252 **DataFrame** 

1253 

1254 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"num_legs": [4, 4, 2], 

1255 ... "num_arms": [0, 0, 2]}, 

1256 ... ["dog", "cat", "monkey"]) 

1257 >>> df 

1258 num_legs num_arms 

1259 dog 4 0 

1260 cat 4 0 

1261 monkey 2 2 

1262 >>> df = df.rename_axis("animal") 

1263 >>> df 

1264 num_legs num_arms 

1265 animal 

1266 dog 4 0 

1267 cat 4 0 

1268 monkey 2 2 

1269 >>> df = df.rename_axis("limbs", axis="columns") 

1270 >>> df 

1271 limbs num_legs num_arms 

1272 animal 

1273 dog 4 0 

1274 cat 4 0 

1275 monkey 2 2 

1276 

1277 **MultiIndex** 

1278 

1279 >>> df.index = pd.MultiIndex.from_product([['mammal'], 

1280 ... ['dog', 'cat', 'monkey']], 

1281 ... names=['type', 'name']) 

1282 >>> df 

1283 limbs num_legs num_arms 

1284 type name 

1285 mammal dog 4 0 

1286 cat 4 0 

1287 monkey 2 2 

1288 

1289 >>> df.rename_axis(index={'type': 'class'}) 

1290 limbs num_legs num_arms 

1291 class name 

1292 mammal dog 4 0 

1293 cat 4 0 

1294 monkey 2 2 

1295 

1296 >>> df.rename_axis(columns=str.upper) 

1297 LIMBS num_legs num_arms 

1298 type name 

1299 mammal dog 4 0 

1300 cat 4 0 

1301 monkey 2 2 

1302 """ 

1303 axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments( 

1304 (), kwargs, sentinel=sentinel 

1305 ) 

1306 copy = kwargs.pop("copy", True) 

1307 inplace = kwargs.pop("inplace", False) 

1308 axis = kwargs.pop("axis", 0) 

1309 if axis is not None: 

1310 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1311 

1312 if kwargs: 

1313 raise TypeError( 

1314 "rename_axis() got an unexpected keyword " 

1315 'argument "{0}"'.format(list(kwargs.keys())[0]) 

1316 ) 

1317 

1318 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace") 

1319 

1320 if mapper is not sentinel: 

1321 # Use v0.23 behavior if a scalar or list 

1322 non_mapper = is_scalar(mapper) or ( 

1323 is_list_like(mapper) and not is_dict_like(mapper) 

1324 ) 

1325 if non_mapper: 

1326 return self._set_axis_name(mapper, axis=axis, inplace=inplace) 

1327 else: 

1328 raise ValueError("Use `.rename` to alter labels " "with a mapper.") 

1329 else: 

1330 # Use new behavior. Means that index and/or columns 

1331 # is specified 

1332 result = self if inplace else self.copy(deep=copy) 

1333 

1334 for axis in range(self._AXIS_LEN): 

1335 v = axes.get(self._AXIS_NAMES[axis]) 

1336 if v is sentinel: 

1337 continue 

1338 non_mapper = is_scalar(v) or (is_list_like(v) and not is_dict_like(v)) 

1339 if non_mapper: 

1340 newnames = v 

1341 else: 

1342 f = com._get_rename_function(v) 

1343 curnames = self._get_axis(axis).names 

1344 newnames = [f(name) for name in curnames] 

1345 result._set_axis_name(newnames, axis=axis, inplace=True) 

1346 if not inplace: 

1347 return result 

1348 

1349 def _set_axis_name(self, name, axis=0, inplace=False): 

1350 """ 

1351 Set the name(s) of the axis. 

1352 

1353 Parameters 

1354 ---------- 

1355 name : str or list of str 

1356 Name(s) to set. 

1357 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

1358 The axis to set the label. The value 0 or 'index' specifies index, 

1359 and the value 1 or 'columns' specifies columns. 

1360 inplace : bool, default False 

1361 If `True`, do operation inplace and return None. 

1362 

1363 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

1364 

1365 Returns 

1366 ------- 

1367 Series, DataFrame, or None 

1368 The same type as the caller or `None` if `inplace` is `True`. 

1369 

1370 See Also 

1371 -------- 

1372 DataFrame.rename : Alter the axis labels of :class:`DataFrame`. 

1373 Series.rename : Alter the index labels or set the index name 

1374 of :class:`Series`. 

1375 Index.rename : Set the name of :class:`Index` or :class:`MultiIndex`. 

1376 

1377 Examples 

1378 -------- 

1379 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"num_legs": [4, 4, 2]}, 

1380 ... ["dog", "cat", "monkey"]) 

1381 >>> df 

1382 num_legs 

1383 dog 4 

1384 cat 4 

1385 monkey 2 

1386 >>> df._set_axis_name("animal") 

1387 num_legs 

1388 animal 

1389 dog 4 

1390 cat 4 

1391 monkey 2 

1392 >>> df.index = pd.MultiIndex.from_product( 

1393 ... [["mammal"], ['dog', 'cat', 'monkey']]) 

1394 >>> df._set_axis_name(["type", "name"]) 

1395 legs 

1396 type name 

1397 mammal dog 4 

1398 cat 4 

1399 monkey 2 

1400 """ 

1401 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1402 idx = self._get_axis(axis).set_names(name) 

1403 

1404 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace") 

1405 renamed = self if inplace else self.copy() 

1406 renamed.set_axis(idx, axis=axis, inplace=True) 

1407 if not inplace: 

1408 return renamed

1410 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

1411 # Comparison Methods 

1412 

1413 def _indexed_same(self, other): 

1414 return all( 

1415 self._get_axis(a).equals(other._get_axis(a)) for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS 

1416 ) 

1417 

1418 def equals(self, other): 

1419 """ 

1420 Test whether two objects contain the same elements. 

1421 

1422 This function allows two Series or DataFrames to be compared against 

1423 each other to see if they have the same shape and elements. NaNs in 

1424 the same location are considered equal. The column headers do not 

1425 need to have the same type, but the elements within the columns must 

1426 be the same dtype. 

1427 

1428 Parameters 

1429 ---------- 

1430 other : Series or DataFrame 

1431 The other Series or DataFrame to be compared with the first. 

1432 

1433 Returns 

1434 ------- 

1435 bool 

1436 True if all elements are the same in both objects, False 

1437 otherwise. 

1438 

1439 See Also 

1440 -------- 

1441 Series.eq : Compare two Series objects of the same length 

1442 and return a Series where each element is True if the element 

1443 in each Series is equal, False otherwise. 

1444 DataFrame.eq : Compare two DataFrame objects of the same shape and 

1445 return a DataFrame where each element is True if the respective 

1446 element in each DataFrame is equal, False otherwise. 

1447 assert_series_equal : Return True if left and right Series are equal, 

1448 False otherwise. 

1449 assert_frame_equal : Return True if left and right DataFrames are 

1450 equal, False otherwise. 

1451 numpy.array_equal : Return True if two arrays have the same shape 

1452 and elements, False otherwise. 

1453 

1454 Notes 

1455 ----- 

1456 This function requires that the elements have the same dtype as their 

1457 respective elements in the other Series or DataFrame. However, the 

1458 column labels do not need to have the same type, as long as they are 

1459 still considered equal. 

1460 

1461 Examples 

1462 -------- 

1463 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({1: [10], 2: [20]}) 

1464 >>> df 

1465 1 2 

1466 0 10 20 

1467 

1468 DataFrames df and exactly_equal have the same types and values for 

1469 their elements and column labels, which will return True. 

1470 

1471 >>> exactly_equal = pd.DataFrame({1: [10], 2: [20]}) 

1472 >>> exactly_equal 

1473 1 2 

1474 0 10 20 

1475 >>> df.equals(exactly_equal) 

1476 True 

1477 

1478 DataFrames df and different_column_type have the same element 

1479 types and values, but have different types for the column labels, 

1480 which will still return True. 

1481 

1482 >>> different_column_type = pd.DataFrame({1.0: [10], 2.0: [20]}) 

1483 >>> different_column_type 

1484 1.0 2.0 

1485 0 10 20 

1486 >>> df.equals(different_column_type) 

1487 True 

1488 

1489 DataFrames df and different_data_type have different types for the 

1490 same values for their elements, and will return False even though 

1491 their column labels are the same values and types. 

1492 

1493 >>> different_data_type = pd.DataFrame({1: [10.0], 2: [20.0]}) 

1494 >>> different_data_type 

1495 1 2 

1496 0 10.0 20.0 

1497 >>> df.equals(different_data_type) 

1498 False 

1499 """ 

1500 if not isinstance(other, self._constructor): 

1501 return False 

1502 return self._data.equals(other._data) 

1503 

1504 # ------------------------------------------------------------------------- 

1505 # Unary Methods 

1506 

1507 def __neg__(self): 

1508 values = com.values_from_object(self) 

1509 if is_bool_dtype(values): 

1510 arr = operator.inv(values) 

1511 elif ( 

1512 is_numeric_dtype(values) 

1513 or is_timedelta64_dtype(values) 

1514 or is_object_dtype(values) 

1515 ): 

1516 arr = operator.neg(values) 

1517 else: 

1518 raise TypeError( 

1519 "Unary negative expects numeric dtype, not {}".format(values.dtype) 

1520 ) 

1521 return self.__array_wrap__(arr) 

1522 

1523 def __pos__(self): 

1524 values = com.values_from_object(self) 

1525 if is_bool_dtype(values) or is_period_arraylike(values): 

1526 arr = values 

1527 elif ( 

1528 is_numeric_dtype(values) 

1529 or is_timedelta64_dtype(values) 

1530 or is_object_dtype(values) 

1531 ): 

1532 arr = operator.pos(values) 

1533 else: 

1534 raise TypeError( 

1535 "Unary plus expects numeric dtype, not {}".format(values.dtype) 

1536 ) 

1537 return self.__array_wrap__(arr) 

1538 

1539 def __invert__(self): 

1540 try: 

1541 arr = operator.inv(com.values_from_object(self)) 

1542 return self.__array_wrap__(arr) 

1543 except Exception: 

1544 

1545 # inv fails with 0 len 

1546 if not np.prod(self.shape): 

1547 return self 

1548 

1549 raise 

1550 

1551 def __nonzero__(self): 

1552 raise ValueError( 

1553 "The truth value of a {0} is ambiguous. " 

1554 "Use a.empty, a.bool(), a.item(), a.any() or a.all().".format( 

1555 self.__class__.__name__ 

1556 ) 

1557 ) 

1558 

1559 __bool__ = __nonzero__ 

1560 

1561 def bool(self): 

1562 """ 

1563 Return the bool of a single element PandasObject. 

1564 

1565 This must be a boolean scalar value, either True or False. Raise a 

1566 ValueError if the PandasObject does not have exactly 1 element, or that 

1567 element is not boolean 

1568 

1569 Returns 

1570 ------- 

1571 bool 

1572 Same single boolean value converted to bool type. 

1573 """ 

1574 v = self.squeeze() 

1575 if isinstance(v, (bool, np.bool_)): 

1576 return bool(v) 

1577 elif is_scalar(v): 

1578 raise ValueError( 

1579 "bool cannot act on a non-boolean single element " 

1580 "{0}".format(self.__class__.__name__) 

1581 ) 

1582 

1583 self.__nonzero__() 

1584 

1585 def __abs__(self): 

1586 return self.abs() 

1587 

1588 def __round__(self, decimals=0): 

1589 return self.round(decimals) 

1590 

1591 # ------------------------------------------------------------------------- 

1592 # Label or Level Combination Helpers 

1593 # 

1594 # A collection of helper methods for DataFrame/Series operations that 

1595 # accept a combination of column/index labels and levels. All such 

1596 # operations should utilize/extend these methods when possible so that we 

1597 # have consistent precedence and validation logic throughout the library. 

1598 

1599 def _is_level_reference(self, key, axis=0): 

1600 """ 

1601 Test whether a key is a level reference for a given axis. 

1602 

1603 To be considered a level reference, `key` must be a string that: 

1604 - (axis=0): Matches the name of an index level and does NOT match 

1605 a column label. 

1606 - (axis=1): Matches the name of a column level and does NOT match 

1607 an index label. 

1608 

1609 Parameters 

1610 ---------- 

1611 key : str 

1612 Potential level name for the given axis 

1613 axis : int, default 0 

1614 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1615 

1616 Returns 

1617 ------- 

1618 is_level : bool 

1619 """ 

1620 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1621 

1622 return ( 

1623 key is not None 

1624 and is_hashable(key) 

1625 and key in self.axes[axis].names 

1626 and not self._is_label_reference(key, axis=axis) 

1627 ) 

1628 

1629 def _is_label_reference(self, key, axis=0): 

1630 """ 

1631 Test whether a key is a label reference for a given axis. 

1632 

1633 To be considered a label reference, `key` must be a string that: 

1634 - (axis=0): Matches a column label 

1635 - (axis=1): Matches an index label 

1636 

1637 Parameters 

1638 ---------- 

1639 key: str 

1640 Potential label name 

1641 axis: int, default 0 

1642 Axis perpendicular to the axis that labels are associated with 

1643 (0 means search for column labels, 1 means search for index labels) 

1644 

1645 Returns 

1646 ------- 

1647 is_label: bool 

1648 """ 

1649 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1650 other_axes = (ax for ax in range(self._AXIS_LEN) if ax != axis) 

1651 

1652 return ( 

1653 key is not None 

1654 and is_hashable(key) 

1655 and any(key in self.axes[ax] for ax in other_axes) 

1656 ) 

1657 

1658 def _is_label_or_level_reference(self, key, axis=0): 

1659 """ 

1660 Test whether a key is a label or level reference for a given axis. 

1661 

1662 To be considered either a label or a level reference, `key` must be a 

1663 string that: 

1664 - (axis=0): Matches a column label or an index level 

1665 - (axis=1): Matches an index label or a column level 

1666 

1667 Parameters 

1668 ---------- 

1669 key: str 

1670 Potential label or level name 

1671 axis: int, default 0 

1672 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1673 

1674 Returns 

1675 ------- 

1676 is_label_or_level: bool 

1677 """ 

1678 return self._is_level_reference(key, axis=axis) or self._is_label_reference( 

1679 key, axis=axis 

1680 ) 

1681 

1682 def _check_label_or_level_ambiguity(self, key, axis=0): 

1683 """ 

1684 Check whether `key` is ambiguous. 

1685 

1686 By ambiguous, we mean that it matches both a level of the input 

1687 `axis` and a label of the other axis. 

1688 

1689 Parameters 

1690 ---------- 

1691 key: str or object 

1692 label or level name 

1693 axis: int, default 0 

1694 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1695 

1696 Raises 

1697 ------ 

1698 ValueError: `key` is ambiguous 

1699 """ 

1700 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1701 other_axes = (ax for ax in range(self._AXIS_LEN) if ax != axis) 

1702 

1703 if ( 

1704 key is not None 

1705 and is_hashable(key) 

1706 and key in self.axes[axis].names 

1707 and any(key in self.axes[ax] for ax in other_axes) 

1708 ): 

1709 

1710 # Build an informative and grammatical warning 

1711 level_article, level_type = ( 

1712 ("an", "index") if axis == 0 else ("a", "column") 

1713 ) 

1714 

1715 label_article, label_type = ( 

1716 ("a", "column") if axis == 0 else ("an", "index") 

1717 ) 

1718 

1719 msg = ( 

1720 "'{key}' is both {level_article} {level_type} level and " 

1721 "{label_article} {label_type} label, which is ambiguous." 

1722 ).format( 

1723 key=key, 

1724 level_article=level_article, 

1725 level_type=level_type, 

1726 label_article=label_article, 

1727 label_type=label_type, 

1728 ) 

1729 raise ValueError(msg) 

1730 

1731 def _get_label_or_level_values(self, key, axis=0): 

1732 """ 

1733 Return a 1-D array of values associated with `key`, a label or level 

1734 from the given `axis`. 

1735 

1736 Retrieval logic: 

1737 - (axis=0): Return column values if `key` matches a column label. 

1738 Otherwise return index level values if `key` matches an index 

1739 level. 

1740 - (axis=1): Return row values if `key` matches an index label. 

1741 Otherwise return column level values if 'key' matches a column 

1742 level 

1743 

1744 Parameters 

1745 ---------- 

1746 key: str 

1747 Label or level name. 

1748 axis: int, default 0 

1749 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1750 

1751 Returns 

1752 ------- 

1753 values: np.ndarray 

1754 

1755 Raises 

1756 ------ 

1757 KeyError 

1758 if `key` matches neither a label nor a level 

1759 ValueError 

1760 if `key` matches multiple labels 

1761 FutureWarning 

1762 if `key` is ambiguous. This will become an ambiguity error in a 

1763 future version 

1764 """ 

1765 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1766 other_axes = [ax for ax in range(self._AXIS_LEN) if ax != axis] 

1767 

1768 if self._is_label_reference(key, axis=axis): 

1769 self._check_label_or_level_ambiguity(key, axis=axis) 

1770 values = self.xs(key, axis=other_axes[0])._values 

1771 elif self._is_level_reference(key, axis=axis): 

1772 values = self.axes[axis].get_level_values(key)._values 

1773 else: 

1774 raise KeyError(key) 

1775 

1776 # Check for duplicates 

1777 if values.ndim > 1: 

1778 

1779 if other_axes and isinstance(self._get_axis(other_axes[0]), MultiIndex): 

1780 multi_message = ( 

1781 "\n" 

1782 "For a multi-index, the label must be a " 

1783 "tuple with elements corresponding to " 

1784 "each level." 

1785 ) 

1786 else: 

1787 multi_message = "" 

1788 

1789 label_axis_name = "column" if axis == 0 else "index" 

1790 raise ValueError( 

1791 ( 

1792 "The {label_axis_name} label '{key}' " 

1793 "is not unique.{multi_message}" 

1794 ).format( 

1795 key=key, 

1796 label_axis_name=label_axis_name, 

1797 multi_message=multi_message, 

1798 ) 

1799 ) 

1800 

1801 return values 

1802 

1803 def _drop_labels_or_levels(self, keys, axis=0): 

1804 """ 

1805 Drop labels and/or levels for the given `axis`. 

1806 

1807 For each key in `keys`: 

1808 - (axis=0): If key matches a column label then drop the column. 

1809 Otherwise if key matches an index level then drop the level. 

1810 - (axis=1): If key matches an index label then drop the row. 

1811 Otherwise if key matches a column level then drop the level. 

1812 

1813 Parameters 

1814 ---------- 

1815 keys: str or list of str 

1816 labels or levels to drop 

1817 axis: int, default 0 

1818 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1819 

1820 Returns 

1821 ------- 

1822 dropped: DataFrame 

1823 

1824 Raises 

1825 ------ 

1826 ValueError 

1827 if any `keys` match neither a label nor a level 

1828 """ 

1829 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1830 

1831 # Validate keys 

1832 keys = com.maybe_make_list(keys) 

1833 invalid_keys = [ 

1834 k for k in keys if not self._is_label_or_level_reference(k, axis=axis) 

1835 ] 

1836 

1837 if invalid_keys: 

1838 raise ValueError( 

1839 ( 

1840 "The following keys are not valid labels or " 

1841 "levels for axis {axis}: {invalid_keys}" 

1842 ).format(axis=axis, invalid_keys=invalid_keys) 

1843 ) 

1844 

1845 # Compute levels and labels to drop 

1846 levels_to_drop = [k for k in keys if self._is_level_reference(k, axis=axis)] 

1847 

1848 labels_to_drop = [k for k in keys if not self._is_level_reference(k, axis=axis)] 

1849 

1850 # Perform copy upfront and then use inplace operations below. 

1851 # This ensures that we always perform exactly one copy. 

1852 # ``copy`` and/or ``inplace`` options could be added in the future. 

1853 dropped = self.copy() 

1854 

1855 if axis == 0: 

1856 # Handle dropping index levels 

1857 if levels_to_drop: 

1858 dropped.reset_index(levels_to_drop, drop=True, inplace=True) 

1859 

1860 # Handle dropping columns labels 

1861 if labels_to_drop: 

1862 dropped.drop(labels_to_drop, axis=1, inplace=True) 

1863 else: 

1864 # Handle dropping column levels 

1865 if levels_to_drop: 

1866 if isinstance(dropped.columns, MultiIndex): 

1867 # Drop the specified levels from the MultiIndex 

1868 dropped.columns = dropped.columns.droplevel(levels_to_drop) 

1869 else: 

1870 # Drop the last level of Index by replacing with 

1871 # a RangeIndex 

1872 dropped.columns = RangeIndex(dropped.columns.size) 

1873 

1874 # Handle dropping index labels 

1875 if labels_to_drop: 

1876 dropped.drop(labels_to_drop, axis=0, inplace=True) 

1877 

1878 return dropped 

1879

1884 raise TypeError(

1914 def items(self): 

1915 """Iterate over (label, values) on info axis

1921 Generator 

1922 """

1937 

1938 @property 

1939 def empty(self): 

1940 """ 

1941 Indicator whether DataFrame is empty. 

1942 

1943 True if DataFrame is entirely empty (no items), meaning any of the 

1944 axes are of length 0. 

1945 

1946 Returns 

1947 ------- 

1948 bool 

1949 If DataFrame is empty, return True, if not return False. 

1950 

1951 See Also 

1952 -------- 

1953 Series.dropna 

1954 DataFrame.dropna 

1955 

1956 Notes 

1957 ----- 

1958 If DataFrame contains only NaNs, it is still not considered empty. See 

1959 the example below. 

1960 

1961 Examples 

1962 -------- 

1963 An example of an actual empty DataFrame. Notice the index is empty: 

1964 

1965 >>> df_empty = pd.DataFrame({'A' : []}) 

1966 >>> df_empty 

1967 Empty DataFrame 

1968 Columns: [A] 

1969 Index: [] 

1970 >>> df_empty.empty 

1971 True 

1972 

1973 If we only have NaNs in our DataFrame, it is not considered empty! We 

1974 will need to drop the NaNs to make the DataFrame empty: 

1975 

1976 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A' : [np.nan]}) 

1977 >>> df 

1978 A 

1979 0 NaN 

1980 >>> df.empty 

1981 False 

1982 >>> df.dropna().empty 

1983 True 

1984 """ 

1985 return any(len(self._get_axis(a)) == 0 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS) 

1986

1995 return com.values_from_object(self) 

1996 

1997 def __array_wrap__(self, result, context=None): 

1998 d = self._construct_axes_dict(self._AXIS_ORDERS, copy=False) 

1999 return self._constructor(result, **d).__finalize__(self) 

2000

2002 # is slower

2005 # """ provide numpy array interface method """ 

2006 # values = self.values 

2007 # return dict(typestr=values.dtype.str,shape=values.shape,data=values)

2010 """ 

2011 Return dense representation of Series/DataFrame (as opposed to sparse). 

2012 

2013 .. deprecated:: 0.25.0 

2014 

2015 Returns 

2016 ------- 

2017 %(klass)s 

2018 Dense %(klass)s. 

2019 """ 

2020 warnings.warn( 

2021 "DataFrame/Series.to_dense is deprecated " 

2022 "and will be removed in a future version", 

2023 FutureWarning, 

2024 stacklevel=2, 

2025 ) 

2026 # compat 

2027 return self

2029 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

2030 # Picklability 

2031 

2032 def __getstate__(self): 

2033 meta = {k: getattr(self, k, None) for k in self._metadata} 

2034 return dict(_data=self._data, _typ=self._typ, _metadata=self._metadata, **meta) 

2035 

2036 def __setstate__(self, state): 

2037 

2038 if isinstance(state, BlockManager): 

2039 self._data = state 

2040 elif isinstance(state, dict): 

2041 typ = state.get("_typ") 

2042 if typ is not None: 

2043 

2044 # set in the order of internal names 

2045 # to avoid definitional recursion 

2046 # e.g. say fill_value needing _data to be 

2047 # defined 

2048 meta = set(self._internal_names + self._metadata) 

2049 for k in list(meta): 

2050 if k in state: 

2051 v = state[k] 

2052 object.__setattr__(self, k, v) 

2053 

2054 for k, v in state.items(): 

2055 if k not in meta: 

2056 object.__setattr__(self, k, v) 

2057 

2058 else: 

2059 self._unpickle_series_compat(state) 

2060 elif isinstance(state[0], dict): 

2061 if len(state) == 5: 

2062 self._unpickle_sparse_frame_compat(state) 

2063 else: 

2064 self._unpickle_frame_compat(state) 

2065 elif len(state) == 4: 

2066 self._unpickle_panel_compat(state) 

2067 elif len(state) == 2: 

2068 self._unpickle_series_compat(state) 

2069 else: # pragma: no cover 

2070 # old pickling format, for compatibility 

2071 self._unpickle_matrix_compat(state) 

2072 

2073 self._item_cache = {} 

2074

2077 

2078 def __repr__(self): 

2079 # string representation based upon iterating over self 

2080 # (since, by definition, `PandasContainers` are iterable) 

2081 prepr = "[%s]" % ",".join(map(pprint_thing, self)) 

2082 return "%s(%s)" % (self.__class__.__name__, prepr)

2085 """ 

2086 Returns a LaTeX representation for a particular object. 

2087 Mainly for use with nbconvert (jupyter notebook conversion to pdf). 

2088 """ 

2089 if config.get_option("display.latex.repr"): 

2090 return self.to_latex() 

2091 else: 

2092 return None

2095 """ 

2096 Not a real Jupyter special repr method, but we use the same 

2097 naming convention. 

2098 """ 

2099 if config.get_option("display.html.table_schema"): 

2100 data = self.head(config.get_option("display.max_rows")) 

2101 payload = json.loads( 

2102 data.to_json(orient="table"), object_pairs_hook=collections.OrderedDict 

2103 ) 

2104 return payload

2107 # I/O Methods 

2108 

2109 _shared_docs[ 

2110 "to_excel" 

2111 ] = """ 

2112 Write %(klass)s to an Excel sheet. 

2113 

2114 To write a single %(klass)s to an Excel .xlsx file it is only necessary to 

2115 specify a target file name. To write to multiple sheets it is necessary to 

2116 create an `ExcelWriter` object with a target file name, and specify a sheet 

2117 in the file to write to. 

2118 

2119 Multiple sheets may be written to by specifying unique `sheet_name`. 

2120 With all data written to the file it is necessary to save the changes. 

2121 Note that creating an `ExcelWriter` object with a file name that already 

2122 exists will result in the contents of the existing file being erased. 

2123 

2124 Parameters 

2125 ---------- 

2126 excel_writer : str or ExcelWriter object 

2127 File path or existing ExcelWriter. 

2128 sheet_name : str, default 'Sheet1' 

2129 Name of sheet which will contain DataFrame. 

2130 na_rep : str, default '' 

2131 Missing data representation. 

2132 float_format : str, optional 

2133 Format string for floating point numbers. For example 

2134 ``float_format="%%.2f"`` will format 0.1234 to 0.12. 

2135 columns : sequence or list of str, optional 

2136 Columns to write. 

2137 header : bool or list of str, default True 

2138 Write out the column names. If a list of string is given it is 

2139 assumed to be aliases for the column names. 

2140 index : bool, default True 

2141 Write row names (index). 

2142 index_label : str or sequence, optional 

2143 Column label for index column(s) if desired. If not specified, and 

2144 `header` and `index` are True, then the index names are used. A 

2145 sequence should be given if the DataFrame uses MultiIndex. 

2146 startrow : int, default 0 

2147 Upper left cell row to dump data frame. 

2148 startcol : int, default 0 

2149 Upper left cell column to dump data frame. 

2150 engine : str, optional 

2151 Write engine to use, 'openpyxl' or 'xlsxwriter'. You can also set this 

2152 via the options ``io.excel.xlsx.writer``, ``io.excel.xls.writer``, and 

2153 ``io.excel.xlsm.writer``. 

2154 merge_cells : bool, default True 

2155 Write MultiIndex and Hierarchical Rows as merged cells. 

2156 encoding : str, optional 

2157 Encoding of the resulting excel file. Only necessary for xlwt, 

2158 other writers support unicode natively. 

2159 inf_rep : str, default 'inf' 

2160 Representation for infinity (there is no native representation for 

2161 infinity in Excel). 

2162 verbose : bool, default True 

2163 Display more information in the error logs. 

2164 freeze_panes : tuple of int (length 2), optional 

2165 Specifies the one-based bottommost row and rightmost column that 

2166 is to be frozen. 

2167 

2168 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0. 

2169 

2170 See Also 

2171 -------- 

2172 to_csv : Write DataFrame to a comma-separated values (csv) file. 

2173 ExcelWriter : Class for writing DataFrame objects into excel sheets. 

2174 read_excel : Read an Excel file into a pandas DataFrame. 

2175 read_csv : Read a comma-separated values (csv) file into DataFrame. 

2176 

2177 Notes 

2178 ----- 

2179 For compatibility with :meth:`~DataFrame.to_csv`, 

2180 to_excel serializes lists and dicts to strings before writing. 

2181 

2182 Once a workbook has been saved it is not possible write further data 

2183 without rewriting the whole workbook. 

2184 

2185 Examples 

2186 -------- 

2187 

2188 Create, write to and save a workbook: 

2189 

2190 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame([['a', 'b'], ['c', 'd']], 

2191 ... index=['row 1', 'row 2'], 

2192 ... columns=['col 1', 'col 2']) 

2193 >>> df1.to_excel("output.xlsx") # doctest: +SKIP 

2194 

2195 To specify the sheet name: 

2196 

2197 >>> df1.to_excel("output.xlsx", 

2198 ... sheet_name='Sheet_name_1') # doctest: +SKIP 

2199 

2200 If you wish to write to more than one sheet in the workbook, it is 

2201 necessary to specify an ExcelWriter object: 

2202 

2203 >>> df2 = df1.copy() 

2204 >>> with pd.ExcelWriter('output.xlsx') as writer: # doctest: +SKIP 

2205 ... df1.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_1') 

2206 ... df2.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_2') 

2207 

2208 To set the library that is used to write the Excel file, 

2209 you can pass the `engine` keyword (the default engine is 

2210 automatically chosen depending on the file extension): 

2211 

2212 >>> df1.to_excel('output1.xlsx', engine='xlsxwriter') # doctest: +SKIP 

2213 """ 

2214 

2215 @Appender(_shared_docs["to_excel"] % dict(klass="object")) 

2216 def to_excel( 

2217 self, 

2218 excel_writer, 

2219 sheet_name="Sheet1", 

2220 na_rep="", 

2221 float_format=None, 

2222 columns=None, 

2223 header=True, 

2224 index=True, 

2225 index_label=None, 

2226 startrow=0, 

2227 startcol=0, 

2228 engine=None, 

2229 merge_cells=True, 

2230 encoding=None, 

2231 inf_rep="inf", 

2232 verbose=True, 

2233 freeze_panes=None, 

2234 ): 

2235 df = self if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame) else self.to_frame() 

2236 

2237 from pandas.io.formats.excel import ExcelFormatter 

2238 

2239 formatter = ExcelFormatter( 

2240 df, 

2241 na_rep=na_rep, 

2242 cols=columns, 

2243 header=header, 

2244 float_format=float_format, 

2245 index=index, 

2246 index_label=index_label, 

2247 merge_cells=merge_cells, 

2248 inf_rep=inf_rep, 

2249 ) 

2250 formatter.write( 

2251 excel_writer, 

2252 sheet_name=sheet_name, 

2253 startrow=startrow, 

2254 startcol=startcol, 

2255 freeze_panes=freeze_panes, 

2256 engine=engine, 

2257 )
