4110 def sort_values( 

4111 self, 

4112 by=None, 

4113 axis=0, 

4114 ascending=True, 

4115 inplace=False, 

4116 kind="quicksort", 

4117 na_position="last", 

4118 ): 

4119 """ 

4120 Sort by the values along either axis. 

4121 

4122 Parameters 

4123 ----------%(optional_by)s 

4124 axis : %(axes_single_arg)s, default 0 

4125 Axis to be sorted. 

4126 ascending : bool or list of bool, default True 

4127 Sort ascending vs. descending. Specify list for multiple sort 

4128 orders. If this is a list of bools, must match the length of 

4129 the by. 

4130 inplace : bool, default False 

4131 If True, perform operation in-place. 

4132 kind : {'quicksort', 'mergesort', 'heapsort'}, default 'quicksort' 

4133 Choice of sorting algorithm. See also ndarray.np.sort for more 

4134 information. `mergesort` is the only stable algorithm. For 

4135 DataFrames, this option is only applied when sorting on a single 

4136 column or label. 

4137 na_position : {'first', 'last'}, default 'last' 

4138 Puts NaNs at the beginning if `first`; `last` puts NaNs at the 

4139 end. 

4140 

4141 Returns 

4142 ------- 

4143 sorted_obj : DataFrame or None 

4144 DataFrame with sorted values if inplace=False, None otherwise. 

4145 

4146 Examples 

4147 -------- 

4148 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({ 

4149 ... 'col1': ['A', 'A', 'B', np.nan, 'D', 'C'], 

4150 ... 'col2': [2, 1, 9, 8, 7, 4], 

4151 ... 'col3': [0, 1, 9, 4, 2, 3], 

4152 ... }) 

4153 >>> df 

4154 col1 col2 col3 

4155 0 A 2 0 

4156 1 A 1 1 

4157 2 B 9 9 

4158 3 NaN 8 4 

4159 4 D 7 2 

4160 5 C 4 3 

4161 

4162 Sort by col1 

4163 

4164 >>> df.sort_values(by=['col1']) 

4165 col1 col2 col3 

4166 0 A 2 0 

4167 1 A 1 1 

4168 2 B 9 9 

4169 5 C 4 3 

4170 4 D 7 2 

4171 3 NaN 8 4 

4172 

4173 Sort by multiple columns 

4174 

4175 >>> df.sort_values(by=['col1', 'col2']) 

4176 col1 col2 col3 

4177 1 A 1 1 

4178 0 A 2 0 

4179 2 B 9 9 

4180 5 C 4 3 

4181 4 D 7 2 

4182 3 NaN 8 4 

4183 

4184 Sort Descending 

4185 

4186 >>> df.sort_values(by='col1', ascending=False) 

4187 col1 col2 col3 

4188 4 D 7 2 

4189 5 C 4 3 

4190 2 B 9 9 

4191 0 A 2 0 

4192 1 A 1 1 

4193 3 NaN 8 4 

4194 

4195 Putting NAs first 

4196 

4197 >>> df.sort_values(by='col1', ascending=False, na_position='first') 

4198 col1 col2 col3 

4199 3 NaN 8 4 

4200 4 D 7 2 

4201 5 C 4 3 

4202 2 B 9 9 

4203 0 A 2 0 

4204 1 A 1 1 

4205 """ 

4206 raise AbstractMethodError(self) 

4207 

4208 def sort_index( 

4209 self, 

4210 axis=0, 

4211 level=None, 

4212 ascending=True, 

4213 inplace=False, 

4214 kind="quicksort", 

4215 na_position="last", 

4216 sort_remaining=True, 

4217 ): 

4218 """ 

4219 Sort object by labels (along an axis). 

4220 

4221 Parameters 

4222 ---------- 

4223 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

4224 The axis along which to sort. The value 0 identifies the rows, 

4225 and 1 identifies the columns. 

4226 level : int or level name or list of ints or list of level names 

4227 If not None, sort on values in specified index level(s). 

4228 ascending : bool, default True 

4229 Sort ascending vs. descending. 

4230 inplace : bool, default False 

4231 If True, perform operation in-place. 

4232 kind : {'quicksort', 'mergesort', 'heapsort'}, default 'quicksort' 

4233 Choice of sorting algorithm. See also ndarray.np.sort for more 

4234 information. `mergesort` is the only stable algorithm. For 

4235 DataFrames, this option is only applied when sorting on a single 

4236 column or label. 

4237 na_position : {'first', 'last'}, default 'last' 

4238 Puts NaNs at the beginning if `first`; `last` puts NaNs at the end. 

4239 Not implemented for MultiIndex. 

4240 sort_remaining : bool, default True 

4241 If True and sorting by level and index is multilevel, sort by other 

4242 levels too (in order) after sorting by specified level. 

4243 

4244 Returns 

4245 ------- 

4246 sorted_obj : DataFrame or None 

4247 DataFrame with sorted index if inplace=False, None otherwise. 

4248 """ 

4249 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace") 

4250 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

4251 axis_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

4252 labels = self._get_axis(axis) 

4253 

4254 if level is not None: 

4255 raise NotImplementedError("level is not implemented") 

4256 if inplace: 

4257 raise NotImplementedError("inplace is not implemented") 

4258 

4259 sort_index = labels.argsort() 

4260 if not ascending: 

4261 sort_index = sort_index[::-1] 

4262 

4263 new_axis = labels.take(sort_index) 

4264 return self.reindex(**{axis_name: new_axis}) 

4265 

4266 def reindex(self, *args, **kwargs): 

4267 """ 

4268 Conform %(klass)s to new index with optional filling logic, placing 

4269 NA/NaN in locations having no value in the previous index. A new object 

4270 is produced unless the new index is equivalent to the current one and 

4271 ``copy=False``. 

4272 

4273 Parameters 

4274 ---------- 

4275 %(optional_labels)s 

4276 %(axes)s : array-like, optional 

4277 New labels / index to conform to, should be specified using 

4278 keywords. Preferably an Index object to avoid duplicating data 

4279 %(optional_axis)s 

4280 method : {None, 'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill', 'nearest'} 

4281 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed DataFrame. 

4282 Please note: this is only applicable to DataFrames/Series with a 

4283 monotonically increasing/decreasing index. 

4284 

4285 * None (default): don't fill gaps 

4286 * pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next 

4287 valid 

4288 * backfill / bfill: use next valid observation to fill gap 

4289 * nearest: use nearest valid observations to fill gap 

4290 

4291 copy : bool, default True 

4292 Return a new object, even if the passed indexes are the same. 

4293 level : int or name 

4294 Broadcast across a level, matching Index values on the 

4295 passed MultiIndex level. 

4296 fill_value : scalar, default np.NaN 

4297 Value to use for missing values. Defaults to NaN, but can be any 

4298 "compatible" value. 

4299 limit : int, default None 

4300 Maximum number of consecutive elements to forward or backward fill. 

4301 tolerance : optional 

4302 Maximum distance between original and new labels for inexact 

4303 matches. The values of the index at the matching locations most 

4304 satisfy the equation ``abs(index[indexer] - target) <= tolerance``. 

4305 

4306 Tolerance may be a scalar value, which applies the same tolerance 

4307 to all values, or list-like, which applies variable tolerance per 

4308 element. List-like includes list, tuple, array, Series, and must be 

4309 the same size as the index and its dtype must exactly match the 

4310 index's type. 

4311 

4312 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 (list-like tolerance) 

4313 

4314 Returns 

4315 ------- 

4316 %(klass)s with changed index. 

4317 

4318 See Also 

4319 -------- 

4320 DataFrame.set_index : Set row labels. 

4321 DataFrame.reset_index : Remove row labels or move them to new columns. 

4322 DataFrame.reindex_like : Change to same indices as other DataFrame. 

4323 

4324 Examples 

4325 -------- 

4326 

4327 ``DataFrame.reindex`` supports two calling conventions 

4328 

4329 * ``(index=index_labels, columns=column_labels, ...)`` 

4330 * ``(labels, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)`` 

4331 

4332 We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your 

4333 intent. 

4334 

4335 Create a dataframe with some fictional data. 

4336 

4337 >>> index = ['Firefox', 'Chrome', 'Safari', 'IE10', 'Konqueror'] 

4338 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({ 

4339 ... 'http_status': [200,200,404,404,301], 

4340 ... 'response_time': [0.04, 0.02, 0.07, 0.08, 1.0]}, 

4341 ... index=index) 

4342 >>> df 

4343 http_status response_time 

4344 Firefox 200 0.04 

4345 Chrome 200 0.02 

4346 Safari 404 0.07 

4347 IE10 404 0.08 

4348 Konqueror 301 1.00 

4349 

4350 Create a new index and reindex the dataframe. By default 

4351 values in the new index that do not have corresponding 

4352 records in the dataframe are assigned ``NaN``. 

4353 

4354 >>> new_index= ['Safari', 'Iceweasel', 'Comodo Dragon', 'IE10', 

4355 ... 'Chrome'] 

4356 >>> df.reindex(new_index) 

4357 http_status response_time 

4358 Safari 404.0 0.07 

4359 Iceweasel NaN NaN 

4360 Comodo Dragon NaN NaN 

4361 IE10 404.0 0.08 

4362 Chrome 200.0 0.02 

4363 

4364 We can fill in the missing values by passing a value to 

4365 the keyword ``fill_value``. Because the index is not monotonically 

4366 increasing or decreasing, we cannot use arguments to the keyword 

4367 ``method`` to fill the ``NaN`` values. 

4368 

4369 >>> df.reindex(new_index, fill_value=0) 

4370 http_status response_time 

4371 Safari 404 0.07 

4372 Iceweasel 0 0.00 

4373 Comodo Dragon 0 0.00 

4374 IE10 404 0.08 

4375 Chrome 200 0.02 

4376 

4377 >>> df.reindex(new_index, fill_value='missing') 

4378 http_status response_time 

4379 Safari 404 0.07 

4380 Iceweasel missing missing 

4381 Comodo Dragon missing missing 

4382 IE10 404 0.08 

4383 Chrome 200 0.02 

4384 

4385 We can also reindex the columns. 

4386 

4387 >>> df.reindex(columns=['http_status', 'user_agent']) 

4388 http_status user_agent 

4389 Firefox 200 NaN 

4390 Chrome 200 NaN 

4391 Safari 404 NaN 

4392 IE10 404 NaN 

4393 Konqueror 301 NaN 

4394 

4395 Or we can use "axis-style" keyword arguments 

4396 

4397 >>> df.reindex(['http_status', 'user_agent'], axis="columns") 

4398 http_status user_agent 

4399 Firefox 200 NaN 

4400 Chrome 200 NaN 

4401 Safari 404 NaN 

4402 IE10 404 NaN 

4403 Konqueror 301 NaN 

4404 

4405 To further illustrate the filling functionality in 

4406 ``reindex``, we will create a dataframe with a 

4407 monotonically increasing index (for example, a sequence 

4408 of dates). 

4409 

4410 >>> date_index = pd.date_range('1/1/2010', periods=6, freq='D') 

4411 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({"prices": [100, 101, np.nan, 100, 89, 88]}, 

4412 ... index=date_index) 

4413 >>> df2 

4414 prices 

4415 2010-01-01 100.0 

4416 2010-01-02 101.0 

4417 2010-01-03 NaN 

4418 2010-01-04 100.0 

4419 2010-01-05 89.0 

4420 2010-01-06 88.0 

4421 

4422 Suppose we decide to expand the dataframe to cover a wider 

4423 date range. 

4424 

4425 >>> date_index2 = pd.date_range('12/29/2009', periods=10, freq='D') 

4426 >>> df2.reindex(date_index2) 

4427 prices 

4428 2009-12-29 NaN 

4429 2009-12-30 NaN 

4430 2009-12-31 NaN 

4431 2010-01-01 100.0 

4432 2010-01-02 101.0 

4433 2010-01-03 NaN 

4434 2010-01-04 100.0 

4435 2010-01-05 89.0 

4436 2010-01-06 88.0 

4437 2010-01-07 NaN 

4438 

4439 The index entries that did not have a value in the original data frame 

4440 (for example, '2009-12-29') are by default filled with ``NaN``. 

4441 If desired, we can fill in the missing values using one of several 

4442 options. 

4443 

4444 For example, to back-propagate the last valid value to fill the ``NaN`` 

4445 values, pass ``bfill`` as an argument to the ``method`` keyword. 

4446 

4447 >>> df2.reindex(date_index2, method='bfill') 

4448 prices 

4449 2009-12-29 100.0 

4450 2009-12-30 100.0 

4451 2009-12-31 100.0 

4452 2010-01-01 100.0 

4453 2010-01-02 101.0 

4454 2010-01-03 NaN 

4455 2010-01-04 100.0 

4456 2010-01-05 89.0 

4457 2010-01-06 88.0 

4458 2010-01-07 NaN 

4459 

4460 Please note that the ``NaN`` value present in the original dataframe 

4461 (at index value 2010-01-03) will not be filled by any of the 

4462 value propagation schemes. This is because filling while reindexing 

4463 does not look at dataframe values, but only compares the original and 

4464 desired indexes. If you do want to fill in the ``NaN`` values present 

4465 in the original dataframe, use the ``fillna()`` method. 

4466 

4467 See the :ref:`user guide <basics.reindexing>` for more. 

4468 """ 

4469 # TODO: Decide if we care about having different examples for different 

4470 # kinds 

4471 

4472 # construct the args 

4473 axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments(args, kwargs) 

4474 method = missing.clean_reindex_fill_method(kwargs.pop("method", None)) 

4475 level = kwargs.pop("level", None) 

4476 copy = kwargs.pop("copy", True) 

4477 limit = kwargs.pop("limit", None) 

4478 tolerance = kwargs.pop("tolerance", None) 

4479 fill_value = kwargs.pop("fill_value", None) 

4480 

4481 # Series.reindex doesn't use / need the axis kwarg 

4482 # We pop and ignore it here, to make writing Series/Frame generic code 

4483 # easier 

4484 kwargs.pop("axis", None) 

4485 

4486 if kwargs: 

4487 raise TypeError( 

4488 "reindex() got an unexpected keyword " 

4489 'argument "{0}"'.format(list(kwargs.keys())[0]) 

4490 ) 

4491 

4492 self._consolidate_inplace() 

4493 

4494 # if all axes that are requested to reindex are equal, then only copy 

4495 # if indicated must have index names equal here as well as values 

4496 if all( 

4497 self._get_axis(axis).identical(ax) 

4498 for axis, ax in axes.items() 

4499 if ax is not None 

4500 ): 

4501 if copy: 

4502 return self.copy() 

4503 return self 

4504 

4505 # check if we are a multi reindex 

4506 if self._needs_reindex_multi(axes, method, level): 

4507 try: 

4508 return self._reindex_multi(axes, copy, fill_value) 

4509 except Exception: 

4510 pass 

4511 

4512 # perform the reindex on the axes 

4513 return self._reindex_axes( 

4514 axes, level, limit, tolerance, method, fill_value, copy 

4515 ).__finalize__(self) 

4516 

4517 def _reindex_axes(self, axes, level, limit, tolerance, method, fill_value, copy): 

4518 """Perform the reindex for all the axes.""" 

4519 obj = self 

4520 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS: 

4521 labels = axes[a] 

4522 if labels is None: 

4523 continue 

4524 

4525 ax = self._get_axis(a) 

4526 new_index, indexer = ax.reindex( 

4527 labels, level=level, limit=limit, tolerance=tolerance, method=method 

4528 ) 

4529 

4530 axis = self._get_axis_number(a) 

4531 obj = obj._reindex_with_indexers( 

4532 {axis: [new_index, indexer]}, 

4533 fill_value=fill_value, 

4534 copy=copy, 

4535 allow_dups=False, 

4536 ) 

4537 

4538 return obj 

4539 

4540 def _needs_reindex_multi(self, axes, method, level): 

4541 """Check if we do need a multi reindex.""" 

4542 return ( 

4543 (com.count_not_none(*axes.values()) == self._AXIS_LEN) 

4544 and method is None 

4545 and level is None 

4546 and not self._is_mixed_type 

4547 ) 

4548 

4549 def _reindex_multi(self, axes, copy, fill_value): 

4550 return NotImplemented 

4551 

4552 def _reindex_with_indexers( 

4553 self, reindexers, fill_value=None, copy=False, allow_dups=False 

4554 ): 

4555 """allow_dups indicates an internal call here """ 

4556 

4557 # reindex doing multiple operations on different axes if indicated 

4558 new_data = self._data 

4559 for axis in sorted(reindexers.keys()): 

4560 index, indexer = reindexers[axis] 

4561 baxis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

4562 

4563 if index is None: 

4564 continue 

4565 

4566 index = ensure_index(index) 

4567 if indexer is not None: 

4568 indexer = ensure_int64(indexer) 

4569 

4570 # TODO: speed up on homogeneous DataFrame objects 

4571 new_data = new_data.reindex_indexer( 

4572 index, 

4573 indexer, 

4574 axis=baxis, 

4575 fill_value=fill_value, 

4576 allow_dups=allow_dups, 

4577 copy=copy, 

4578 ) 

4579 

4580 if copy and new_data is self._data: 

4581 new_data = new_data.copy() 

4582 

4583 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self) 

4584 

4585 def filter(self, items=None, like=None, regex=None, axis=None): 

4586 """ 

4587 Subset rows or columns of dataframe according to labels in 

4588 the specified index. 

4589 

4590 Note that this routine does not filter a dataframe on its 

4591 contents. The filter is applied to the labels of the index. 

4592 

4593 Parameters 

4594 ---------- 

4595 items : list-like 

4596 Keep labels from axis which are in items. 

4597 like : string 

4598 Keep labels from axis for which "like in label == True". 

4599 regex : string (regular expression) 

4600 Keep labels from axis for which re.search(regex, label) == True. 

4601 axis : int or string axis name 

4602 The axis to filter on. By default this is the info axis, 

4603 'index' for Series, 'columns' for DataFrame. 

4604 

4605 Returns 

4606 ------- 

4607 same type as input object 

4608 

4609 See Also 

4610 -------- 

4611 DataFrame.loc 

4612 

4613 Notes 

4614 ----- 

4615 The ``items``, ``like``, and ``regex`` parameters are 

4616 enforced to be mutually exclusive. 

4617 

4618 ``axis`` defaults to the info axis that is used when indexing 

4619 with ``[]``. 

4620 

4621 Examples 

4622 -------- 

4623 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(np.array(([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6])), 

4624 ... index=['mouse', 'rabbit'], 

4625 ... columns=['one', 'two', 'three']) 

4626 

4627 >>> # select columns by name 

4628 >>> df.filter(items=['one', 'three']) 

4629 one three 

4630 mouse 1 3 

4631 rabbit 4 6 

4632 

4633 >>> # select columns by regular expression 

4634 >>> df.filter(regex='e$', axis=1) 

4635 one three 

4636 mouse 1 3 

4637 rabbit 4 6 

4638 

4639 >>> # select rows containing 'bbi' 

4640 >>> df.filter(like='bbi', axis=0) 

4641 one two three 

4642 rabbit 4 5 6 

4643 """ 

4644 import re 

4645 

4646 nkw = com.count_not_none(items, like, regex) 

4647 if nkw > 1: 

4648 raise TypeError( 

4649 "Keyword arguments `items`, `like`, or `regex` " 

4650 "are mutually exclusive" 

4651 ) 

4652 

4653 if axis is None: 

4654 axis = self._info_axis_name 

4655 labels = self._get_axis(axis) 

4656 

4657 if items is not None: 

4658 name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

4659 return self.reindex(**{name: [r for r in items if r in labels]}) 

4660 elif like: 

4661 

4662 def f(x): 

4663 return like in ensure_str(x) 

4664 

4665 values = labels.map(f) 

4666 return self.loc(axis=axis)[values] 

4667 elif regex: 

4668 

4669 def f(x): 

4670 return matcher.search(ensure_str(x)) is not None 

4671 

4672 matcher = re.compile(regex) 

4673 values = labels.map(f) 

4674 return self.loc(axis=axis)[values] 

4675 else: 

4676 raise TypeError("Must pass either `items`, `like`, or `regex`") 

4677 

4678 def head(self, n=5): 

4679 """ 

4680 Return the first `n` rows. 

4681 

4682 This function returns the first `n` rows for the object based 

4683 on position. It is useful for quickly testing if your object 

4684 has the right type of data in it. 

4685 

4686 Parameters 

4687 ---------- 

4688 n : int, default 5 

4689 Number of rows to select. 

4690 

4691 Returns 

4692 ------- 

4693 obj_head : same type as caller 

4694 The first `n` rows of the caller object. 

4695 

4696 See Also 

4697 -------- 

4698 DataFrame.tail: Returns the last `n` rows. 

4699 

4700 Examples 

4701 -------- 

4702 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'animal':['alligator', 'bee', 'falcon', 'lion', 

4703 ... 'monkey', 'parrot', 'shark', 'whale', 'zebra']}) 

4704 >>> df 

4705 animal 

4706 0 alligator 

4707 1 bee 

4708 2 falcon 

4709 3 lion 

4710 4 monkey 

4711 5 parrot 

4712 6 shark 

4713 7 whale 

4714 8 zebra 

4715 

4716 Viewing the first 5 lines 

4717 

4718 >>> df.head() 

4719 animal 

4720 0 alligator 

4721 1 bee 

4722 2 falcon 

4723 3 lion 

4724 4 monkey 

4725 

4726 Viewing the first `n` lines (three in this case) 

4727 

4728 >>> df.head(3) 

4729 animal 

4730 0 alligator 

4731 1 bee 

4732 2 falcon 

4733 """ 

4734 

4735 return self.iloc[:n] 

4736 

4737 def tail(self, n=5): 

4738 """ 

4739 Return the last `n` rows. 

4740 

4741 This function returns last `n` rows from the object based on 

4742 position. It is useful for quickly verifying data, for example, 

4743 after sorting or appending rows. 

4744 

4745 Parameters 

4746 ---------- 

4747 n : int, default 5 

4748 Number of rows to select. 

4749 

4750 Returns 

4751 ------- 

4752 type of caller 

4753 The last `n` rows of the caller object. 

4754 

4755 See Also 

4756 -------- 

4757 DataFrame.head : The first `n` rows of the caller object. 

4758 

4759 Examples 

4760 -------- 

4761 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'animal':['alligator', 'bee', 'falcon', 'lion', 

4762 ... 'monkey', 'parrot', 'shark', 'whale', 'zebra']}) 

4763 >>> df 

4764 animal 

4765 0 alligator 

4766 1 bee 

4767 2 falcon 

4768 3 lion 

4769 4 monkey 

4770 5 parrot 

4771 6 shark 

4772 7 whale 

4773 8 zebra 

4774 

4775 Viewing the last 5 lines 

4776 

4777 >>> df.tail() 

4778 animal 

4779 4 monkey 

4780 5 parrot 

4781 6 shark 

4782 7 whale 

4783 8 zebra 

4784 

4785 Viewing the last `n` lines (three in this case) 

4786 

4787 >>> df.tail(3) 

4788 animal 

4789 6 shark 

4790 7 whale 

4791 8 zebra 

4792 """ 

4793 

4794 if n == 0: 

4795 return self.iloc[0:0] 

4796 return self.iloc[-n:] 

4797 

4798 def sample( 

4799 self, 

4800 n=None, 

4801 frac=None, 

4802 replace=False, 

4803 weights=None, 

4804 random_state=None, 

4805 axis=None, 

4806 ): 

4807 """ 

4808 Return a random sample of items from an axis of object. 

4809 

4810 You can use `random_state` for reproducibility. 

4811 

4812 Parameters 

4813 ---------- 

4814 n : int, optional 

4815 Number of items from axis to return. Cannot be used with `frac`. 

4816 Default = 1 if `frac` = None. 

4817 frac : float, optional 

4818 Fraction of axis items to return. Cannot be used with `n`. 

4819 replace : bool, default False 

4820 Sample with or without replacement. 

4821 weights : str or ndarray-like, optional 

4822 Default 'None' results in equal probability weighting. 

4823 If passed a Series, will align with target object on index. Index 

4824 values in weights not found in sampled object will be ignored and 

4825 index values in sampled object not in weights will be assigned 

4826 weights of zero. 

4827 If called on a DataFrame, will accept the name of a column 

4828 when axis = 0. 

4829 Unless weights are a Series, weights must be same length as axis 

4830 being sampled. 

4831 If weights do not sum to 1, they will be normalized to sum to 1. 

4832 Missing values in the weights column will be treated as zero. 

4833 Infinite values not allowed. 

4834 random_state : int or numpy.random.RandomState, optional 

4835 Seed for the random number generator (if int), or numpy RandomState 

4836 object. 

4837 axis : int or string, optional 

4838 Axis to sample. Accepts axis number or name. Default is stat axis 

4839 for given data type (0 for Series and DataFrames). 

4840 

4841 Returns 

4842 ------- 

4843 Series or DataFrame 

4844 A new object of same type as caller containing `n` items randomly 

4845 sampled from the caller object. 

4846 

4847 See Also 

4848 -------- 

4849 numpy.random.choice: Generates a random sample from a given 1-D numpy 

4850 array. 

4851 

4852 Examples 

4853 -------- 

4854 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'num_legs': [2, 4, 8, 0], 

4855 ... 'num_wings': [2, 0, 0, 0], 

4856 ... 'num_specimen_seen': [10, 2, 1, 8]}, 

4857 ... index=['falcon', 'dog', 'spider', 'fish']) 

4858 >>> df 

4859 num_legs num_wings num_specimen_seen 

4860 falcon 2 2 10 

4861 dog 4 0 2 

4862 spider 8 0 1 

4863 fish 0 0 8 

4864 

4865 Extract 3 random elements from the ``Series`` ``df['num_legs']``: 

4866 Note that we use `random_state` to ensure the reproducibility of 

4867 the examples. 

4868 

4869 >>> df['num_legs'].sample(n=3, random_state=1) 

4870 fish 0 

4871 spider 8 

4872 falcon 2 

4873 Name: num_legs, dtype: int64 

4874 

4875 A random 50% sample of the ``DataFrame`` with replacement: 

4876 

4877 >>> df.sample(frac=0.5, replace=True, random_state=1) 

4878 num_legs num_wings num_specimen_seen 

4879 dog 4 0 2 

4880 fish 0 0 8 

4881 

4882 Using a DataFrame column as weights. Rows with larger value in the 

4883 `num_specimen_seen` column are more likely to be sampled. 

4884 

4885 >>> df.sample(n=2, weights='num_specimen_seen', random_state=1) 

4886 num_legs num_wings num_specimen_seen 

4887 falcon 2 2 10 

4888 fish 0 0 8 

4889 """ 

4890 

4891 if axis is None: 

4892 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

4893 

4894 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

4895 axis_length = self.shape[axis] 

4896 

4897 # Process random_state argument 

4898 rs = com.random_state(random_state) 

4899 

4900 # Check weights for compliance 

4901 if weights is not None: 

4902 

4903 # If a series, align with frame 

4904 if isinstance(weights, pd.Series): 

4905 weights = weights.reindex(self.axes[axis]) 

4906 

4907 # Strings acceptable if a dataframe and axis = 0 

4908 if isinstance(weights, str): 

4909 if isinstance(self, pd.DataFrame): 

4910 if axis == 0: 

4911 try: 

4912 weights = self[weights] 

4913 except KeyError: 

4914 raise KeyError( 

4915 "String passed to weights not a " "valid column" 

4916 ) 

4917 else: 

4918 raise ValueError( 

4919 "Strings can only be passed to " 

4920 "weights when sampling from rows on " 

4921 "a DataFrame" 

4922 ) 

4923 else: 

4924 raise ValueError( 

4925 "Strings cannot be passed as weights " 

4926 "when sampling from a Series." 

4927 ) 

4928 

4929 weights = pd.Series(weights, dtype="float64") 

4930 

4931 if len(weights) != axis_length: 

4932 raise ValueError( 

4933 "Weights and axis to be sampled must be of " "same length" 

4934 ) 

4935 

4936 if (weights == np.inf).any() or (weights == -np.inf).any(): 

4937 raise ValueError("weight vector may not include `inf` values") 

4938 

4939 if (weights < 0).any(): 

4940 raise ValueError("weight vector many not include negative " "values") 

4941 

4942 # If has nan, set to zero. 

4943 weights = weights.fillna(0) 

4944 

4945 # Renormalize if don't sum to 1 

4946 if weights.sum() != 1: 

4947 if weights.sum() != 0: 

4948 weights = weights / weights.sum() 

4949 else: 

4950 raise ValueError("Invalid weights: weights sum to zero") 

4951 

4952 weights = weights.values 

4953 

4954 # If no frac or n, default to n=1. 

4955 if n is None and frac is None: 

4956 n = 1 

4957 elif n is not None and frac is None and n % 1 != 0: 

4958 raise ValueError("Only integers accepted as `n` values") 

4959 elif n is None and frac is not None: 

4960 n = int(round(frac * axis_length)) 

4961 elif n is not None and frac is not None: 

4962 raise ValueError("Please enter a value for `frac` OR `n`, not " "both") 

4963 

4964 # Check for negative sizes 

4965 if n < 0: 

4966 raise ValueError( 

4967 "A negative number of rows requested. Please " "provide positive value." 

4968 ) 

4969 

4970 locs = rs.choice(axis_length, size=n, replace=replace, p=weights) 

4971 return self.take(locs, axis=axis, is_copy=False) 

4972

4976 Apply func(self, \*args, \*\*kwargs). 

4977 

4978 Parameters 

4979 ---------- 

4980 func : function 

4981 function to apply to the %(klass)s. 

4982 ``args``, and ``kwargs`` are passed into ``func``. 

4983 Alternatively a ``(callable, data_keyword)`` tuple where 

4984 ``data_keyword`` is a string indicating the keyword of 

4985 ``callable`` that expects the %(klass)s. 

4986 args : iterable, optional 

4987 positional arguments passed into ``func``. 

4988 kwargs : mapping, optional 

4989 a dictionary of keyword arguments passed into ``func``. 

4990 

4991 Returns 

4992 ------- 

4993 object : the return type of ``func``. 

4994 

4995 See Also 

4996 -------- 

4997 DataFrame.apply 

4998 DataFrame.applymap 

4999 Series.map 

5000 

5001 Notes 

5002 ----- 

5003 

5004 Use ``.pipe`` when chaining together functions that expect 

5005 Series, DataFrames or GroupBy objects. Instead of writing 

5006 

5007 >>> f(g(h(df), arg1=a), arg2=b, arg3=c) 

5008 

5009 You can write 

5010 

5011 >>> (df.pipe(h) 

5012 ... .pipe(g, arg1=a) 

5013 ... .pipe(f, arg2=b, arg3=c) 

5014 ... ) 

5015 

5016 If you have a function that takes the data as (say) the second 

5017 argument, pass a tuple indicating which keyword expects the 

5018 data. For example, suppose ``f`` takes its data as ``arg2``: 

5019 

5020 >>> (df.pipe(h) 

5021 ... .pipe(g, arg1=a) 

5022 ... .pipe((f, 'arg2'), arg1=a, arg3=c) 

5023 ... ) 

5024 """ 

5025 

5026 @Appender(_shared_docs["pipe"] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

5027 def pipe(self, func, *args, **kwargs):

5142 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

5143 # Attribute access 

5144 

5145 def __finalize__(self, other, method=None, **kwargs): 

5146 """ 

5147 Propagate metadata from other to self. 

5148 

5149 Parameters 

5150 ---------- 

5151 other : the object from which to get the attributes that we are going 

5152 to propagate 

5153 method : optional, a passed method name ; possibly to take different 

5154 types of propagation actions based on this 

5155 

5156 """ 

5157 if isinstance(other, NDFrame): 

5158 for name in self._metadata: 

5159 object.__setattr__(self, name, getattr(other, name, None)) 

5160 return self 

5161 

5162 def __getattr__(self, name): 

5163 """After regular attribute access, try looking up the name 

5164 This allows simpler access to columns for interactive use. 

5165 """ 

5166 

5167 # Note: obj.x will always call obj.__getattribute__('x') prior to 

5168 # calling obj.__getattr__('x'). 

5169 

5170 if ( 

5171 name in self._internal_names_set 

5172 or name in self._metadata 

5173 or name in self._accessors 

5174 ): 

5175 return object.__getattribute__(self, name) 

5176 else: 

5177 if self._info_axis._can_hold_identifiers_and_holds_name(name): 

5178 return self[name] 

5179 return object.__getattribute__(self, name) 

5180 

5181 def __setattr__(self, name, value): 

5182 """After regular attribute access, try setting the name 

5183 This allows simpler access to columns for interactive use. 

5184 """ 

5185 

5186 # first try regular attribute access via __getattribute__, so that 

5187 # e.g. ``obj.x`` and ``obj.x = 4`` will always reference/modify 

5188 # the same attribute. 

5189 

5190 try: 

5191 object.__getattribute__(self, name) 

5192 return object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5193 except AttributeError: 

5194 pass 

5195 

5196 # if this fails, go on to more involved attribute setting 

5197 # (note that this matches __getattr__, above). 

5198 if name in self._internal_names_set: 

5199 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5200 elif name in self._metadata: 

5201 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5202 else: 

5203 try: 

5204 existing = getattr(self, name) 

5205 if isinstance(existing, Index): 

5206 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5207 elif name in self._info_axis: 

5208 self[name] = value 

5209 else: 

5210 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5211 except (AttributeError, TypeError): 

5212 if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame) and (is_list_like(value)): 

5213 warnings.warn( 

5214 "Pandas doesn't allow columns to be " 

5215 "created via a new attribute name - see " 

5216 "https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/" 

5217 "stable/indexing.html#attribute-access", 

5218 stacklevel=2, 

5219 ) 

5220 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5221 

5222 def _dir_additions(self): 

5223 """ add the string-like attributes from the info_axis. 

5224 If info_axis is a MultiIndex, it's first level values are used. 

5225 """ 

5226 additions = { 

5227 c 

5228 for c in self._info_axis.unique(level=0)[:100] 

5229 if isinstance(c, str) and c.isidentifier() 

5230 } 

5231 return super()._dir_additions().union(additions) 

5232 

5233 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

5234 # Consolidation of internals 

5235 

5236 def _protect_consolidate(self, f): 

5237 """Consolidate _data -- if the blocks have changed, then clear the 

5238 cache 

5239 """ 

5240 blocks_before = len(self._data.blocks) 

5241 result = f() 

5242 if len(self._data.blocks) != blocks_before: 

5243 self._clear_item_cache() 

5244 return result 

5245 

5246 def _consolidate_inplace(self): 

5247 """Consolidate data in place and return None""" 

5248 

5249 def f(): 

5250 self._data = self._data.consolidate() 

5251 

5252 self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5253 

5254 def _consolidate(self, inplace=False): 

5255 """ 

5256 Compute NDFrame with "consolidated" internals (data of each dtype 

5257 grouped together in a single ndarray). 

5258 

5259 Parameters 

5260 ---------- 

5261 inplace : boolean, default False 

5262 If False return new object, otherwise modify existing object 

5263 

5264 Returns 

5265 ------- 

5266 consolidated : same type as caller 

5267 """ 

5268 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace") 

5269 if inplace: 

5270 self._consolidate_inplace() 

5271 else: 

5272 f = lambda: self._data.consolidate() 

5273 cons_data = self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5274 return self._constructor(cons_data).__finalize__(self) 

5275 

5276 @property 

5277 def _is_mixed_type(self): 

5278 f = lambda: self._data.is_mixed_type 

5279 return self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5280 

5281 @property 

5282 def _is_numeric_mixed_type(self): 

5283 f = lambda: self._data.is_numeric_mixed_type 

5284 return self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5285 

5286 @property 

5287 def _is_datelike_mixed_type(self): 

5288 f = lambda: self._data.is_datelike_mixed_type 

5289 return self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5290 

5291 def _check_inplace_setting(self, value): 

5292 """ check whether we allow in-place setting with this type of value """ 

5293 

5294 if self._is_mixed_type: 

5295 if not self._is_numeric_mixed_type: 

5296 

5297 # allow an actual np.nan thru 

5298 try: 

5299 if np.isnan(value): 

5300 return True 

5301 except Exception: 

5302 pass 

5303 

5304 raise TypeError( 

5305 "Cannot do inplace boolean setting on " 

5306 "mixed-types with a non np.nan value" 

5307 ) 

5308 

5309 return True 

5310 

5311 def _get_numeric_data(self): 

5312 return self._constructor(self._data.get_numeric_data()).__finalize__(self) 

5313 

5314 def _get_bool_data(self): 

5315 return self._constructor(self._data.get_bool_data()).__finalize__(self)

5319 

5320 def as_matrix(self, columns=None): 

5321 """ 

5322 Convert the frame to its Numpy-array representation. 

5323 

5324 .. deprecated:: 0.23.0 

5325 Use :meth:`DataFrame.values` instead. 

5326 

5327 Parameters 

5328 ---------- 

5329 columns : list, optional, default:None 

5330 If None, return all columns, otherwise, returns specified columns. 

5331 

5332 Returns 

5333 ------- 

5334 values : ndarray 

5335 If the caller is heterogeneous and contains booleans or objects, 

5336 the result will be of dtype=object. See Notes. 

5337 

5338 See Also 

5339 -------- 

5340 DataFrame.values 

5341 

5342 Notes 

5343 ----- 

5344 Return is NOT a Numpy-matrix, rather, a Numpy-array. 

5345 

5346 The dtype will be a lower-common-denominator dtype (implicit 

5347 upcasting); that is to say if the dtypes (even of numeric types) 

5348 are mixed, the one that accommodates all will be chosen. Use this 

5349 with care if you are not dealing with the blocks. 

5350 

5351 e.g. If the dtypes are float16 and float32, dtype will be upcast to 

5352 float32. If dtypes are int32 and uint8, dtype will be upcase to 

5353 int32. By numpy.find_common_type convention, mixing int64 and uint64 

5354 will result in a float64 dtype. 

5355 

5356 This method is provided for backwards compatibility. Generally, 

5357 it is recommended to use '.values'. 

5358 """ 

5359 warnings.warn( 

5360 "Method .as_matrix will be removed in a future version. " 

5361 "Use .values instead.", 

5362 FutureWarning, 

5363 stacklevel=2, 

5364 ) 

5365 self._consolidate_inplace() 

5366 return self._data.as_array(transpose=self._AXIS_REVERSED, items=columns) 

5367 

5368 @property 

5369 def values(self): 

5370 """ 

5371 Return a Numpy representation of the DataFrame. 

5372 

5373 .. warning:: 

5374 

5375 We recommend using :meth:`DataFrame.to_numpy` instead. 

5376 

5377 Only the values in the DataFrame will be returned, the axes labels 

5378 will be removed. 

5379 

5380 Returns 

5381 ------- 

5382 numpy.ndarray 

5383 The values of the DataFrame. 

5384 

5385 See Also 

5386 -------- 

5387 DataFrame.to_numpy : Recommended alternative to this method. 

5388 DataFrame.index : Retrieve the index labels. 

5389 DataFrame.columns : Retrieving the column names. 

5390 

5391 Notes 

5392 ----- 

5393 The dtype will be a lower-common-denominator dtype (implicit 

5394 upcasting); that is to say if the dtypes (even of numeric types) 

5395 are mixed, the one that accommodates all will be chosen. Use this 

5396 with care if you are not dealing with the blocks. 

5397 

5398 e.g. If the dtypes are float16 and float32, dtype will be upcast to 

5399 float32. If dtypes are int32 and uint8, dtype will be upcast to 

5400 int32. By :func:`numpy.find_common_type` convention, mixing int64 

5401 and uint64 will result in a float64 dtype. 

5402 

5403 Examples 

5404 -------- 

5405 A DataFrame where all columns are the same type (e.g., int64) results 

5406 in an array of the same type. 

5407 

5408 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'age': [ 3, 29], 

5409 ... 'height': [94, 170], 

5410 ... 'weight': [31, 115]}) 

5411 >>> df 

5412 age height weight 

5413 0 3 94 31 

5414 1 29 170 115 

5415 >>> df.dtypes 

5416 age int64 

5417 height int64 

5418 weight int64 

5419 dtype: object 

5420 >>> df.values 

5421 array([[ 3, 94, 31], 

5422 [ 29, 170, 115]], dtype=int64) 

5423 

5424 A DataFrame with mixed type columns(e.g., str/object, int64, float32) 

5425 results in an ndarray of the broadest type that accommodates these 

5426 mixed types (e.g., object). 

5427 

5428 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame([('parrot', 24.0, 'second'), 

5429 ... ('lion', 80.5, 1), 

5430 ... ('monkey', np.nan, None)], 

5431 ... columns=('name', 'max_speed', 'rank')) 

5432 >>> df2.dtypes 

5433 name object 

5434 max_speed float64 

5435 rank object 

5436 dtype: object 

5437 >>> df2.values 

5438 array([['parrot', 24.0, 'second'], 

5439 ['lion', 80.5, 1], 

5440 ['monkey', nan, None]], dtype=object) 

5441 """ 

5442 self._consolidate_inplace() 

5443 return self._data.as_array(transpose=self._AXIS_REVERSED)

5569 Series with the count of columns with each type and

5574 ftypes : Return ftypes (indication of sparse/dense and dtype) in 

5575 this object. 

5576 

5577 Examples

5581 >>> df 

5582 str int float 

5583 0 a 1 1.0 

5584 1 b 2 2.0 

5585 2 c 3 3.0 

5586 

5587 >>> df.get_ftype_counts() # doctest: +SKIP 

5588 float64:dense 1 

5589 int64:dense 1 

5590 object:dense 1 

5591 dtype: int64 

5592 """ 

5593 warnings.warn( 

5594 "get_ftype_counts is deprecated and will " "be removed in a future version", 

5595 FutureWarning, 

5596 stacklevel=2, 

5597 ) 

5598 

5599 from pandas import Series 

5600 

5601 return Series(self._data.get_ftype_counts())

5709

5712 values : a dict of dtype -> Constructor Types 

5713 """

5730 def _to_dict_of_blocks(self, copy=True): 

5731 """ 

5732 Return a dict of dtype -> Constructor Types that 

5733 each is a homogeneous dtype. 

5734 

5735 Internal ONLY 

5736 """ 

5737 return { 

5738 k: self._constructor(v).__finalize__(self) 

5739 for k, v, in self._data.to_dict(copy=copy).items() 

5740 } 

5741 

5742 def astype(self, dtype, copy=True, errors="raise", **kwargs): 

5743 """ 

5744 Cast a pandas object to a specified dtype ``dtype``. 

5745 

5746 Parameters 

5747 ---------- 

5748 dtype : data type, or dict of column name -> data type 

5749 Use a numpy.dtype or Python type to cast entire pandas object to 

5750 the same type. Alternatively, use {col: dtype, ...}, where col is a 

5751 column label and dtype is a numpy.dtype or Python type to cast one 

5752 or more of the DataFrame's columns to column-specific types. 

5753 copy : bool, default True 

5754 Return a copy when ``copy=True`` (be very careful setting 

5755 ``copy=False`` as changes to values then may propagate to other 

5756 pandas objects). 

5757 errors : {'raise', 'ignore'}, default 'raise' 

5758 Control raising of exceptions on invalid data for provided dtype. 

5759 

5760 - ``raise`` : allow exceptions to be raised 

5761 - ``ignore`` : suppress exceptions. On error return original object 

5762 

5763 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

5764 

5765 kwargs : keyword arguments to pass on to the constructor 

5766 

5767 Returns 

5768 ------- 

5769 casted : same type as caller 

5770 

5771 See Also 

5772 -------- 

5773 to_datetime : Convert argument to datetime. 

5774 to_timedelta : Convert argument to timedelta. 

5775 to_numeric : Convert argument to a numeric type. 

5776 numpy.ndarray.astype : Cast a numpy array to a specified type. 

5777 

5778 Examples 

5779 -------- 

5780 Create a DataFrame: 

5781 

5782 >>> d = {'col1': [1, 2], 'col2': [3, 4]} 

5783 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data=d) 

5784 >>> df.dtypes 

5785 col1 int64 

5786 col2 int64 

5787 dtype: object 

5788 

5789 Cast all columns to int32: 

5790 

5791 >>> df.astype('int32').dtypes 

5792 col1 int32 

5793 col2 int32 

5794 dtype: object 

5795 

5796 Cast col1 to int32 using a dictionary: 

5797 

5798 >>> df.astype({'col1': 'int32'}).dtypes 

5799 col1 int32 

5800 col2 int64 

5801 dtype: object 

5802 

5803 Create a series: 

5804 

5805 >>> ser = pd.Series([1, 2], dtype='int32') 

5806 >>> ser 

5807 0 1 

5808 1 2 

5809 dtype: int32 

5810 >>> ser.astype('int64') 

5811 0 1 

5812 1 2 

5813 dtype: int64 

5814 

5815 Convert to categorical type: 

5816 

5817 >>> ser.astype('category') 

5818 0 1 

5819 1 2 

5820 dtype: category 

5821 Categories (2, int64): [1, 2] 

5822 

5823 Convert to ordered categorical type with custom ordering: 

5824 

5825 >>> cat_dtype = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype( 

5826 ... categories=[2, 1], ordered=True) 

5827 >>> ser.astype(cat_dtype) 

5828 0 1 

5829 1 2 

5830 dtype: category 

5831 Categories (2, int64): [2 < 1] 

5832 

5833 Note that using ``copy=False`` and changing data on a new 

5834 pandas object may propagate changes: 

5835 

5836 >>> s1 = pd.Series([1,2]) 

5837 >>> s2 = s1.astype('int64', copy=False) 

5838 >>> s2[0] = 10 

5839 >>> s1 # note that s1[0] has changed too 

5840 0 10 

5841 1 2 

5842 dtype: int64 

5843 """ 

5844 if is_dict_like(dtype): 

5845 if self.ndim == 1: # i.e. Series 

5846 if len(dtype) > 1 or self.name not in dtype: 

5847 raise KeyError( 

5848 "Only the Series name can be used for " 

5849 "the key in Series dtype mappings." 

5850 ) 

5851 new_type = dtype[self.name] 

5852 return self.astype(new_type, copy, errors, **kwargs) 

5853 

5854 for col_name in dtype.keys(): 

5855 if col_name not in self: 

5856 raise KeyError( 

5857 "Only a column name can be used for the " 

5858 "key in a dtype mappings argument." 

5859 ) 

5860 results = [] 

5861 for col_name, col in self.items(): 

5862 if col_name in dtype: 

5863 results.append( 

5864 col.astype( 

5865 dtype=dtype[col_name], copy=copy, errors=errors, **kwargs 

5866 ) 

5867 ) 

5868 else: 

5869 results.append(results.append(col.copy() if copy else col)) 

5870 

5871 elif is_extension_array_dtype(dtype) and self.ndim > 1: 

5872 # GH 18099/22869: columnwise conversion to extension dtype 

5873 # GH 24704: use iloc to handle duplicate column names 

5874 results = ( 

5875 self.iloc[:, i].astype(dtype, copy=copy) 

5876 for i in range(len(self.columns)) 

5877 ) 

5878 

5879 else: 

5880 # else, only a single dtype is given 

5881 new_data = self._data.astype( 

5882 dtype=dtype, copy=copy, errors=errors, **kwargs 

5883 ) 

5884 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self) 

5885 

5886 # GH 19920: retain column metadata after concat 

5887 result = pd.concat(results, axis=1, copy=False) 

5888 result.columns = self.columns 

5889 return result 

5890 

5891 def copy(self, deep=True): 

5892 """ 

5893 Make a copy of this object's indices and data. 

5894 

5895 When ``deep=True`` (default), a new object will be created with a 

5896 copy of the calling object's data and indices. Modifications to 

5897 the data or indices of the copy will not be reflected in the 

5898 original object (see notes below). 

5899 

5900 When ``deep=False``, a new object will be created without copying 

5901 the calling object's data or index (only references to the data 

5902 and index are copied). Any changes to the data of the original 

5903 will be reflected in the shallow copy (and vice versa). 

5904 

5905 Parameters 

5906 ---------- 

5907 deep : bool, default True 

5908 Make a deep copy, including a copy of the data and the indices. 

5909 With ``deep=False`` neither the indices nor the data are copied. 

5910 

5911 Returns 

5912 ------- 

5913 copy : Series or DataFrame 

5914 Object type matches caller. 

5915 

5916 Notes 

5917 ----- 

5918 When ``deep=True``, data is copied but actual Python objects 

5919 will not be copied recursively, only the reference to the object. 

5920 This is in contrast to `copy.deepcopy` in the Standard Library, 

5921 which recursively copies object data (see examples below). 

5922 

5923 While ``Index`` objects are copied when ``deep=True``, the underlying 

5924 numpy array is not copied for performance reasons. Since ``Index`` is 

5925 immutable, the underlying data can be safely shared and a copy 

5926 is not needed. 

5927 

5928 Examples 

5929 -------- 

5930 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=["a", "b"]) 

5931 >>> s 

5932 a 1 

5933 b 2 

5934 dtype: int64 

5935 

5936 >>> s_copy = s.copy() 

5937 >>> s_copy 

5938 a 1 

5939 b 2 

5940 dtype: int64 

5941 

5942 **Shallow copy versus default (deep) copy:** 

5943 

5944 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=["a", "b"]) 

5945 >>> deep = s.copy() 

5946 >>> shallow = s.copy(deep=False) 

5947 

5948 Shallow copy shares data and index with original. 

5949 

5950 >>> s is shallow 

5951 False 

5952 >>> s.values is shallow.values and s.index is shallow.index 

5953 True 

5954 

5955 Deep copy has own copy of data and index. 

5956 

5957 >>> s is deep 

5958 False 

5959 >>> s.values is deep.values or s.index is deep.index 

5960 False 

5961 

5962 Updates to the data shared by shallow copy and original is reflected 

5963 in both; deep copy remains unchanged. 

5964 

5965 >>> s[0] = 3 

5966 >>> shallow[1] = 4 

5967 >>> s 

5968 a 3 

5969 b 4 

5970 dtype: int64 

5971 >>> shallow 

5972 a 3 

5973 b 4 

5974 dtype: int64 

5975 >>> deep 

5976 a 1 

5977 b 2 

5978 dtype: int64 

5979 

5980 Note that when copying an object containing Python objects, a deep copy 

5981 will copy the data, but will not do so recursively. Updating a nested 

5982 data object will be reflected in the deep copy. 

5983 

5984 >>> s = pd.Series([[1, 2], [3, 4]]) 

5985 >>> deep = s.copy() 

5986 >>> s[0][0] = 10 

5987 >>> s 

5988 0 [10, 2] 

5989 1 [3, 4] 

5990 dtype: object 

5991 >>> deep 

5992 0 [10, 2] 

5993 1 [3, 4] 

5994 dtype: object 

5995 """ 

5996 data = self._data.copy(deep=deep) 

5997 return self._constructor(data).__finalize__(self) 

5998 

5999 def __copy__(self, deep=True): 

6000 return self.copy(deep=deep) 

6001 

6002 def __deepcopy__(self, memo=None): 

6003 """ 

6004 Parameters 

6005 ---------- 

6006 memo, default None 

6007 Standard signature. Unused 

6008 """ 

6009 if memo is None: 

6010 memo = {} 

6011 return self.copy(deep=True)

6013 def _convert( 

6014 self, datetime=False, numeric=False, timedelta=False, coerce=False, copy=True 

6015 ): 

6016 """ 

6017 Attempt to infer better dtype for object columns 

6018 

6019 Parameters 

6020 ---------- 

6021 datetime : boolean, default False 

6022 If True, convert to date where possible. 

6023 numeric : boolean, default False 

6024 If True, attempt to convert to numbers (including strings), with 

6025 unconvertible values becoming NaN. 

6026 timedelta : boolean, default False 

6027 If True, convert to timedelta where possible. 

6028 coerce : boolean, default False 

6029 If True, force conversion with unconvertible values converted to 

6030 nulls (NaN or NaT) 

6031 copy : boolean, default True 

6032 If True, return a copy even if no copy is necessary (e.g. no 

6033 conversion was done). Note: This is meant for internal use, and 

6034 should not be confused with inplace. 

6035 

6036 Returns 

6037 ------- 

6038 converted : same as input object 

6039 """ 

6040 return self._constructor( 

6041 self._data.convert( 

6042 datetime=datetime, 

6043 numeric=numeric, 

6044 timedelta=timedelta, 

6045 coerce=coerce, 

6046 copy=copy, 

6047 ) 

6048 ).__finalize__(self)

6050 def infer_objects(self): 

6051 """ 

6052 Attempt to infer better dtypes for object columns. 

6053 

6054 Attempts soft conversion of object-dtyped 

6055 columns, leaving non-object and unconvertible 

6056 columns unchanged. The inference rules are the 

6057 same as during normal Series/DataFrame construction. 

6058 

6059 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

6060 

6061 Returns 

6062 ------- 

6063 converted : same type as input object 

6064 

6065 See Also 

6066 -------- 

6067 to_datetime : Convert argument to datetime. 

6068 to_timedelta : Convert argument to timedelta. 

6069 to_numeric : Convert argument to numeric type. 

6070 

6071 Examples 

6072 -------- 

6073 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": ["a", 1, 2, 3]}) 

6074 >>> df = df.iloc[1:] 

6075 >>> df 

6076 A 

6077 1 1 

6078 2 2 

6079 3 3 

6080 

6081 >>> df.dtypes 

6082 A object 

6083 dtype: object 

6084 

6085 >>> df.infer_objects().dtypes 

6086 A int64 

6087 dtype: object 

6088 """ 

6089 # numeric=False necessary to only soft convert; 

6090 # python objects will still be converted to 

6091 # native numpy numeric types 

6092 return self._constructor( 

6093 self._data.convert( 

6094 datetime=True, numeric=False, timedelta=True, coerce=False, copy=True 

6095 ) 

6096 ).__finalize__(self)

6098 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

6099 # Filling NA's 

6100 

6101 def fillna( 

6102 self, 

6103 value=None, 

6104 method=None, 

6105 axis=None, 

6106 inplace=False, 

6107 limit=None, 

6108 downcast=None, 

6109 ): 

6110 """ 

6111 Fill NA/NaN values using the specified method. 

6112 

6113 Parameters 

6114 ---------- 

6115 value : scalar, dict, Series, or DataFrame 

6116 Value to use to fill holes (e.g. 0), alternately a 

6117 dict/Series/DataFrame of values specifying which value to use for 

6118 each index (for a Series) or column (for a DataFrame). Values not 

6119 in the dict/Series/DataFrame will not be filled. This value cannot 

6120 be a list. 

6121 method : {'backfill', 'bfill', 'pad', 'ffill', None}, default None 

6122 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed Series 

6123 pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next valid 

6124 backfill / bfill: use next valid observation to fill gap. 

6125 axis : %(axes_single_arg)s 

6126 Axis along which to fill missing values. 

6127 inplace : bool, default False 

6128 If True, fill in-place. Note: this will modify any 

6129 other views on this object (e.g., a no-copy slice for a column in a 

6130 DataFrame). 

6131 limit : int, default None 

6132 If method is specified, this is the maximum number of consecutive 

6133 NaN values to forward/backward fill. In other words, if there is 

6134 a gap with more than this number of consecutive NaNs, it will only 

6135 be partially filled. If method is not specified, this is the 

6136 maximum number of entries along the entire axis where NaNs will be 

6137 filled. Must be greater than 0 if not None. 

6138 downcast : dict, default is None 

6139 A dict of item->dtype of what to downcast if possible, 

6140 or the string 'infer' which will try to downcast to an appropriate 

6141 equal type (e.g. float64 to int64 if possible). 

6142 

6143 Returns 

6144 ------- 

6145 %(klass)s 

6146 Object with missing values filled. 

6147 

6148 See Also 

6149 -------- 

6150 interpolate : Fill NaN values using interpolation. 

6151 reindex : Conform object to new index. 

6152 asfreq : Convert TimeSeries to specified frequency. 

6153 

6154 Examples 

6155 -------- 

6156 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[np.nan, 2, np.nan, 0], 

6157 ... [3, 4, np.nan, 1], 

6158 ... [np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, 5], 

6159 ... [np.nan, 3, np.nan, 4]], 

6160 ... columns=list('ABCD')) 

6161 >>> df 

6162 A B C D 

6163 0 NaN 2.0 NaN 0 

6164 1 3.0 4.0 NaN 1 

6165 2 NaN NaN NaN 5 

6166 3 NaN 3.0 NaN 4 

6167 

6168 Replace all NaN elements with 0s. 

6169 

6170 >>> df.fillna(0) 

6171 A B C D 

6172 0 0.0 2.0 0.0 0 

6173 1 3.0 4.0 0.0 1 

6174 2 0.0 0.0 0.0 5 

6175 3 0.0 3.0 0.0 4 

6176 

6177 We can also propagate non-null values forward or backward. 

6178 

6179 >>> df.fillna(method='ffill') 

6180 A B C D 

6181 0 NaN 2.0 NaN 0 

6182 1 3.0 4.0 NaN 1 

6183 2 3.0 4.0 NaN 5 

6184 3 3.0 3.0 NaN 4 

6185 

6186 Replace all NaN elements in column 'A', 'B', 'C', and 'D', with 0, 1, 

6187 2, and 3 respectively. 

6188 

6189 >>> values = {'A': 0, 'B': 1, 'C': 2, 'D': 3} 

6190 >>> df.fillna(value=values) 

6191 A B C D 

6192 0 0.0 2.0 2.0 0 

6193 1 3.0 4.0 2.0 1 

6194 2 0.0 1.0 2.0 5 

6195 3 0.0 3.0 2.0 4 

6196 

6197 Only replace the first NaN element. 

6198 

6199 >>> df.fillna(value=values, limit=1) 

6200 A B C D 

6201 0 0.0 2.0 2.0 0 

6202 1 3.0 4.0 NaN 1 

6203 2 NaN 1.0 NaN 5 

6204 3 NaN 3.0 NaN 4 

6205 """ 

6206 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace") 

6207 value, method = validate_fillna_kwargs(value, method) 

6208 

6209 self._consolidate_inplace() 

6210 

6211 # set the default here, so functions examining the signaure 

6212 # can detect if something was set (e.g. in groupby) (GH9221) 

6213 if axis is None: 

6214 axis = 0 

6215 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

6216 

6217 from pandas import DataFrame 

6218 

6219 if value is None: 

6220 

6221 if self._is_mixed_type and axis == 1: 

6222 if inplace: 

6223 raise NotImplementedError() 

6224 result = self.T.fillna(method=method, limit=limit).T 

6225 

6226 # need to downcast here because of all of the transposes 

6227 result._data = result._data.downcast() 

6228 

6229 return result 

6230 

6231 new_data = self._data.interpolate( 

6232 method=method, 

6233 axis=axis, 

6234 limit=limit, 

6235 inplace=inplace, 

6236 coerce=True, 

6237 downcast=downcast, 

6238 ) 

6239 else: 

6240 if len(self._get_axis(axis)) == 0: 

6241 return self 

6242 

6243 if self.ndim == 1: 

6244 if isinstance(value, (dict, ABCSeries)): 

6245 from pandas import Series 

6246 

6247 value = Series(value) 

6248 elif not is_list_like(value): 

6249 pass 

6250 else: 

6251 raise TypeError( 

6252 '"value" parameter must be a scalar, dict ' 

6253 "or Series, but you passed a " 

6254 '"{0}"'.format(type(value).__name__) 

6255 ) 

6256 

6257 new_data = self._data.fillna( 

6258 value=value, limit=limit, inplace=inplace, downcast=downcast 

6259 ) 

6260 

6261 elif isinstance(value, (dict, ABCSeries)): 

6262 if axis == 1: 

6263 raise NotImplementedError( 

6264 "Currently only can fill " 

6265 "with dict/Series column " 

6266 "by column" 

6267 ) 

6268 

6269 result = self if inplace else self.copy() 

6270 for k, v in value.items(): 

6271 if k not in result: 

6272 continue 

6273 obj = result[k] 

6274 obj.fillna(v, limit=limit, inplace=True, downcast=downcast) 

6275 return result if not inplace else None 

6276 

6277 elif not is_list_like(value): 

6278 new_data = self._data.fillna( 

6279 value=value, limit=limit, inplace=inplace, downcast=downcast 

6280 ) 

6281 elif isinstance(value, DataFrame) and self.ndim == 2: 

6282 new_data = self.where(self.notna(), value) 

6283 else: 

6284 raise ValueError("invalid fill value with a %s" % type(value)) 

6285 

6286 if inplace: 

6287 self._update_inplace(new_data) 

6288 else: 

6289 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self) 

6290 

6291 def ffill(self, axis=None, inplace=False, limit=None, downcast=None): 

6292 """ 

6293 Synonym for :meth:`DataFrame.fillna` with ``method='ffill'``. 

6294 

6295 Returns 

6296 ------- 

6297 %(klass)s 

6298 Object with missing values filled. 

6299 """ 

6300 return self.fillna( 

6301 method="ffill", axis=axis, inplace=inplace, limit=limit, downcast=downcast 

6302 ) 

6303 

6304 def bfill(self, axis=None, inplace=False, limit=None, downcast=None): 

6305 """ 

6306 Synonym for :meth:`DataFrame.fillna` with ``method='bfill'``. 

6307 

6308 Returns 

6309 ------- 

6310 %(klass)s 

6311 Object with missing values filled. 

6312 """ 

6313 return self.fillna( 

6314 method="bfill", axis=axis, inplace=inplace, limit=limit, downcast=downcast 

6315 )

6317 _shared_docs[ 

6318 "replace" 

6319 ] = """ 

6320 Replace values given in `to_replace` with `value`. 

6321 

6322 Values of the %(klass)s are replaced with other values dynamically. 

6323 This differs from updating with ``.loc`` or ``.iloc``, which require 

6324 you to specify a location to update with some value. 

6325 

6326 Parameters 

6327 ---------- 

6328 to_replace : str, regex, list, dict, Series, int, float, or None 

6329 How to find the values that will be replaced. 

6330 

6331 * numeric, str or regex: 

6332 

6333 - numeric: numeric values equal to `to_replace` will be 

6334 replaced with `value` 

6335 - str: string exactly matching `to_replace` will be replaced 

6336 with `value` 

6337 - regex: regexs matching `to_replace` will be replaced with 

6338 `value` 

6339 

6340 * list of str, regex, or numeric: 

6341 

6342 - First, if `to_replace` and `value` are both lists, they 

6343 **must** be the same length. 

6344 - Second, if ``regex=True`` then all of the strings in **both** 

6345 lists will be interpreted as regexs otherwise they will match 

6346 directly. This doesn't matter much for `value` since there 

6347 are only a few possible substitution regexes you can use. 

6348 - str, regex and numeric rules apply as above. 

6349 

6350 * dict: 

6351 

6352 - Dicts can be used to specify different replacement values 

6353 for different existing values. For example, 

6354 ``{'a': 'b', 'y': 'z'}`` replaces the value 'a' with 'b' and 

6355 'y' with 'z'. To use a dict in this way the `value` 

6356 parameter should be `None`. 

6357 - For a DataFrame a dict can specify that different values 

6358 should be replaced in different columns. For example, 

6359 ``{'a': 1, 'b': 'z'}`` looks for the value 1 in column 'a' 

6360 and the value 'z' in column 'b' and replaces these values 

6361 with whatever is specified in `value`. The `value` parameter 

6362 should not be ``None`` in this case. You can treat this as a 

6363 special case of passing two lists except that you are 

6364 specifying the column to search in. 

6365 - For a DataFrame nested dictionaries, e.g., 

6366 ``{'a': {'b': np.nan}}``, are read as follows: look in column 

6367 'a' for the value 'b' and replace it with NaN. The `value` 

6368 parameter should be ``None`` to use a nested dict in this 

6369 way. You can nest regular expressions as well. Note that 

6370 column names (the top-level dictionary keys in a nested 

6371 dictionary) **cannot** be regular expressions. 

6372 

6373 * None: 

6374 

6375 - This means that the `regex` argument must be a string, 

6376 compiled regular expression, or list, dict, ndarray or 

6377 Series of such elements. If `value` is also ``None`` then 

6378 this **must** be a nested dictionary or Series. 

6379 

6380 See the examples section for examples of each of these. 

6381 value : scalar, dict, list, str, regex, default None 

6382 Value to replace any values matching `to_replace` with. 

6383 For a DataFrame a dict of values can be used to specify which 

6384 value to use for each column (columns not in the dict will not be 

6385 filled). Regular expressions, strings and lists or dicts of such 

6386 objects are also allowed. 

6387 inplace : bool, default False 

6388 If True, in place. Note: this will modify any 

6389 other views on this object (e.g. a column from a DataFrame). 

6390 Returns the caller if this is True. 

6391 limit : int, default None 

6392 Maximum size gap to forward or backward fill. 

6393 regex : bool or same types as `to_replace`, default False 

6394 Whether to interpret `to_replace` and/or `value` as regular 

6395 expressions. If this is ``True`` then `to_replace` *must* be a 

6396 string. Alternatively, this could be a regular expression or a 

6397 list, dict, or array of regular expressions in which case 

6398 `to_replace` must be ``None``. 

6399 method : {'pad', 'ffill', 'bfill', `None`} 

6400 The method to use when for replacement, when `to_replace` is a 

6401 scalar, list or tuple and `value` is ``None``. 

6402 

6403 .. versionchanged:: 0.23.0 

6404 Added to DataFrame. 

6405 

6406 Returns 

6407 ------- 

6408 %(klass)s 

6409 Object after replacement. 

6410 

6411 Raises 

6412 ------ 

6413 AssertionError 

6414 * If `regex` is not a ``bool`` and `to_replace` is not 

6415 ``None``. 

6416 TypeError 

6417 * If `to_replace` is a ``dict`` and `value` is not a ``list``, 

6418 ``dict``, ``ndarray``, or ``Series`` 

6419 * If `to_replace` is ``None`` and `regex` is not compilable 

6420 into a regular expression or is a list, dict, ndarray, or 

6421 Series. 

6422 * When replacing multiple ``bool`` or ``datetime64`` objects and 

6423 the arguments to `to_replace` does not match the type of the 

6424 value being replaced 

6425 ValueError 

6426 * If a ``list`` or an ``ndarray`` is passed to `to_replace` and 

6427 `value` but they are not the same length. 

6428 

6429 See Also 

6430 -------- 

6431 %(klass)s.fillna : Fill NA values. 

6432 %(klass)s.where : Replace values based on boolean condition. 

6433 Series.str.replace : Simple string replacement. 

6434 

6435 Notes 

6436 ----- 

6437 * Regex substitution is performed under the hood with ``re.sub``. The 

6438 rules for substitution for ``re.sub`` are the same. 

6439 * Regular expressions will only substitute on strings, meaning you 

6440 cannot provide, for example, a regular expression matching floating 

6441 point numbers and expect the columns in your frame that have a 

6442 numeric dtype to be matched. However, if those floating point 

6443 numbers *are* strings, then you can do this. 

6444 * This method has *a lot* of options. You are encouraged to experiment 

6445 and play with this method to gain intuition about how it works. 

6446 * When dict is used as the `to_replace` value, it is like 

6447 key(s) in the dict are the to_replace part and 

6448 value(s) in the dict are the value parameter. 

6449 

6450 Examples 

6451 -------- 

6452 

6453 **Scalar `to_replace` and `value`** 

6454 

6455 >>> s = pd.Series([0, 1, 2, 3, 4]) 

6456 >>> s.replace(0, 5) 

6457 0 5 

6458 1 1 

6459 2 2 

6460 3 3 

6461 4 4 

6462 dtype: int64 

6463 

6464 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [0, 1, 2, 3, 4], 

6465 ... 'B': [5, 6, 7, 8, 9], 

6466 ... 'C': ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']}) 

6467 >>> df.replace(0, 5) 

6468 A B C 

6469 0 5 5 a 

6470 1 1 6 b 

6471 2 2 7 c 

6472 3 3 8 d 

6473 4 4 9 e 

6474 

6475 **List-like `to_replace`** 

6476 

6477 >>> df.replace([0, 1, 2, 3], 4) 

6478 A B C 

6479 0 4 5 a 

6480 1 4 6 b 

6481 2 4 7 c 

6482 3 4 8 d 

6483 4 4 9 e 

6484 

6485 >>> df.replace([0, 1, 2, 3], [4, 3, 2, 1]) 

6486 A B C 

6487 0 4 5 a 

6488 1 3 6 b 

6489 2 2 7 c 

6490 3 1 8 d 

6491 4 4 9 e 

6492 

6493 >>> s.replace([1, 2], method='bfill') 

6494 0 0 

6495 1 3 

6496 2 3 

6497 3 3 

6498 4 4 

6499 dtype: int64 

6500 

6501 **dict-like `to_replace`** 

6502 

6503 >>> df.replace({0: 10, 1: 100}) 

6504 A B C 

6505 0 10 5 a 

6506 1 100 6 b 

6507 2 2 7 c 

6508 3 3 8 d 

6509 4 4 9 e 

6510 

6511 >>> df.replace({'A': 0, 'B': 5}, 100) 

6512 A B C 

6513 0 100 100 a 

6514 1 1 6 b 

6515 2 2 7 c 

6516 3 3 8 d 

6517 4 4 9 e 

6518 

6519 >>> df.replace({'A': {0: 100, 4: 400}}) 

6520 A B C 

6521 0 100 5 a 

6522 1 1 6 b 

6523 2 2 7 c 

6524 3 3 8 d 

6525 4 400 9 e 

6526 

6527 **Regular expression `to_replace`** 

6528 

6529 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['bat', 'foo', 'bait'], 

6530 ... 'B': ['abc', 'bar', 'xyz']}) 

6531 >>> df.replace(to_replace=r'^ba.$', value='new', regex=True) 

6532 A B 

6533 0 new abc 

6534 1 foo new 

6535 2 bait xyz 

6536 

6537 >>> df.replace({'A': r'^ba.$'}, {'A': 'new'}, regex=True) 

6538 A B 

6539 0 new abc 

6540 1 foo bar 

6541 2 bait xyz 

6542 

6543 >>> df.replace(regex=r'^ba.$', value='new') 

6544 A B 

6545 0 new abc 

6546 1 foo new 

6547 2 bait xyz 

6548 

6549 >>> df.replace(regex={r'^ba.$': 'new', 'foo': 'xyz'}) 

6550 A B 

6551 0 new abc 

6552 1 xyz new 

6553 2 bait xyz 

6554 

6555 >>> df.replace(regex=[r'^ba.$', 'foo'], value='new') 

6556 A B 

6557 0 new abc 

6558 1 new new 

6559 2 bait xyz 

6560 

6561 Note that when replacing multiple ``bool`` or ``datetime64`` objects, 

6562 the data types in the `to_replace` parameter must match the data 

6563 type of the value being replaced: 

6564 

6565 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [True, False, True], 

6566 ... 'B': [False, True, False]}) 

6567 >>> df.replace({'a string': 'new value', True: False}) # raises 

6568 Traceback (most recent call last): 

6569 ... 

6570 TypeError: Cannot compare types 'ndarray(dtype=bool)' and 'str' 

6571 

6572 This raises a ``TypeError`` because one of the ``dict`` keys is not of 

6573 the correct type for replacement. 

6574 

6575 Compare the behavior of ``s.replace({'a': None})`` and 

6576 ``s.replace('a', None)`` to understand the peculiarities 

6577 of the `to_replace` parameter: 

6578 

6579 >>> s = pd.Series([10, 'a', 'a', 'b', 'a']) 

6580 

6581 When one uses a dict as the `to_replace` value, it is like the 

6582 value(s) in the dict are equal to the `value` parameter. 

6583 ``s.replace({'a': None})`` is equivalent to 

6584 ``s.replace(to_replace={'a': None}, value=None, method=None)``: 

6585 

6586 >>> s.replace({'a': None}) 

6587 0 10 

6588 1 None 

6589 2 None 

6590 3 b 

6591 4 None 

6592 dtype: object 

6593 

6594 When ``value=None`` and `to_replace` is a scalar, list or 

6595 tuple, `replace` uses the method parameter (default 'pad') to do the 

6596 replacement. So this is why the 'a' values are being replaced by 10 

6597 in rows 1 and 2 and 'b' in row 4 in this case. 

6598 The command ``s.replace('a', None)`` is actually equivalent to 

6599 ``s.replace(to_replace='a', value=None, method='pad')``: 

6600 

6601 >>> s.replace('a', None) 

6602 0 10 

6603 1 10 

6604 2 10 

6605 3 b 

6606 4 b 

6607 dtype: object 

6608 """ 

6609 

6610 @Appender(_shared_docs["replace"] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

6611 def replace( 

6612 self, 

6613 to_replace=None, 

6614 value=None, 

6615 inplace=False, 

6616 limit=None, 

6617 regex=False, 

6618 method="pad", 

6619 ): 

6620 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace") 

6621 if not is_bool(regex) and to_replace is not None: 

6622 raise AssertionError( 

6623 "'to_replace' must be 'None' if 'regex' is " "not a bool" 

6624 ) 

6625 

6626 self._consolidate_inplace() 

6627 

6628 if value is None: 

6629 # passing a single value that is scalar like 

6630 # when value is None (GH5319), for compat 

6631 if not is_dict_like(to_replace) and not is_dict_like(regex): 

6632 to_replace = [to_replace] 

6633 

6634 if isinstance(to_replace, (tuple, list)): 

6635 if isinstance(self, pd.DataFrame): 

6636 return self.apply( 

6637 _single_replace, args=(to_replace, method, inplace, limit) 

6638 ) 

6639 return _single_replace(self, to_replace, method, inplace, limit) 

6640 

6641 if not is_dict_like(to_replace): 

6642 if not is_dict_like(regex): 

6643 raise TypeError( 

6644 'If "to_replace" and "value" are both None' 

6645 ' and "to_replace" is not a list, then ' 

6646 "regex must be a mapping" 

6647 ) 

6648 to_replace = regex 

6649 regex = True 

6650 

6651 items = list(to_replace.items()) 

6652 keys, values = zip(*items) if items else ([], []) 

6653 

6654 are_mappings = [is_dict_like(v) for v in values] 

6655 

6656 if any(are_mappings): 

6657 if not all(are_mappings): 

6658 raise TypeError( 

6659 "If a nested mapping is passed, all values" 

6660 " of the top level mapping must be " 

6661 "mappings" 

6662 ) 

6663 # passed a nested dict/Series 

6664 to_rep_dict = {} 

6665 value_dict = {} 

6666 

6667 for k, v in items: 

6668 keys, values = list(zip(*v.items())) or ([], []) 

6669 if set(keys) & set(values): 

6670 raise ValueError( 

6671 "Replacement not allowed with " 

6672 "overlapping keys and values" 

6673 ) 

6674 to_rep_dict[k] = list(keys) 

6675 value_dict[k] = list(values) 

6676 

6677 to_replace, value = to_rep_dict, value_dict 

6678 else: 

6679 to_replace, value = keys, values 

6680 

6681 return self.replace( 

6682 to_replace, value, inplace=inplace, limit=limit, regex=regex 

6683 ) 

6684 else: 

6685 

6686 # need a non-zero len on all axes 

6687 if not self.size: 

6688 return self 

6689 

6690 new_data = self._data 

6691 if is_dict_like(to_replace): 

6692 if is_dict_like(value): # {'A' : NA} -> {'A' : 0} 

6693 res = self if inplace else self.copy() 

6694 for c, src in to_replace.items(): 

6695 if c in value and c in self: 

6696 # object conversion is handled in 

6697 # series.replace which is called recursively 

6698 res[c] = res[c].replace( 

6699 to_replace=src, 

6700 value=value[c], 

6701 inplace=False, 

6702 regex=regex, 

6703 ) 

6704 return None if inplace else res 

6705 

6706 # {'A': NA} -> 0 

6707 elif not is_list_like(value): 

6708 keys = [(k, src) for k, src in to_replace.items() if k in self] 

6709 keys_len = len(keys) - 1 

6710 for i, (k, src) in enumerate(keys): 

6711 convert = i == keys_len 

6712 new_data = new_data.replace( 

6713 to_replace=src, 

6714 value=value, 

6715 filter=[k], 

6716 inplace=inplace, 

6717 regex=regex, 

6718 convert=convert, 

6719 ) 

6720 else: 

6721 raise TypeError("value argument must be scalar, dict, or " "Series") 

6722 

6723 elif is_list_like(to_replace): # [NA, ''] -> [0, 'missing'] 

6724 if is_list_like(value): 

6725 if len(to_replace) != len(value): 

6726 raise ValueError( 

6727 "Replacement lists must match " 

6728 "in length. Expecting %d got %d " 

6729 % (len(to_replace), len(value)) 

6730 ) 

6731 

6732 new_data = self._data.replace_list( 

6733 src_list=to_replace, 

6734 dest_list=value, 

6735 inplace=inplace, 

6736 regex=regex, 

6737 ) 

6738 

6739 else: # [NA, ''] -> 0 

6740 new_data = self._data.replace( 

6741 to_replace=to_replace, value=value, inplace=inplace, regex=regex 

6742 ) 

6743 elif to_replace is None: 

6744 if not ( 

6745 is_re_compilable(regex) 

6746 or is_list_like(regex) 

6747 or is_dict_like(regex) 

6748 ): 

6749 raise TypeError( 

6750 "'regex' must be a string or a compiled " 

6751 "regular expression or a list or dict of " 

6752 "strings or regular expressions, you " 

6753 "passed a" 

6754 " {0!r}".format(type(regex).__name__) 

6755 ) 

6756 return self.replace( 

6757 regex, value, inplace=inplace, limit=limit, regex=True 

6758 ) 

6759 else: 

6760 

6761 # dest iterable dict-like 

6762 if is_dict_like(value): # NA -> {'A' : 0, 'B' : -1} 

6763 new_data = self._data 

6764 

6765 for k, v in value.items(): 

6766 if k in self: 

6767 new_data = new_data.replace( 

6768 to_replace=to_replace, 

6769 value=v, 

6770 filter=[k], 

6771 inplace=inplace, 

6772 regex=regex, 

6773 ) 

6774 

6775 elif not is_list_like(value): # NA -> 0 

6776 new_data = self._data.replace( 

6777 to_replace=to_replace, value=value, inplace=inplace, regex=regex 

6778 ) 

6779 else: 

6780 msg = ('Invalid "to_replace" type: ' "{0!r}").format( 

6781 type(to_replace).__name__ 

6782 ) 

6783 raise TypeError(msg) # pragma: no cover 

6784 

6785 if inplace: 

6786 self._update_inplace(new_data) 

6787 else: 

6788 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self)
