6790 _shared_docs[ 

6791 "interpolate" 

6792 ] = """ 

6793 Please note that only ``method='linear'`` is supported for 

6794 DataFrame/Series with a MultiIndex. 

6795 

6796 Parameters 

6797 ---------- 

6798 method : str, default 'linear' 

6799 Interpolation technique to use. One of: 

6800 

6801 * 'linear': Ignore the index and treat the values as equally 

6802 spaced. This is the only method supported on MultiIndexes. 

6803 * 'time': Works on daily and higher resolution data to interpolate 

6804 given length of interval. 

6805 * 'index', 'values': use the actual numerical values of the index. 

6806 * 'pad': Fill in NaNs using existing values. 

6807 * 'nearest', 'zero', 'slinear', 'quadratic', 'cubic', 'spline', 

6808 'barycentric', 'polynomial': Passed to 

6809 `scipy.interpolate.interp1d`. These methods use the numerical 

6810 values of the index. Both 'polynomial' and 'spline' require that 

6811 you also specify an `order` (int), e.g. 

6812 ``df.interpolate(method='polynomial', order=5)``. 

6813 * 'krogh', 'piecewise_polynomial', 'spline', 'pchip', 'akima': 

6814 Wrappers around the SciPy interpolation methods of similar 

6815 names. See `Notes`. 

6816 * 'from_derivatives': Refers to 

6817 `scipy.interpolate.BPoly.from_derivatives` which 

6818 replaces 'piecewise_polynomial' interpolation method in 

6819 scipy 0.18. 

6820 

6821 .. versionadded:: 0.18.1 

6822 

6823 Added support for the 'akima' method. 

6824 Added interpolate method 'from_derivatives' which replaces 

6825 'piecewise_polynomial' in SciPy 0.18; backwards-compatible with 

6826 SciPy < 0.18 

6827 

6828 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default None 

6829 Axis to interpolate along. 

6830 limit : int, optional 

6831 Maximum number of consecutive NaNs to fill. Must be greater than 

6832 0. 

6833 inplace : bool, default False 

6834 Update the data in place if possible. 

6835 limit_direction : {'forward', 'backward', 'both'}, default 'forward' 

6836 If limit is specified, consecutive NaNs will be filled in this 

6837 direction. 

6838 limit_area : {`None`, 'inside', 'outside'}, default None 

6839 If limit is specified, consecutive NaNs will be filled with this 

6840 restriction. 

6841 

6842 * ``None``: No fill restriction. 

6843 * 'inside': Only fill NaNs surrounded by valid values 

6844 (interpolate). 

6845 * 'outside': Only fill NaNs outside valid values (extrapolate). 

6846 

6847 .. versionadded:: 0.23.0 

6848 

6849 downcast : optional, 'infer' or None, defaults to None 

6850 Downcast dtypes if possible. 

6851 **kwargs 

6852 Keyword arguments to pass on to the interpolating function. 

6853 

6854 Returns 

6855 ------- 

6856 Series or DataFrame 

6857 Returns the same object type as the caller, interpolated at 

6858 some or all ``NaN`` values. 

6859 

6860 See Also 

6861 -------- 

6862 fillna : Fill missing values using different methods. 

6863 scipy.interpolate.Akima1DInterpolator : Piecewise cubic polynomials 

6864 (Akima interpolator). 

6865 scipy.interpolate.BPoly.from_derivatives : Piecewise polynomial in the 

6866 Bernstein basis. 

6867 scipy.interpolate.interp1d : Interpolate a 1-D function. 

6868 scipy.interpolate.KroghInterpolator : Interpolate polynomial (Krogh 

6869 interpolator). 

6870 scipy.interpolate.PchipInterpolator : PCHIP 1-d monotonic cubic 

6871 interpolation. 

6872 scipy.interpolate.CubicSpline : Cubic spline data interpolator. 

6873 

6874 Notes 

6875 ----- 

6876 The 'krogh', 'piecewise_polynomial', 'spline', 'pchip' and 'akima' 

6877 methods are wrappers around the respective SciPy implementations of 

6878 similar names. These use the actual numerical values of the index. 

6879 For more information on their behavior, see the 

6880 `SciPy documentation 

6881 <http://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/interpolate.html#univariate-interpolation>`__ 

6882 and `SciPy tutorial 

6883 <http://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/tutorial/interpolate.html>`__. 

6884 

6885 Examples 

6886 -------- 

6887 Filling in ``NaN`` in a :class:`~pandas.Series` via linear 

6888 interpolation. 

6889 

6890 >>> s = pd.Series([0, 1, np.nan, 3]) 

6891 >>> s 

6892 0 0.0 

6893 1 1.0 

6894 2 NaN 

6895 3 3.0 

6896 dtype: float64 

6897 >>> s.interpolate() 

6898 0 0.0 

6899 1 1.0 

6900 2 2.0 

6901 3 3.0 

6902 dtype: float64 

6903 

6904 Filling in ``NaN`` in a Series by padding, but filling at most two 

6905 consecutive ``NaN`` at a time. 

6906 

6907 >>> s = pd.Series([np.nan, "single_one", np.nan, 

6908 ... "fill_two_more", np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, 

6909 ... 4.71, np.nan]) 

6910 >>> s 

6911 0 NaN 

6912 1 single_one 

6913 2 NaN 

6914 3 fill_two_more 

6915 4 NaN 

6916 5 NaN 

6917 6 NaN 

6918 7 4.71 

6919 8 NaN 

6920 dtype: object 

6921 >>> s.interpolate(method='pad', limit=2) 

6922 0 NaN 

6923 1 single_one 

6924 2 single_one 

6925 3 fill_two_more 

6926 4 fill_two_more 

6927 5 fill_two_more 

6928 6 NaN 

6929 7 4.71 

6930 8 4.71 

6931 dtype: object 

6932 

6933 Filling in ``NaN`` in a Series via polynomial interpolation or splines: 

6934 Both 'polynomial' and 'spline' methods require that you also specify 

6935 an ``order`` (int). 

6936 

6937 >>> s = pd.Series([0, 2, np.nan, 8]) 

6938 >>> s.interpolate(method='polynomial', order=2) 

6939 0 0.000000 

6940 1 2.000000 

6941 2 4.666667 

6942 3 8.000000 

6943 dtype: float64 

6944 

6945 Fill the DataFrame forward (that is, going down) along each column 

6946 using linear interpolation. 

6947 

6948 Note how the last entry in column 'a' is interpolated differently, 

6949 because there is no entry after it to use for interpolation. 

6950 Note how the first entry in column 'b' remains ``NaN``, because there 

6951 is no entry before it to use for interpolation. 

6952 

6953 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([(0.0, np.nan, -1.0, 1.0), 

6954 ... (np.nan, 2.0, np.nan, np.nan), 

6955 ... (2.0, 3.0, np.nan, 9.0), 

6956 ... (np.nan, 4.0, -4.0, 16.0)], 

6957 ... columns=list('abcd')) 

6958 >>> df 

6959 a b c d 

6960 0 0.0 NaN -1.0 1.0 

6961 1 NaN 2.0 NaN NaN 

6962 2 2.0 3.0 NaN 9.0 

6963 3 NaN 4.0 -4.0 16.0 

6964 >>> df.interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='forward', axis=0) 

6965 a b c d 

6966 0 0.0 NaN -1.0 1.0 

6967 1 1.0 2.0 -2.0 5.0 

6968 2 2.0 3.0 -3.0 9.0 

6969 3 2.0 4.0 -4.0 16.0 

6970 

6971 Using polynomial interpolation. 

6972 

6973 >>> df['d'].interpolate(method='polynomial', order=2) 

6974 0 1.0 

6975 1 4.0 

6976 2 9.0 

6977 3 16.0 

6978 Name: d, dtype: float64 

6979 """ 

6980 

6981 @Appender(_shared_docs["interpolate"] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

6982 def interpolate( 

6983 self, 

6984 method="linear", 

6985 axis=0, 

6986 limit=None, 

6987 inplace=False, 

6988 limit_direction="forward", 

6989 limit_area=None, 

6990 downcast=None, 

6991 **kwargs 

6992 ): 

6993 """ 

6994 Interpolate values according to different methods. 

6995 """ 

6996 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace") 

6997 

6998 if axis == 0: 

6999 ax = self._info_axis_name 

7000 _maybe_transposed_self = self 

7001 elif axis == 1: 

7002 _maybe_transposed_self = self.T 

7003 ax = 1 

7004 else: 

7005 _maybe_transposed_self = self 

7006 ax = _maybe_transposed_self._get_axis_number(ax) 

7007 

7008 if _maybe_transposed_self.ndim == 2: 

7009 alt_ax = 1 - ax 

7010 else: 

7011 alt_ax = ax 

7012 

7013 if isinstance(_maybe_transposed_self.index, MultiIndex) and method != "linear": 

7014 raise ValueError( 

7015 "Only `method=linear` interpolation is supported " "on MultiIndexes." 

7016 ) 

7017 

7018 if _maybe_transposed_self._data.get_dtype_counts().get("object") == len( 

7019 _maybe_transposed_self.T 

7020 ): 

7021 raise TypeError( 

7022 "Cannot interpolate with all object-dtype columns " 

7023 "in the DataFrame. Try setting at least one " 

7024 "column to a numeric dtype." 

7025 ) 

7026 

7027 # create/use the index 

7028 if method == "linear": 

7029 # prior default 

7030 index = np.arange(len(_maybe_transposed_self._get_axis(alt_ax))) 

7031 else: 

7032 index = _maybe_transposed_self._get_axis(alt_ax) 

7033 methods = {"index", "values", "nearest", "time"} 

7034 is_numeric_or_datetime = ( 

7035 is_numeric_dtype(index) 

7036 or is_datetime64_any_dtype(index) 

7037 or is_timedelta64_dtype(index) 

7038 ) 

7039 if method not in methods and not is_numeric_or_datetime: 

7040 raise ValueError( 

7041 "Index column must be numeric or datetime type when " 

7042 "using {method} method other than linear. " 

7043 "Try setting a numeric or datetime index column before " 

7044 "interpolating.".format(method=method) 

7045 ) 

7046 

7047 if isna(index).any(): 

7048 raise NotImplementedError( 

7049 "Interpolation with NaNs in the index " 

7050 "has not been implemented. Try filling " 

7051 "those NaNs before interpolating." 

7052 ) 

7053 data = _maybe_transposed_self._data 

7054 new_data = data.interpolate( 

7055 method=method, 

7056 axis=ax, 

7057 index=index, 

7058 values=_maybe_transposed_self, 

7059 limit=limit, 

7060 limit_direction=limit_direction, 

7061 limit_area=limit_area, 

7062 inplace=inplace, 

7063 downcast=downcast, 

7064 **kwargs 

7065 ) 

7066 

7067 if inplace: 

7068 if axis == 1: 

7069 new_data = self._constructor(new_data).T._data 

7070 self._update_inplace(new_data) 

7071 else: 

7072 res = self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self) 

7073 if axis == 1: 

7074 res = res.T 

7075 return res 

7076 

7077 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

7078 # Timeseries methods Methods 

7079 

7080 def asof(self, where, subset=None): 

7081 """ 

7082 Return the last row(s) without any NaNs before `where`. 

7083 

7084 The last row (for each element in `where`, if list) without any 

7085 NaN is taken. 

7086 In case of a :class:`~pandas.DataFrame`, the last row without NaN 

7087 considering only the subset of columns (if not `None`) 

7088 

7089 .. versionadded:: 0.19.0 For DataFrame 

7090 

7091 If there is no good value, NaN is returned for a Series or 

7092 a Series of NaN values for a DataFrame 

7093 

7094 Parameters 

7095 ---------- 

7096 where : date or array-like of dates 

7097 Date(s) before which the last row(s) are returned. 

7098 subset : str or array-like of str, default `None` 

7099 For DataFrame, if not `None`, only use these columns to 

7100 check for NaNs. 

7101 

7102 Returns 

7103 ------- 

7104 scalar, Series, or DataFrame 

7105 

7106 The return can be: 

7107 

7108 * scalar : when `self` is a Series and `where` is a scalar 

7109 * Series: when `self` is a Series and `where` is an array-like, 

7110 or when `self` is a DataFrame and `where` is a scalar 

7111 * DataFrame : when `self` is a DataFrame and `where` is an 

7112 array-like 

7113 

7114 Return scalar, Series, or DataFrame. 

7115 

7116 See Also 

7117 -------- 

7118 merge_asof : Perform an asof merge. Similar to left join. 

7119 

7120 Notes 

7121 ----- 

7122 Dates are assumed to be sorted. Raises if this is not the case. 

7123 

7124 Examples 

7125 -------- 

7126 A Series and a scalar `where`. 

7127 

7128 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, np.nan, 4], index=[10, 20, 30, 40]) 

7129 >>> s 

7130 10 1.0 

7131 20 2.0 

7132 30 NaN 

7133 40 4.0 

7134 dtype: float64 

7135 

7136 >>> s.asof(20) 

7137 2.0 

7138 

7139 For a sequence `where`, a Series is returned. The first value is 

7140 NaN, because the first element of `where` is before the first 

7141 index value. 

7142 

7143 >>> s.asof([5, 20]) 

7144 5 NaN 

7145 20 2.0 

7146 dtype: float64 

7147 

7148 Missing values are not considered. The following is ``2.0``, not 

7149 NaN, even though NaN is at the index location for ``30``. 

7150 

7151 >>> s.asof(30) 

7152 2.0 

7153 

7154 Take all columns into consideration 

7155 

7156 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'a': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50], 

7157 ... 'b': [None, None, None, None, 500]}, 

7158 ... index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:01:00', 

7159 ... '2018-02-27 09:02:00', 

7160 ... '2018-02-27 09:03:00', 

7161 ... '2018-02-27 09:04:00', 

7162 ... '2018-02-27 09:05:00'])) 

7163 >>> df.asof(pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:03:30', 

7164 ... '2018-02-27 09:04:30'])) 

7165 a b 

7166 2018-02-27 09:03:30 NaN NaN 

7167 2018-02-27 09:04:30 NaN NaN 

7168 

7169 Take a single column into consideration 

7170 

7171 >>> df.asof(pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:03:30', 

7172 ... '2018-02-27 09:04:30']), 

7173 ... subset=['a']) 

7174 a b 

7175 2018-02-27 09:03:30 30.0 NaN 

7176 2018-02-27 09:04:30 40.0 NaN 

7177 """ 

7178 if isinstance(where, str): 

7179 from pandas import to_datetime 

7180 

7181 where = to_datetime(where) 

7182 

7183 if not self.index.is_monotonic: 

7184 raise ValueError("asof requires a sorted index") 

7185 

7186 is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries) 

7187 if is_series: 

7188 if subset is not None: 

7189 raise ValueError("subset is not valid for Series") 

7190 else: 

7191 if subset is None: 

7192 subset = self.columns 

7193 if not is_list_like(subset): 

7194 subset = [subset] 

7195 

7196 is_list = is_list_like(where) 

7197 if not is_list: 

7198 start = self.index[0] 

7199 if isinstance(self.index, PeriodIndex): 

7200 where = Period(where, freq=self.index.freq).ordinal 

7201 start = start.ordinal 

7202 

7203 if where < start: 

7204 if not is_series: 

7205 from pandas import Series 

7206 

7207 return Series(index=self.columns, name=where) 

7208 return np.nan 

7209 

7210 # It's always much faster to use a *while* loop here for 

7211 # Series than pre-computing all the NAs. However a 

7212 # *while* loop is extremely expensive for DataFrame 

7213 # so we later pre-compute all the NAs and use the same 

7214 # code path whether *where* is a scalar or list. 

7215 # See PR: https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/14476 

7216 if is_series: 

7217 loc = self.index.searchsorted(where, side="right") 

7218 if loc > 0: 

7219 loc -= 1 

7220 

7221 values = self._values 

7222 while loc > 0 and isna(values[loc]): 

7223 loc -= 1 

7224 return values[loc] 

7225 

7226 if not isinstance(where, Index): 

7227 where = Index(where) if is_list else Index([where]) 

7228 

7229 nulls = self.isna() if is_series else self[subset].isna().any(1) 

7230 if nulls.all(): 

7231 if is_series: 

7232 return self._constructor(np.nan, index=where, name=self.name) 

7233 elif is_list: 

7234 from pandas import DataFrame 

7235 

7236 return DataFrame(np.nan, index=where, columns=self.columns) 

7237 else: 

7238 from pandas import Series 

7239 

7240 return Series(np.nan, index=self.columns, name=where[0]) 

7241 

7242 locs = self.index.asof_locs(where, ~(nulls.values)) 

7243 

7244 # mask the missing 

7245 missing = locs == -1 

7246 data = self.take(locs, is_copy=False) 

7247 data.index = where 

7248 data.loc[missing] = np.nan 

7249 return data if is_list else data.iloc[-1] 

7250

7254 _shared_docs[ 

7255 "isna" 

7256 ] = """ 

7257 Detect missing values. 

7258 

7259 Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are NA. 

7260 NA values, such as None or :attr:`numpy.NaN`, gets mapped to True 

7261 values. 

7262 Everything else gets mapped to False values. Characters such as empty 

7263 strings ``''`` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values 

7264 (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``). 

7265 

7266 Returns 

7267 ------- 

7268 %(klass)s 

7269 Mask of bool values for each element in %(klass)s that 

7270 indicates whether an element is not an NA value. 

7271 

7272 See Also 

7273 -------- 

7274 %(klass)s.isnull : Alias of isna. 

7275 %(klass)s.notna : Boolean inverse of isna. 

7276 %(klass)s.dropna : Omit axes labels with missing values. 

7277 isna : Top-level isna. 

7278 

7279 Examples 

7280 -------- 

7281 Show which entries in a DataFrame are NA. 

7282 

7283 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'age': [5, 6, np.NaN], 

7284 ... 'born': [pd.NaT, pd.Timestamp('1939-05-27'), 

7285 ... pd.Timestamp('1940-04-25')], 

7286 ... 'name': ['Alfred', 'Batman', ''], 

7287 ... 'toy': [None, 'Batmobile', 'Joker']}) 

7288 >>> df 

7289 age born name toy 

7290 0 5.0 NaT Alfred None 

7291 1 6.0 1939-05-27 Batman Batmobile 

7292 2 NaN 1940-04-25 Joker 

7293 

7294 >>> df.isna() 

7295 age born name toy 

7296 0 False True False True 

7297 1 False False False False 

7298 2 True False False False 

7299 

7300 Show which entries in a Series are NA. 

7301 

7302 >>> ser = pd.Series([5, 6, np.NaN]) 

7303 >>> ser 

7304 0 5.0 

7305 1 6.0 

7306 2 NaN 

7307 dtype: float64 

7308 

7309 >>> ser.isna() 

7310 0 False 

7311 1 False 

7312 2 True 

7313 dtype: bool 

7314 """

7387 def notna(self): 

7388 return notna(self).__finalize__(self)

7391 def notnull(self): 

7392 return notna(self).__finalize__(self) 

7393 

7394 def _clip_with_scalar(self, lower, upper, inplace=False): 

7395 if (lower is not None and np.any(isna(lower))) or ( 

7396 upper is not None and np.any(isna(upper)) 

7397 ): 

7398 raise ValueError("Cannot use an NA value as a clip threshold") 

7399 

7400 result = self 

7401 mask = isna(self.values) 

7402 

7403 with np.errstate(all="ignore"): 

7404 if upper is not None: 

7405 subset = self.to_numpy() <= upper 

7406 result = result.where(subset, upper, axis=None, inplace=False) 

7407 if lower is not None: 

7408 subset = self.to_numpy() >= lower 

7409 result = result.where(subset, lower, axis=None, inplace=False) 

7410 

7411 if np.any(mask): 

7412 result[mask] = np.nan 

7413 

7414 if inplace: 

7415 self._update_inplace(result) 

7416 else: 

7417 return result 

7418 

7419 def _clip_with_one_bound(self, threshold, method, axis, inplace): 

7420 

7421 if axis is not None: 

7422 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7423 

7424 # method is self.le for upper bound and self.ge for lower bound 

7425 if is_scalar(threshold) and is_number(threshold): 

7426 if method.__name__ == "le": 

7427 return self._clip_with_scalar(None, threshold, inplace=inplace) 

7428 return self._clip_with_scalar(threshold, None, inplace=inplace) 

7429 

7430 subset = method(threshold, axis=axis) | isna(self) 

7431 

7432 # GH #15390 

7433 # In order for where method to work, the threshold must 

7434 # be transformed to NDFrame from other array like structure. 

7435 if (not isinstance(threshold, ABCSeries)) and is_list_like(threshold): 

7436 if isinstance(self, ABCSeries): 

7437 threshold = pd.Series(threshold, index=self.index) 

7438 else: 

7439 threshold = _align_method_FRAME(self, threshold, axis) 

7440 return self.where(subset, threshold, axis=axis, inplace=inplace) 

7441 

7442 def clip(self, lower=None, upper=None, axis=None, inplace=False, *args, **kwargs): 

7443 """ 

7444 Trim values at input threshold(s). 

7445 

7446 Assigns values outside boundary to boundary values. Thresholds 

7447 can be singular values or array like, and in the latter case 

7448 the clipping is performed element-wise in the specified axis. 

7449 

7450 Parameters 

7451 ---------- 

7452 lower : float or array_like, default None 

7453 Minimum threshold value. All values below this 

7454 threshold will be set to it. 

7455 upper : float or array_like, default None 

7456 Maximum threshold value. All values above this 

7457 threshold will be set to it. 

7458 axis : int or str axis name, optional 

7459 Align object with lower and upper along the given axis. 

7460 inplace : bool, default False 

7461 Whether to perform the operation in place on the data. 

7462 

7463 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

7464 *args, **kwargs 

7465 Additional keywords have no effect but might be accepted 

7466 for compatibility with numpy. 

7467 

7468 Returns 

7469 ------- 

7470 Series or DataFrame 

7471 Same type as calling object with the values outside the 

7472 clip boundaries replaced. 

7473 

7474 Examples 

7475 -------- 

7476 >>> data = {'col_0': [9, -3, 0, -1, 5], 'col_1': [-2, -7, 6, 8, -5]} 

7477 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data) 

7478 >>> df 

7479 col_0 col_1 

7480 0 9 -2 

7481 1 -3 -7 

7482 2 0 6 

7483 3 -1 8 

7484 4 5 -5 

7485 

7486 Clips per column using lower and upper thresholds: 

7487 

7488 >>> df.clip(-4, 6) 

7489 col_0 col_1 

7490 0 6 -2 

7491 1 -3 -4 

7492 2 0 6 

7493 3 -1 6 

7494 4 5 -4 

7495 

7496 Clips using specific lower and upper thresholds per column element: 

7497 

7498 >>> t = pd.Series([2, -4, -1, 6, 3]) 

7499 >>> t 

7500 0 2 

7501 1 -4 

7502 2 -1 

7503 3 6 

7504 4 3 

7505 dtype: int64 

7506 

7507 >>> df.clip(t, t + 4, axis=0) 

7508 col_0 col_1 

7509 0 6 2 

7510 1 -3 -4 

7511 2 0 3 

7512 3 6 8 

7513 4 5 3 

7514 """ 

7515 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace") 

7516 

7517 axis = nv.validate_clip_with_axis(axis, args, kwargs) 

7518 if axis is not None: 

7519 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7520 

7521 # GH 17276 

7522 # numpy doesn't like NaN as a clip value 

7523 # so ignore 

7524 # GH 19992 

7525 # numpy doesn't drop a list-like bound containing NaN 

7526 if not is_list_like(lower) and np.any(pd.isnull(lower)): 

7527 lower = None 

7528 if not is_list_like(upper) and np.any(pd.isnull(upper)): 

7529 upper = None 

7530 

7531 # GH 2747 (arguments were reversed) 

7532 if lower is not None and upper is not None: 

7533 if is_scalar(lower) and is_scalar(upper): 

7534 lower, upper = min(lower, upper), max(lower, upper) 

7535 

7536 # fast-path for scalars 

7537 if (lower is None or (is_scalar(lower) and is_number(lower))) and ( 

7538 upper is None or (is_scalar(upper) and is_number(upper)) 

7539 ): 

7540 return self._clip_with_scalar(lower, upper, inplace=inplace) 

7541 

7542 result = self 

7543 if lower is not None: 

7544 result = result._clip_with_one_bound( 

7545 lower, method=self.ge, axis=axis, inplace=inplace 

7546 ) 

7547 if upper is not None: 

7548 if inplace: 

7549 result = self 

7550 result = result._clip_with_one_bound( 

7551 upper, method=self.le, axis=axis, inplace=inplace 

7552 ) 

7553 

7554 return result 

7555 

7556 def clip_upper(self, threshold, axis=None, inplace=False): 

7557 """ 

7558 Trim values above a given threshold. 

7559 

7560 .. deprecated:: 0.24.0 

7561 Use clip(upper=threshold) instead. 

7562 

7563 Elements above the `threshold` will be changed to match the 

7564 `threshold` value(s). Threshold can be a single value or an array, 

7565 in the latter case it performs the truncation element-wise. 

7566 

7567 Parameters 

7568 ---------- 

7569 threshold : numeric or array-like 

7570 Maximum value allowed. All values above threshold will be set to 

7571 this value. 

7572 

7573 * float : every value is compared to `threshold`. 

7574 * array-like : The shape of `threshold` should match the object 

7575 it's compared to. When `self` is a Series, `threshold` should be 

7576 the length. When `self` is a DataFrame, `threshold` should 2-D 

7577 and the same shape as `self` for ``axis=None``, or 1-D and the 

7578 same length as the axis being compared. 

7579 

7580 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7581 Align object with `threshold` along the given axis. 

7582 inplace : bool, default False 

7583 Whether to perform the operation in place on the data. 

7584 

7585 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

7586 

7587 Returns 

7588 ------- 

7589 Series or DataFrame 

7590 Original data with values trimmed. 

7591 

7592 See Also 

7593 -------- 

7594 Series.clip : General purpose method to trim Series values to given 

7595 threshold(s). 

7596 DataFrame.clip : General purpose method to trim DataFrame values to 

7597 given threshold(s). 

7598 

7599 Examples 

7600 -------- 

7601 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]) 

7602 >>> s 

7603 0 1 

7604 1 2 

7605 2 3 

7606 3 4 

7607 4 5 

7608 dtype: int64 

7609 

7610 >>> s.clip(upper=3) 

7611 0 1 

7612 1 2 

7613 2 3 

7614 3 3 

7615 4 3 

7616 dtype: int64 

7617 

7618 >>> elemwise_thresholds = [5, 4, 3, 2, 1] 

7619 >>> elemwise_thresholds 

7620 [5, 4, 3, 2, 1] 

7621 

7622 >>> s.clip(upper=elemwise_thresholds) 

7623 0 1 

7624 1 2 

7625 2 3 

7626 3 2 

7627 4 1 

7628 dtype: int64 

7629 """ 

7630 warnings.warn( 

7631 "clip_upper(threshold) is deprecated, " "use clip(upper=threshold) instead", 

7632 FutureWarning, 

7633 stacklevel=2, 

7634 ) 

7635 return self._clip_with_one_bound( 

7636 threshold, method=self.le, axis=axis, inplace=inplace 

7637 ) 

7638 

7639 def clip_lower(self, threshold, axis=None, inplace=False): 

7640 """ 

7641 Trim values below a given threshold. 

7642 

7643 .. deprecated:: 0.24.0 

7644 Use clip(lower=threshold) instead. 

7645 

7646 Elements below the `threshold` will be changed to match the 

7647 `threshold` value(s). Threshold can be a single value or an array, 

7648 in the latter case it performs the truncation element-wise. 

7649 

7650 Parameters 

7651 ---------- 

7652 threshold : numeric or array-like 

7653 Minimum value allowed. All values below threshold will be set to 

7654 this value. 

7655 

7656 * float : every value is compared to `threshold`. 

7657 * array-like : The shape of `threshold` should match the object 

7658 it's compared to. When `self` is a Series, `threshold` should be 

7659 the length. When `self` is a DataFrame, `threshold` should 2-D 

7660 and the same shape as `self` for ``axis=None``, or 1-D and the 

7661 same length as the axis being compared. 

7662 

7663 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7664 Align `self` with `threshold` along the given axis. 

7665 

7666 inplace : bool, default False 

7667 Whether to perform the operation in place on the data. 

7668 

7669 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

7670 

7671 Returns 

7672 ------- 

7673 Series or DataFrame 

7674 Original data with values trimmed. 

7675 

7676 See Also 

7677 -------- 

7678 Series.clip : General purpose method to trim Series values to given 

7679 threshold(s). 

7680 DataFrame.clip : General purpose method to trim DataFrame values to 

7681 given threshold(s). 

7682 

7683 Examples 

7684 -------- 

7685 

7686 Series single threshold clipping: 

7687 

7688 >>> s = pd.Series([5, 6, 7, 8, 9]) 

7689 >>> s.clip(lower=8) 

7690 0 8 

7691 1 8 

7692 2 8 

7693 3 8 

7694 4 9 

7695 dtype: int64 

7696 

7697 Series clipping element-wise using an array of thresholds. `threshold` 

7698 should be the same length as the Series. 

7699 

7700 >>> elemwise_thresholds = [4, 8, 7, 2, 5] 

7701 >>> s.clip(lower=elemwise_thresholds) 

7702 0 5 

7703 1 8 

7704 2 7 

7705 3 8 

7706 4 9 

7707 dtype: int64 

7708 

7709 DataFrames can be compared to a scalar. 

7710 

7711 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 3, 5], "B": [2, 4, 6]}) 

7712 >>> df 

7713 A B 

7714 0 1 2 

7715 1 3 4 

7716 2 5 6 

7717 

7718 >>> df.clip(lower=3) 

7719 A B 

7720 0 3 3 

7721 1 3 4 

7722 2 5 6 

7723 

7724 Or to an array of values. By default, `threshold` should be the same 

7725 shape as the DataFrame. 

7726 

7727 >>> df.clip(lower=np.array([[3, 4], [2, 2], [6, 2]])) 

7728 A B 

7729 0 3 4 

7730 1 3 4 

7731 2 6 6 

7732 

7733 Control how `threshold` is broadcast with `axis`. In this case 

7734 `threshold` should be the same length as the axis specified by 

7735 `axis`. 

7736 

7737 >>> df.clip(lower=[3, 3, 5], axis='index') 

7738 A B 

7739 0 3 3 

7740 1 3 4 

7741 2 5 6 

7742 

7743 >>> df.clip(lower=[4, 5], axis='columns') 

7744 A B 

7745 0 4 5 

7746 1 4 5 

7747 2 5 6 

7748 """ 

7749 warnings.warn( 

7750 "clip_lower(threshold) is deprecated, " "use clip(lower=threshold) instead", 

7751 FutureWarning, 

7752 stacklevel=2, 

7753 ) 

7754 return self._clip_with_one_bound( 

7755 threshold, method=self.ge, axis=axis, inplace=inplace 

7756 ) 

7757 

7758 def groupby( 

7759 self, 

7760 by=None, 

7761 axis=0, 

7762 level=None, 

7763 as_index=True, 

7764 sort=True, 

7765 group_keys=True, 

7766 squeeze=False, 

7767 observed=False, 

7768 **kwargs 

7769 ): 

7770 """ 

7771 Group DataFrame or Series using a mapper or by a Series of columns. 

7772 

7773 A groupby operation involves some combination of splitting the 

7774 object, applying a function, and combining the results. This can be 

7775 used to group large amounts of data and compute operations on these 

7776 groups. 

7777 

7778 Parameters 

7779 ---------- 

7780 by : mapping, function, label, or list of labels 

7781 Used to determine the groups for the groupby. 

7782 If ``by`` is a function, it's called on each value of the object's 

7783 index. If a dict or Series is passed, the Series or dict VALUES 

7784 will be used to determine the groups (the Series' values are first 

7785 aligned; see ``.align()`` method). If an ndarray is passed, the 

7786 values are used as-is determine the groups. A label or list of 

7787 labels may be passed to group by the columns in ``self``. Notice 

7788 that a tuple is interpreted as a (single) key. 

7789 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7790 Split along rows (0) or columns (1). 

7791 level : int, level name, or sequence of such, default None 

7792 If the axis is a MultiIndex (hierarchical), group by a particular 

7793 level or levels. 

7794 as_index : bool, default True 

7795 For aggregated output, return object with group labels as the 

7796 index. Only relevant for DataFrame input. as_index=False is 

7797 effectively "SQL-style" grouped output. 

7798 sort : bool, default True 

7799 Sort group keys. Get better performance by turning this off. 

7800 Note this does not influence the order of observations within each 

7801 group. Groupby preserves the order of rows within each group. 

7802 group_keys : bool, default True 

7803 When calling apply, add group keys to index to identify pieces. 

7804 squeeze : bool, default False 

7805 Reduce the dimensionality of the return type if possible, 

7806 otherwise return a consistent type. 

7807 observed : bool, default False 

7808 This only applies if any of the groupers are Categoricals. 

7809 If True: only show observed values for categorical groupers. 

7810 If False: show all values for categorical groupers. 

7811 

7812 .. versionadded:: 0.23.0 

7813 

7814 **kwargs 

7815 Optional, only accepts keyword argument 'mutated' and is passed 

7816 to groupby. 

7817 

7818 Returns 

7819 ------- 

7820 DataFrameGroupBy or SeriesGroupBy 

7821 Depends on the calling object and returns groupby object that 

7822 contains information about the groups. 

7823 

7824 See Also 

7825 -------- 

7826 resample : Convenience method for frequency conversion and resampling 

7827 of time series. 

7828 

7829 Notes 

7830 ----- 

7831 See the `user guide 

7832 <http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/groupby.html>`_ for more. 

7833 

7834 Examples 

7835 -------- 

7836 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'Animal': ['Falcon', 'Falcon', 

7837 ... 'Parrot', 'Parrot'], 

7838 ... 'Max Speed': [380., 370., 24., 26.]}) 

7839 >>> df 

7840 Animal Max Speed 

7841 0 Falcon 380.0 

7842 1 Falcon 370.0 

7843 2 Parrot 24.0 

7844 3 Parrot 26.0 

7845 >>> df.groupby(['Animal']).mean() 

7846 Max Speed 

7847 Animal 

7848 Falcon 375.0 

7849 Parrot 25.0 

7850 

7851 **Hierarchical Indexes** 

7852 

7853 We can groupby different levels of a hierarchical index 

7854 using the `level` parameter: 

7855 

7856 >>> arrays = [['Falcon', 'Falcon', 'Parrot', 'Parrot'], 

7857 ... ['Captive', 'Wild', 'Captive', 'Wild']] 

7858 >>> index = pd.MultiIndex.from_arrays(arrays, names=('Animal', 'Type')) 

7859 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'Max Speed': [390., 350., 30., 20.]}, 

7860 ... index=index) 

7861 >>> df 

7862 Max Speed 

7863 Animal Type 

7864 Falcon Captive 390.0 

7865 Wild 350.0 

7866 Parrot Captive 30.0 

7867 Wild 20.0 

7868 >>> df.groupby(level=0).mean() 

7869 Max Speed 

7870 Animal 

7871 Falcon 370.0 

7872 Parrot 25.0 

7873 >>> df.groupby(level=1).mean() 

7874 Max Speed 

7875 Type 

7876 Captive 210.0 

7877 Wild 185.0 

7878 """ 

7879 from pandas.core.groupby.groupby import groupby 

7880 

7881 if level is None and by is None: 

7882 raise TypeError("You have to supply one of 'by' and 'level'") 

7883 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7884 return groupby( 

7885 self, 

7886 by=by, 

7887 axis=axis, 

7888 level=level, 

7889 as_index=as_index, 

7890 sort=sort, 

7891 group_keys=group_keys, 

7892 squeeze=squeeze, 

7893 observed=observed, 

7894 **kwargs 

7895 ) 

7896 

7897 def asfreq(self, freq, method=None, how=None, normalize=False, fill_value=None): 

7898 """ 

7899 Convert TimeSeries to specified frequency. 

7900 

7901 Optionally provide filling method to pad/backfill missing values. 

7902 

7903 Returns the original data conformed to a new index with the specified 

7904 frequency. ``resample`` is more appropriate if an operation, such as 

7905 summarization, is necessary to represent the data at the new frequency. 

7906 

7907 Parameters 

7908 ---------- 

7909 freq : DateOffset object, or string 

7910 method : {'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill'}, default None 

7911 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed Series (note this 

7912 does not fill NaNs that already were present): 

7913 

7914 * 'pad' / 'ffill': propagate last valid observation forward to next 

7915 valid 

7916 * 'backfill' / 'bfill': use NEXT valid observation to fill 

7917 how : {'start', 'end'}, default end 

7918 For PeriodIndex only, see PeriodIndex.asfreq 

7919 normalize : bool, default False 

7920 Whether to reset output index to midnight 

7921 fill_value : scalar, optional 

7922 Value to use for missing values, applied during upsampling (note 

7923 this does not fill NaNs that already were present). 

7924 

7925 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

7926 

7927 Returns 

7928 ------- 

7929 converted : same type as caller 

7930 

7931 See Also 

7932 -------- 

7933 reindex 

7934 

7935 Notes 

7936 ----- 

7937 To learn more about the frequency strings, please see `this link 

7938 <http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/timeseries.html#offset-aliases>`__. 

7939 

7940 Examples 

7941 -------- 

7942 

7943 Start by creating a series with 4 one minute timestamps. 

7944 

7945 >>> index = pd.date_range('1/1/2000', periods=4, freq='T') 

7946 >>> series = pd.Series([0.0, None, 2.0, 3.0], index=index) 

7947 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'s':series}) 

7948 >>> df 

7949 s 

7950 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

7951 2000-01-01 00:01:00 NaN 

7952 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

7953 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3.0 

7954 

7955 Upsample the series into 30 second bins. 

7956 

7957 >>> df.asfreq(freq='30S') 

7958 s 

7959 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

7960 2000-01-01 00:00:30 NaN 

7961 2000-01-01 00:01:00 NaN 

7962 2000-01-01 00:01:30 NaN 

7963 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

7964 2000-01-01 00:02:30 NaN 

7965 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3.0 

7966 

7967 Upsample again, providing a ``fill value``. 

7968 

7969 >>> df.asfreq(freq='30S', fill_value=9.0) 

7970 s 

7971 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

7972 2000-01-01 00:00:30 9.0 

7973 2000-01-01 00:01:00 NaN 

7974 2000-01-01 00:01:30 9.0 

7975 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

7976 2000-01-01 00:02:30 9.0 

7977 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3.0 

7978 

7979 Upsample again, providing a ``method``. 

7980 

7981 >>> df.asfreq(freq='30S', method='bfill') 

7982 s 

7983 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

7984 2000-01-01 00:00:30 NaN 

7985 2000-01-01 00:01:00 NaN 

7986 2000-01-01 00:01:30 2.0 

7987 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

7988 2000-01-01 00:02:30 3.0 

7989 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3.0 

7990 """ 

7991 from pandas.core.resample import asfreq 

7992 

7993 return asfreq( 

7994 self, 

7995 freq, 

7996 method=method, 

7997 how=how, 

7998 normalize=normalize, 

7999 fill_value=fill_value, 

8000 ) 

8001 

8002 def at_time(self, time, asof=False, axis=None): 

8003 """ 

8004 Select values at particular time of day (e.g. 9:30AM). 

8005 

8006 Parameters 

8007 ---------- 

8008 time : datetime.time or str 

8009 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

8010 

8011 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

8012 

8013 Returns 

8014 ------- 

8015 Series or DataFrame 

8016 

8017 Raises 

8018 ------ 

8019 TypeError 

8020 If the index is not a :class:`DatetimeIndex` 

8021 

8022 See Also 

8023 -------- 

8024 between_time : Select values between particular times of the day. 

8025 first : Select initial periods of time series based on a date offset. 

8026 last : Select final periods of time series based on a date offset. 

8027 DatetimeIndex.indexer_at_time : Get just the index locations for 

8028 values at particular time of the day. 

8029 

8030 Examples 

8031 -------- 

8032 >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='12H') 

8033 >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3, 4]}, index=i) 

8034 >>> ts 

8035 A 

8036 2018-04-09 00:00:00 1 

8037 2018-04-09 12:00:00 2 

8038 2018-04-10 00:00:00 3 

8039 2018-04-10 12:00:00 4 

8040 

8041 >>> ts.at_time('12:00') 

8042 A 

8043 2018-04-09 12:00:00 2 

8044 2018-04-10 12:00:00 4 

8045 """ 

8046 if axis is None: 

8047 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

8048 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

8049 

8050 index = self._get_axis(axis) 

8051 try: 

8052 indexer = index.indexer_at_time(time, asof=asof) 

8053 except AttributeError: 

8054 raise TypeError("Index must be DatetimeIndex") 

8055 

8056 return self.take(indexer, axis=axis) 

8057 

8058 def between_time( 

8059 self, start_time, end_time, include_start=True, include_end=True, axis=None 

8060 ): 

8061 """ 

8062 Select values between particular times of the day (e.g., 9:00-9:30 AM). 

8063 

8064 By setting ``start_time`` to be later than ``end_time``, 

8065 you can get the times that are *not* between the two times. 

8066 

8067 Parameters 

8068 ---------- 

8069 start_time : datetime.time or str 

8070 end_time : datetime.time or str 

8071 include_start : bool, default True 

8072 include_end : bool, default True 

8073 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

8074 

8075 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

8076 

8077 Returns 

8078 ------- 

8079 Series or DataFrame 

8080 

8081 Raises 

8082 ------ 

8083 TypeError 

8084 If the index is not a :class:`DatetimeIndex` 

8085 

8086 See Also 

8087 -------- 

8088 at_time : Select values at a particular time of the day. 

8089 first : Select initial periods of time series based on a date offset. 

8090 last : Select final periods of time series based on a date offset. 

8091 DatetimeIndex.indexer_between_time : Get just the index locations for 

8092 values between particular times of the day. 

8093 

8094 Examples 

8095 -------- 

8096 >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='1D20min') 

8097 >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3, 4]}, index=i) 

8098 >>> ts 

8099 A 

8100 2018-04-09 00:00:00 1 

8101 2018-04-10 00:20:00 2 

8102 2018-04-11 00:40:00 3 

8103 2018-04-12 01:00:00 4 

8104 

8105 >>> ts.between_time('0:15', '0:45') 

8106 A 

8107 2018-04-10 00:20:00 2 

8108 2018-04-11 00:40:00 3 

8109 

8110 You get the times that are *not* between two times by setting 

8111 ``start_time`` later than ``end_time``: 

8112 

8113 >>> ts.between_time('0:45', '0:15') 

8114 A 

8115 2018-04-09 00:00:00 1 

8116 2018-04-12 01:00:00 4 

8117 """ 

8118 if axis is None: 

8119 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

8120 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

8121 

8122 index = self._get_axis(axis) 

8123 try: 

8124 indexer = index.indexer_between_time( 

8125 start_time, 

8126 end_time, 

8127 include_start=include_start, 

8128 include_end=include_end, 

8129 ) 

8130 except AttributeError: 

8131 raise TypeError("Index must be DatetimeIndex") 

8132 

8133 return self.take(indexer, axis=axis) 

8134 

8135 def resample( 

8136 self, 

8137 rule, 

8138 how=None, 

8139 axis=0, 

8140 fill_method=None, 

8141 closed=None, 

8142 label=None, 

8143 convention="start", 

8144 kind=None, 

8145 loffset=None, 

8146 limit=None, 

8147 base=0, 

8148 on=None, 

8149 level=None, 

8150 ): 

8151 """ 

8152 Resample time-series data. 

8153 

8154 Convenience method for frequency conversion and resampling of time 

8155 series. Object must have a datetime-like index (`DatetimeIndex`, 

8156 `PeriodIndex`, or `TimedeltaIndex`), or pass datetime-like values 

8157 to the `on` or `level` keyword. 

8158 

8159 Parameters 

8160 ---------- 

8161 rule : DateOffset, Timedelta or str 

8162 The offset string or object representing target conversion. 

8163 how : str 

8164 Method for down/re-sampling, default to 'mean' for downsampling. 

8165 

8166 .. deprecated:: 0.18.0 

8167 The new syntax is ``.resample(...).mean()``, or 

8168 ``.resample(...).apply(<func>)`` 

8169 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

8170 Which axis to use for up- or down-sampling. For `Series` this 

8171 will default to 0, i.e. along the rows. Must be 

8172 `DatetimeIndex`, `TimedeltaIndex` or `PeriodIndex`. 

8173 fill_method : str, default None 

8174 Filling method for upsampling. 

8175 

8176 .. deprecated:: 0.18.0 

8177 The new syntax is ``.resample(...).<func>()``, 

8178 e.g. ``.resample(...).pad()`` 

8179 closed : {'right', 'left'}, default None 

8180 Which side of bin interval is closed. The default is 'left' 

8181 for all frequency offsets except for 'M', 'A', 'Q', 'BM', 

8182 'BA', 'BQ', and 'W' which all have a default of 'right'. 

8183 label : {'right', 'left'}, default None 

8184 Which bin edge label to label bucket with. The default is 'left' 

8185 for all frequency offsets except for 'M', 'A', 'Q', 'BM', 

8186 'BA', 'BQ', and 'W' which all have a default of 'right'. 

8187 convention : {'start', 'end', 's', 'e'}, default 'start' 

8188 For `PeriodIndex` only, controls whether to use the start or 

8189 end of `rule`. 

8190 kind : {'timestamp', 'period'}, optional, default None 

8191 Pass 'timestamp' to convert the resulting index to a 

8192 `DateTimeIndex` or 'period' to convert it to a `PeriodIndex`. 

8193 By default the input representation is retained. 

8194 loffset : timedelta, default None 

8195 Adjust the resampled time labels. 

8196 limit : int, default None 

8197 Maximum size gap when reindexing with `fill_method`. 

8198 

8199 .. deprecated:: 0.18.0 

8200 base : int, default 0 

8201 For frequencies that evenly subdivide 1 day, the "origin" of the 

8202 aggregated intervals. For example, for '5min' frequency, base could 

8203 range from 0 through 4. Defaults to 0. 

8204 on : str, optional 

8205 For a DataFrame, column to use instead of index for resampling. 

8206 Column must be datetime-like. 

8207 

8208 .. versionadded:: 0.19.0 

8209 

8210 level : str or int, optional 

8211 For a MultiIndex, level (name or number) to use for 

8212 resampling. `level` must be datetime-like. 

8213 

8214 .. versionadded:: 0.19.0 

8215 

8216 Returns 

8217 ------- 

8218 Resampler object 

8219 

8220 See Also 

8221 -------- 

8222 groupby : Group by mapping, function, label, or list of labels. 

8223 Series.resample : Resample a Series. 

8224 DataFrame.resample: Resample a DataFrame. 

8225 

8226 Notes 

8227 ----- 

8228 See the `user guide 

8229 <https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/timeseries.html#resampling>`_ 

8230 for more. 

8231 

8232 To learn more about the offset strings, please see `this link 

8233 <http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/timeseries.html#dateoffset-objects>`__. 

8234 

8235 Examples 

8236 -------- 

8237 

8238 Start by creating a series with 9 one minute timestamps. 

8239 

8240 >>> index = pd.date_range('1/1/2000', periods=9, freq='T') 

8241 >>> series = pd.Series(range(9), index=index) 

8242 >>> series 

8243 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0 

8244 2000-01-01 00:01:00 1 

8245 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2 

8246 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3 

8247 2000-01-01 00:04:00 4 

8248 2000-01-01 00:05:00 5 

8249 2000-01-01 00:06:00 6 

8250 2000-01-01 00:07:00 7 

8251 2000-01-01 00:08:00 8 

8252 Freq: T, dtype: int64 

8253 

8254 Downsample the series into 3 minute bins and sum the values 

8255 of the timestamps falling into a bin. 

8256 

8257 >>> series.resample('3T').sum() 

8258 2000-01-01 00:00:00 3 

8259 2000-01-01 00:03:00 12 

8260 2000-01-01 00:06:00 21 

8261 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64 

8262 

8263 Downsample the series into 3 minute bins as above, but label each 

8264 bin using the right edge instead of the left. Please note that the 

8265 value in the bucket used as the label is not included in the bucket, 

8266 which it labels. For example, in the original series the 

8267 bucket ``2000-01-01 00:03:00`` contains the value 3, but the summed 

8268 value in the resampled bucket with the label ``2000-01-01 00:03:00`` 

8269 does not include 3 (if it did, the summed value would be 6, not 3). 

8270 To include this value close the right side of the bin interval as 

8271 illustrated in the example below this one. 

8272 

8273 >>> series.resample('3T', label='right').sum() 

8274 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3 

8275 2000-01-01 00:06:00 12 

8276 2000-01-01 00:09:00 21 

8277 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64 

8278 

8279 Downsample the series into 3 minute bins as above, but close the right 

8280 side of the bin interval. 

8281 

8282 >>> series.resample('3T', label='right', closed='right').sum() 

8283 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0 

8284 2000-01-01 00:03:00 6 

8285 2000-01-01 00:06:00 15 

8286 2000-01-01 00:09:00 15 

8287 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64 

8288 

8289 Upsample the series into 30 second bins. 

8290 

8291 >>> series.resample('30S').asfreq()[0:5] # Select first 5 rows 

8292 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

8293 2000-01-01 00:00:30 NaN 

8294 2000-01-01 00:01:00 1.0 

8295 2000-01-01 00:01:30 NaN 

8296 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

8297 Freq: 30S, dtype: float64 

8298 

8299 Upsample the series into 30 second bins and fill the ``NaN`` 

8300 values using the ``pad`` method. 

8301 

8302 >>> series.resample('30S').pad()[0:5] 

8303 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0 

8304 2000-01-01 00:00:30 0 

8305 2000-01-01 00:01:00 1 

8306 2000-01-01 00:01:30 1 

8307 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2 

8308 Freq: 30S, dtype: int64 

8309 

8310 Upsample the series into 30 second bins and fill the 

8311 ``NaN`` values using the ``bfill`` method. 

8312 

8313 >>> series.resample('30S').bfill()[0:5] 

8314 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0 

8315 2000-01-01 00:00:30 1 

8316 2000-01-01 00:01:00 1 

8317 2000-01-01 00:01:30 2 

8318 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2 

8319 Freq: 30S, dtype: int64 

8320 

8321 Pass a custom function via ``apply`` 

8322 

8323 >>> def custom_resampler(array_like): 

8324 ... return np.sum(array_like) + 5 

8325 ... 

8326 >>> series.resample('3T').apply(custom_resampler) 

8327 2000-01-01 00:00:00 8 

8328 2000-01-01 00:03:00 17 

8329 2000-01-01 00:06:00 26 

8330 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64 

8331 

8332 For a Series with a PeriodIndex, the keyword `convention` can be 

8333 used to control whether to use the start or end of `rule`. 

8334 

8335 Resample a year by quarter using 'start' `convention`. Values are 

8336 assigned to the first quarter of the period. 

8337 

8338 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=pd.period_range('2012-01-01', 

8339 ... freq='A', 

8340 ... periods=2)) 

8341 >>> s 

8342 2012 1 

8343 2013 2 

8344 Freq: A-DEC, dtype: int64 

8345 >>> s.resample('Q', convention='start').asfreq() 

8346 2012Q1 1.0 

8347 2012Q2 NaN 

8348 2012Q3 NaN 

8349 2012Q4 NaN 

8350 2013Q1 2.0 

8351 2013Q2 NaN 

8352 2013Q3 NaN 

8353 2013Q4 NaN 

8354 Freq: Q-DEC, dtype: float64 

8355 

8356 Resample quarters by month using 'end' `convention`. Values are 

8357 assigned to the last month of the period. 

8358 

8359 >>> q = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4], index=pd.period_range('2018-01-01', 

8360 ... freq='Q', 

8361 ... periods=4)) 

8362 >>> q 

8363 2018Q1 1 

8364 2018Q2 2 

8365 2018Q3 3 

8366 2018Q4 4 

8367 Freq: Q-DEC, dtype: int64 

8368 >>> q.resample('M', convention='end').asfreq() 

8369 2018-03 1.0 

8370 2018-04 NaN 

8371 2018-05 NaN 

8372 2018-06 2.0 

8373 2018-07 NaN 

8374 2018-08 NaN 

8375 2018-09 3.0 

8376 2018-10 NaN 

8377 2018-11 NaN 

8378 2018-12 4.0 

8379 Freq: M, dtype: float64 

8380 

8381 For DataFrame objects, the keyword `on` can be used to specify the 

8382 column instead of the index for resampling. 

8383 

8384 >>> d = dict({'price': [10, 11, 9, 13, 14, 18, 17, 19], 

8385 ... 'volume': [50, 60, 40, 100, 50, 100, 40, 50]}) 

8386 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(d) 

8387 >>> df['week_starting'] = pd.date_range('01/01/2018', 

8388 ... periods=8, 

8389 ... freq='W') 

8390 >>> df 

8391 price volume week_starting 

8392 0 10 50 2018-01-07 

8393 1 11 60 2018-01-14 

8394 2 9 40 2018-01-21 

8395 3 13 100 2018-01-28 

8396 4 14 50 2018-02-04 

8397 5 18 100 2018-02-11 

8398 6 17 40 2018-02-18 

8399 7 19 50 2018-02-25 

8400 >>> df.resample('M', on='week_starting').mean() 

8401 price volume 

8402 week_starting 

8403 2018-01-31 10.75 62.5 

8404 2018-02-28 17.00 60.0 

8405 

8406 For a DataFrame with MultiIndex, the keyword `level` can be used to 

8407 specify on which level the resampling needs to take place. 

8408 

8409 >>> days = pd.date_range('1/1/2000', periods=4, freq='D') 

8410 >>> d2 = dict({'price': [10, 11, 9, 13, 14, 18, 17, 19], 

8411 ... 'volume': [50, 60, 40, 100, 50, 100, 40, 50]}) 

8412 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame(d2, 

8413 ... index=pd.MultiIndex.from_product([days, 

8414 ... ['morning', 

8415 ... 'afternoon']] 

8416 ... )) 

8417 >>> df2 

8418 price volume 

8419 2000-01-01 morning 10 50 

8420 afternoon 11 60 

8421 2000-01-02 morning 9 40 

8422 afternoon 13 100 

8423 2000-01-03 morning 14 50 

8424 afternoon 18 100 

8425 2000-01-04 morning 17 40 

8426 afternoon 19 50 

8427 >>> df2.resample('D', level=0).sum() 

8428 price volume 

8429 2000-01-01 21 110 

8430 2000-01-02 22 140 

8431 2000-01-03 32 150 

8432 2000-01-04 36 90 

8433 """ 

8434 

8435 from pandas.core.resample import resample, _maybe_process_deprecations 

8436 

8437 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

8438 r = resample( 

8439 self, 

8440 freq=rule, 

8441 label=label, 

8442 closed=closed, 

8443 axis=axis, 

8444 kind=kind, 

8445 loffset=loffset, 

8446 convention=convention, 

8447 base=base, 

8448 key=on, 

8449 level=level, 

8450 ) 

8451 return _maybe_process_deprecations( 

8452 r, how=how, fill_method=fill_method, limit=limit 

8453 ) 

8454 

8455 def first(self, offset): 

8456 """ 

8457 Convenience method for subsetting initial periods of time series data 

8458 based on a date offset. 

8459 

8460 Parameters 

8461 ---------- 

8462 offset : string, DateOffset, dateutil.relativedelta 

8463 

8464 Returns 

8465 ------- 

8466 subset : same type as caller 

8467 

8468 Raises 

8469 ------ 

8470 TypeError 

8471 If the index is not a :class:`DatetimeIndex` 

8472 

8473 See Also 

8474 -------- 

8475 last : Select final periods of time series based on a date offset. 

8476 at_time : Select values at a particular time of the day. 

8477 between_time : Select values between particular times of the day. 

8478 

8479 Examples 

8480 -------- 

8481 >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='2D') 

8482 >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1,2,3,4]}, index=i) 

8483 >>> ts 

8484 A 

8485 2018-04-09 1 

8486 2018-04-11 2 

8487 2018-04-13 3 

8488 2018-04-15 4 

8489 

8490 Get the rows for the first 3 days: 

8491 

8492 >>> ts.first('3D') 

8493 A 

8494 2018-04-09 1 

8495 2018-04-11 2 

8496 

8497 Notice the data for 3 first calender days were returned, not the first 

8498 3 days observed in the dataset, and therefore data for 2018-04-13 was 

8499 not returned. 

8500 """ 

8501 if not isinstance(self.index, DatetimeIndex): 

8502 raise TypeError("'first' only supports a DatetimeIndex index") 

8503 

8504 if len(self.index) == 0: 

8505 return self 

8506 

8507 offset = to_offset(offset) 

8508 end_date = end = self.index[0] + offset 

8509 

8510 # Tick-like, e.g. 3 weeks 

8511 if not offset.isAnchored() and hasattr(offset, "_inc"): 

8512 if end_date in self.index: 

8513 end = self.index.searchsorted(end_date, side="left") 

8514 return self.iloc[:end] 

8515 

8516 return self.loc[:end] 

8517 

8518 def last(self, offset): 

8519 """ 

8520 Convenience method for subsetting final periods of time series data 

8521 based on a date offset. 

8522 

8523 Parameters 

8524 ---------- 

8525 offset : string, DateOffset, dateutil.relativedelta 

8526 

8527 Returns 

8528 ------- 

8529 subset : same type as caller 

8530 

8531 Raises 

8532 ------ 

8533 TypeError 

8534 If the index is not a :class:`DatetimeIndex` 

8535 

8536 See Also 

8537 -------- 

8538 first : Select initial periods of time series based on a date offset. 

8539 at_time : Select values at a particular time of the day. 

8540 between_time : Select values between particular times of the day. 

8541 

8542 Examples 

8543 -------- 

8544 >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='2D') 

8545 >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1,2,3,4]}, index=i) 

8546 >>> ts 

8547 A 

8548 2018-04-09 1 

8549 2018-04-11 2 

8550 2018-04-13 3 

8551 2018-04-15 4 

8552 

8553 Get the rows for the last 3 days: 

8554 

8555 >>> ts.last('3D') 

8556 A 

8557 2018-04-13 3 

8558 2018-04-15 4 

8559 

8560 Notice the data for 3 last calender days were returned, not the last 

8561 3 observed days in the dataset, and therefore data for 2018-04-11 was 

8562 not returned. 

8563 """ 

8564 if not isinstance(self.index, DatetimeIndex): 

8565 raise TypeError("'last' only supports a DatetimeIndex index") 

8566 

8567 if len(self.index) == 0: 

8568 return self 

8569 

8570 offset = to_offset(offset) 

8571 

8572 start_date = self.index[-1] - offset 

8573 start = self.index.searchsorted(start_date, side="right") 

8574 return self.iloc[start:] 

8575 

8576 def rank( 

8577 self, 

8578 axis=0, 

8579 method="average", 

8580 numeric_only=None, 

8581 na_option="keep", 

8582 ascending=True, 

8583 pct=False, 

8584 ): 

8585 """ 

8586 Compute numerical data ranks (1 through n) along axis. 

8587 

8588 By default, equal values are assigned a rank that is the average of the 

8589 ranks of those values. 

8590 

8591 Parameters 

8592 ---------- 

8593 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

8594 Index to direct ranking. 

8595 method : {'average', 'min', 'max', 'first', 'dense'}, default 'average' 

8596 How to rank the group of records that have the same value 

8597 (i.e. ties): 

8598 

8599 * average: average rank of the group 

8600 * min: lowest rank in the group 

8601 * max: highest rank in the group 

8602 * first: ranks assigned in order they appear in the array 

8603 * dense: like 'min', but rank always increases by 1 between groups 

8604 numeric_only : bool, optional 

8605 For DataFrame objects, rank only numeric columns if set to True. 

8606 na_option : {'keep', 'top', 'bottom'}, default 'keep' 

8607 How to rank NaN values: 

8608 

8609 * keep: assign NaN rank to NaN values 

8610 * top: assign smallest rank to NaN values if ascending 

8611 * bottom: assign highest rank to NaN values if ascending 

8612 ascending : bool, default True 

8613 Whether or not the elements should be ranked in ascending order. 

8614 pct : bool, default False 

8615 Whether or not to display the returned rankings in percentile 

8616 form. 

8617 

8618 Returns 

8619 ------- 

8620 same type as caller 

8621 Return a Series or DataFrame with data ranks as values. 

8622 

8623 See Also 

8624 -------- 

8625 core.groupby.GroupBy.rank : Rank of values within each group. 

8626 

8627 Examples 

8628 -------- 

8629 

8630 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data={'Animal': ['cat', 'penguin', 'dog', 

8631 ... 'spider', 'snake'], 

8632 ... 'Number_legs': [4, 2, 4, 8, np.nan]}) 

8633 >>> df 

8634 Animal Number_legs 

8635 0 cat 4.0 

8636 1 penguin 2.0 

8637 2 dog 4.0 

8638 3 spider 8.0 

8639 4 snake NaN 

8640 

8641 The following example shows how the method behaves with the above 

8642 parameters: 

8643 

8644 * default_rank: this is the default behaviour obtained without using 

8645 any parameter. 

8646 * max_rank: setting ``method = 'max'`` the records that have the 

8647 same values are ranked using the highest rank (e.g.: since 'cat' 

8648 and 'dog' are both in the 2nd and 3rd position, rank 3 is assigned.) 

8649 * NA_bottom: choosing ``na_option = 'bottom'``, if there are records 

8650 with NaN values they are placed at the bottom of the ranking. 

8651 * pct_rank: when setting ``pct = True``, the ranking is expressed as 

8652 percentile rank. 

8653 

8654 >>> df['default_rank'] = df['Number_legs'].rank() 

8655 >>> df['max_rank'] = df['Number_legs'].rank(method='max') 

8656 >>> df['NA_bottom'] = df['Number_legs'].rank(na_option='bottom') 

8657 >>> df['pct_rank'] = df['Number_legs'].rank(pct=True) 

8658 >>> df 

8659 Animal Number_legs default_rank max_rank NA_bottom pct_rank 

8660 0 cat 4.0 2.5 3.0 2.5 0.625 

8661 1 penguin 2.0 1.0 1.0 1.0 0.250 

8662 2 dog 4.0 2.5 3.0 2.5 0.625 

8663 3 spider 8.0 4.0 4.0 4.0 1.000 

8664 4 snake NaN NaN NaN 5.0 NaN 

8665 """ 

8666 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

8667 

8668 if na_option not in {"keep", "top", "bottom"}: 

8669 msg = "na_option must be one of 'keep', 'top', or 'bottom'" 

8670 raise ValueError(msg) 

8671 

8672 def ranker(data): 

8673 ranks = algos.rank( 

8674 data.values, 

8675 axis=axis, 

8676 method=method, 

8677 ascending=ascending, 

8678 na_option=na_option, 

8679 pct=pct, 

8680 ) 

8681 ranks = self._constructor(ranks, **data._construct_axes_dict()) 

8682 return ranks.__finalize__(self) 

8683 

8684 # if numeric_only is None, and we can't get anything, we try with 

8685 # numeric_only=True 

8686 if numeric_only is None: 

8687 try: 

8688 return ranker(self) 

8689 except TypeError: 

8690 numeric_only = True 

8691 

8692 if numeric_only: 

8693 data = self._get_numeric_data() 

8694 else: 

8695 data = self 

8696 

8697 return ranker(data) 

8698 

8699 _shared_docs[ 

8700 "align" 

8701 ] = """ 

8702 Align two objects on their axes with the 

8703 specified join method for each axis Index. 

8704 

8705 Parameters 

8706 ---------- 

8707 other : DataFrame or Series 

8708 join : {'outer', 'inner', 'left', 'right'}, default 'outer' 

8709 axis : allowed axis of the other object, default None 

8710 Align on index (0), columns (1), or both (None) 

8711 level : int or level name, default None 

8712 Broadcast across a level, matching Index values on the 

8713 passed MultiIndex level 

8714 copy : boolean, default True 

8715 Always returns new objects. If copy=False and no reindexing is 

8716 required then original objects are returned. 

8717 fill_value : scalar, default np.NaN 

8718 Value to use for missing values. Defaults to NaN, but can be any 

8719 "compatible" value 

8720 method : {'backfill', 'bfill', 'pad', 'ffill', None}, default None 

8721 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed Series 

8722 pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next valid 

8723 backfill / bfill: use NEXT valid observation to fill gap 

8724 limit : int, default None 

8725 If method is specified, this is the maximum number of consecutive 

8726 NaN values to forward/backward fill. In other words, if there is 

8727 a gap with more than this number of consecutive NaNs, it will only 

8728 be partially filled. If method is not specified, this is the 

8729 maximum number of entries along the entire axis where NaNs will be 

8730 filled. Must be greater than 0 if not None. 

8731 fill_axis : %(axes_single_arg)s, default 0 

8732 Filling axis, method and limit 

8733 broadcast_axis : %(axes_single_arg)s, default None 

8734 Broadcast values along this axis, if aligning two objects of 

8735 different dimensions 

8736 

8737 Returns 

8738 ------- 

8739 (left, right) : (%(klass)s, type of other) 

8740 Aligned objects. 

8741 """ 

8742 

8743 @Appender(_shared_docs["align"] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

8744 def align( 

8745 self, 

8746 other, 

8747 join="outer", 

8748 axis=None, 

8749 level=None, 

8750 copy=True, 

8751 fill_value=None, 

8752 method=None, 

8753 limit=None, 

8754 fill_axis=0, 

8755 broadcast_axis=None, 

8756 ): 

8757 from pandas import DataFrame, Series 

8758 

8759 method = missing.clean_fill_method(method) 

8760 

8761 if broadcast_axis == 1 and self.ndim != other.ndim: 

8762 if isinstance(self, Series): 

8763 # this means other is a DataFrame, and we need to broadcast 

8764 # self 

8765 cons = self._constructor_expanddim 

8766 df = cons( 

8767 {c: self for c in other.columns}, **other._construct_axes_dict() 

8768 ) 

8769 return df._align_frame( 

8770 other, 

8771 join=join, 

8772 axis=axis, 

8773 level=level, 

8774 copy=copy, 

8775 fill_value=fill_value, 

8776 method=method, 

8777 limit=limit, 

8778 fill_axis=fill_axis, 

8779 ) 

8780 elif isinstance(other, Series): 

8781 # this means self is a DataFrame, and we need to broadcast 

8782 # other 

8783 cons = other._constructor_expanddim 

8784 df = cons( 

8785 {c: other for c in self.columns}, **self._construct_axes_dict() 

8786 ) 

8787 return self._align_frame( 

8788 df, 

8789 join=join, 

8790 axis=axis, 

8791 level=level, 

8792 copy=copy, 

8793 fill_value=fill_value, 

8794 method=method, 

8795 limit=limit, 

8796 fill_axis=fill_axis, 

8797 ) 

8798 

8799 if axis is not None: 

8800 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

8801 if isinstance(other, DataFrame): 

8802 return self._align_frame( 

8803 other, 

8804 join=join, 

8805 axis=axis, 

8806 level=level, 

8807 copy=copy, 

8808 fill_value=fill_value, 

8809 method=method, 

8810 limit=limit, 

8811 fill_axis=fill_axis, 

8812 ) 

8813 elif isinstance(other, Series): 

8814 return self._align_series( 

8815 other, 

8816 join=join, 

8817 axis=axis, 

8818 level=level, 

8819 copy=copy, 

8820 fill_value=fill_value, 

8821 method=method, 

8822 limit=limit, 

8823 fill_axis=fill_axis, 

8824 ) 

8825 else: # pragma: no cover 

8826 raise TypeError("unsupported type: %s" % type(other)) 

8827 

8828 def _align_frame( 

8829 self, 

8830 other, 

8831 join="outer", 

8832 axis=None, 

8833 level=None, 

8834 copy=True, 

8835 fill_value=None, 

8836 method=None, 

8837 limit=None, 

8838 fill_axis=0, 

8839 ): 

8840 # defaults 

8841 join_index, join_columns = None, None 

8842 ilidx, iridx = None, None 

8843 clidx, cridx = None, None 

8844 

8845 is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries) 

8846 

8847 if axis is None or axis == 0: 

8848 if not self.index.equals(other.index): 

8849 join_index, ilidx, iridx = self.index.join( 

8850 other.index, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True 

8851 ) 

8852 

8853 if axis is None or axis == 1: 

8854 if not is_series and not self.columns.equals(other.columns): 

8855 join_columns, clidx, cridx = self.columns.join( 

8856 other.columns, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True 

8857 ) 

8858 

8859 if is_series: 

8860 reindexers = {0: [join_index, ilidx]} 

8861 else: 

8862 reindexers = {0: [join_index, ilidx], 1: [join_columns, clidx]} 

8863 

8864 left = self._reindex_with_indexers( 

8865 reindexers, copy=copy, fill_value=fill_value, allow_dups=True 

8866 ) 

8867 # other must be always DataFrame 

8868 right = other._reindex_with_indexers( 

8869 {0: [join_index, iridx], 1: [join_columns, cridx]}, 

8870 copy=copy, 

8871 fill_value=fill_value, 

8872 allow_dups=True, 

8873 ) 

8874 

8875 if method is not None: 

8876 left = left.fillna(axis=fill_axis, method=method, limit=limit) 

8877 right = right.fillna(axis=fill_axis, method=method, limit=limit) 

8878 

8879 # if DatetimeIndex have different tz, convert to UTC 

8880 if is_datetime64tz_dtype(left.index): 

8881 if left.index.tz != right.index.tz: 

8882 if join_index is not None: 

8883 left.index = join_index 

8884 right.index = join_index 

8885 

8886 return left.__finalize__(self), right.__finalize__(other) 

8887 

8888 def _align_series( 

8889 self, 

8890 other, 

8891 join="outer", 

8892 axis=None, 

8893 level=None, 

8894 copy=True, 

8895 fill_value=None, 

8896 method=None, 

8897 limit=None, 

8898 fill_axis=0, 

8899 ): 

8900 

8901 is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries) 

8902 

8903 # series/series compat, other must always be a Series 

8904 if is_series: 

8905 if axis: 

8906 raise ValueError("cannot align series to a series other than " "axis 0") 

8907 

8908 # equal 

8909 if self.index.equals(other.index): 

8910 join_index, lidx, ridx = None, None, None 

8911 else: 

8912 join_index, lidx, ridx = self.index.join( 

8913 other.index, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True 

8914 ) 

8915 

8916 left = self._reindex_indexer(join_index, lidx, copy) 

8917 right = other._reindex_indexer(join_index, ridx, copy) 

8918 

8919 else: 

8920 # one has > 1 ndim 

8921 fdata = self._data 

8922 if axis == 0: 

8923 join_index = self.index 

8924 lidx, ridx = None, None 

8925 if not self.index.equals(other.index): 

8926 join_index, lidx, ridx = self.index.join( 

8927 other.index, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True 

8928 ) 

8929 

8930 if lidx is not None: 

8931 fdata = fdata.reindex_indexer(join_index, lidx, axis=1) 

8932 

8933 elif axis == 1: 

8934 join_index = self.columns 

8935 lidx, ridx = None, None 

8936 if not self.columns.equals(other.index): 

8937 join_index, lidx, ridx = self.columns.join( 

8938 other.index, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True 

8939 ) 

8940 

8941 if lidx is not None: 

8942 fdata = fdata.reindex_indexer(join_index, lidx, axis=0) 

8943 else: 

8944 raise ValueError("Must specify axis=0 or 1") 

8945 

8946 if copy and fdata is self._data: 

8947 fdata = fdata.copy() 

8948 

8949 left = self._constructor(fdata) 

8950 

8951 if ridx is None: 

8952 right = other 

8953 else: 

8954 right = other.reindex(join_index, level=level) 

8955 

8956 # fill 

8957 fill_na = notna(fill_value) or (method is not None) 

8958 if fill_na: 

8959 left = left.fillna(fill_value, method=method, limit=limit, axis=fill_axis) 

8960 right = right.fillna(fill_value, method=method, limit=limit) 

8961 

8962 # if DatetimeIndex have different tz, convert to UTC 

8963 if is_series or (not is_series and axis == 0): 

8964 if is_datetime64tz_dtype(left.index): 

8965 if left.index.tz != right.index.tz: 

8966 if join_index is not None: 

8967 left.index = join_index 

8968 right.index = join_index 

8969 

8970 return left.__finalize__(self), right.__finalize__(other) 

8971 

8972 def _where( 

8973 self, 

8974 cond, 

8975 other=np.nan, 

8976 inplace=False, 

8977 axis=None, 

8978 level=None, 

8979 errors="raise", 

8980 try_cast=False, 

8981 ): 

8982 """ 

8983 Equivalent to public method `where`, except that `other` is not 

8984 applied as a function even if callable. Used in __setitem__. 

8985 """ 

8986 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, "inplace") 

8987 

8988 # align the cond to same shape as myself 

8989 cond = com.apply_if_callable(cond, self) 

8990 if isinstance(cond, NDFrame): 

8991 cond, _ = cond.align(self, join="right", broadcast_axis=1) 

8992 else: 

8993 if not hasattr(cond, "shape"): 

8994 cond = np.asanyarray(cond) 

8995 if cond.shape != self.shape: 

8996 raise ValueError("Array conditional must be same shape as " "self") 

8997 cond = self._constructor(cond, **self._construct_axes_dict()) 

8998 

8999 # make sure we are boolean 

9000 fill_value = bool(inplace) 

9001 cond = cond.fillna(fill_value) 

9002 

9003 msg = "Boolean array expected for the condition, not {dtype}" 

9004 

9005 if not isinstance(cond, pd.DataFrame): 

9006 # This is a single-dimensional object. 

9007 if not is_bool_dtype(cond): 

9008 raise ValueError(msg.format(dtype=cond.dtype)) 

9009 elif not cond.empty: 

9010 for dt in cond.dtypes: 

9011 if not is_bool_dtype(dt): 

9012 raise ValueError(msg.format(dtype=dt)) 

9013 

9014 cond = -cond if inplace else cond 

9015 

9016 # try to align with other 

9017 try_quick = True 

9018 if hasattr(other, "align"): 

9019 

9020 # align with me 

9021 if other.ndim <= self.ndim: 

9022 

9023 _, other = self.align( 

9024 other, join="left", axis=axis, level=level, fill_value=np.nan 

9025 ) 

9026 

9027 # if we are NOT aligned, raise as we cannot where index 

9028 if axis is None and not all( 

9029 other._get_axis(i).equals(ax) for i, ax in enumerate(self.axes) 

9030 ): 

9031 raise InvalidIndexError 

9032 

9033 # slice me out of the other 

9034 else: 

9035 raise NotImplementedError( 

9036 "cannot align with a higher " "dimensional NDFrame" 

9037 ) 

9038 

9039 if isinstance(other, np.ndarray): 

9040 

9041 if other.shape != self.shape: 

9042 

9043 if self.ndim == 1: 

9044 

9045 icond = cond.values 

9046 

9047 # GH 2745 / GH 4192 

9048 # treat like a scalar 

9049 if len(other) == 1: 

9050 other = np.array(other[0]) 

9051 

9052 # GH 3235 

9053 # match True cond to other 

9054 elif len(cond[icond]) == len(other): 

9055 

9056 # try to not change dtype at first (if try_quick) 

9057 if try_quick: 

9058 

9059 try: 

9060 new_other = com.values_from_object(self) 

9061 new_other = new_other.copy() 

9062 new_other[icond] = other 

9063 other = new_other 

9064 except Exception: 

9065 try_quick = False 

9066 

9067 # let's create a new (if we failed at the above 

9068 # or not try_quick 

9069 if not try_quick: 

9070 

9071 dtype, fill_value = maybe_promote(other.dtype) 

9072 new_other = np.empty(len(icond), dtype=dtype) 

9073 new_other.fill(fill_value) 

9074 maybe_upcast_putmask(new_other, icond, other) 

9075 other = new_other 

9076 

9077 else: 

9078 raise ValueError( 

9079 "Length of replacements must equal " "series length" 

9080 ) 

9081 

9082 else: 

9083 raise ValueError( 

9084 "other must be the same shape as self " "when an ndarray" 

9085 ) 

9086 

9087 # we are the same shape, so create an actual object for alignment 

9088 else: 

9089 other = self._constructor(other, **self._construct_axes_dict()) 

9090 

9091 if axis is None: 

9092 axis = 0 

9093 

9094 if self.ndim == getattr(other, "ndim", 0): 

9095 align = True 

9096 else: 

9097 align = self._get_axis_number(axis) == 1 

9098 

9099 block_axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

9100 

9101 if inplace: 

9102 # we may have different type blocks come out of putmask, so 

9103 # reconstruct the block manager 

9104 

9105 self._check_inplace_setting(other) 

9106 new_data = self._data.putmask( 

9107 mask=cond, 

9108 new=other, 

9109 align=align, 

9110 inplace=True, 

9111 axis=block_axis, 

9112 transpose=self._AXIS_REVERSED, 

9113 ) 

9114 self._update_inplace(new_data) 

9115 

9116 else: 

9117 new_data = self._data.where( 

9118 other=other, 

9119 cond=cond, 

9120 align=align, 

9121 errors=errors, 

9122 try_cast=try_cast, 

9123 axis=block_axis, 

9124 ) 

9125 

9126 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self)

9136 Where `cond` is %(cond)s, keep the original value. Where 

9137 %(cond_rev)s, replace with corresponding value from `other`. 

9138 If `cond` is callable, it is computed on the %(klass)s and 

9139 should return boolean %(klass)s or array. The callable must 

9140 not change input %(klass)s (though pandas doesn't check it). 

9141

9146 Entries where `cond` is %(cond_rev)s are replaced with 

9147 corresponding value from `other`. 

9148 If other is callable, it is computed on the %(klass)s and 

9149 should return scalar or %(klass)s. The callable must not

9317 _shared_docs[ 

9318 "shift" 

9319 ] = """ 

9320 Shift index by desired number of periods with an optional time `freq`. 

9321 

9322 When `freq` is not passed, shift the index without realigning the data. 

9323 If `freq` is passed (in this case, the index must be date or datetime, 

9324 or it will raise a `NotImplementedError`), the index will be 

9325 increased using the periods and the `freq`. 

9326 

9327 Parameters 

9328 ---------- 

9329 periods : int 

9330 Number of periods to shift. Can be positive or negative. 

9331 freq : DateOffset, tseries.offsets, timedelta, or str, optional 

9332 Offset to use from the tseries module or time rule (e.g. 'EOM'). 

9333 If `freq` is specified then the index values are shifted but the 

9334 data is not realigned. That is, use `freq` if you would like to 

9335 extend the index when shifting and preserve the original data. 

9336 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default None 

9337 Shift direction. 

9338 fill_value : object, optional 

9339 The scalar value to use for newly introduced missing values. 

9340 the default depends on the dtype of `self`. 

9341 For numeric data, ``np.nan`` is used. 

9342 For datetime, timedelta, or period data, etc. :attr:`NaT` is used. 

9343 For extension dtypes, ``self.dtype.na_value`` is used. 

9344 

9345 .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0 

9346 

9347 Returns 

9348 ------- 

9349 %(klass)s 

9350 Copy of input object, shifted. 

9351 

9352 See Also 

9353 -------- 

9354 Index.shift : Shift values of Index. 

9355 DatetimeIndex.shift : Shift values of DatetimeIndex. 

9356 PeriodIndex.shift : Shift values of PeriodIndex. 

9357 tshift : Shift the time index, using the index's frequency if 

9358 available. 

9359 

9360 Examples 

9361 -------- 

9362 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'Col1': [10, 20, 15, 30, 45], 

9363 ... 'Col2': [13, 23, 18, 33, 48], 

9364 ... 'Col3': [17, 27, 22, 37, 52]}) 

9365 

9366 >>> df.shift(periods=3) 

9367 Col1 Col2 Col3 

9368 0 NaN NaN NaN 

9369 1 NaN NaN NaN 

9370 2 NaN NaN NaN 

9371 3 10.0 13.0 17.0 

9372 4 20.0 23.0 27.0 

9373 

9374 >>> df.shift(periods=1, axis='columns') 

9375 Col1 Col2 Col3 

9376 0 NaN 10.0 13.0 

9377 1 NaN 20.0 23.0 

9378 2 NaN 15.0 18.0 

9379 3 NaN 30.0 33.0 

9380 4 NaN 45.0 48.0 

9381

9384 0 0 0 0 

9385 1 0 0 0 

9386 2 0 0 0 

9387 3 10 13 17 

9388 4 20 23 27 

9389 """ 

9390 

9391 @Appender(_shared_docs["shift"] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

9392 def shift(self, periods=1, freq=None, axis=0, fill_value=None): 

9393 if periods == 0: 

9394 return self.copy() 

9395 

9396 block_axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

9397 if freq is None: 

9398 new_data = self._data.shift( 

9399 periods=periods, axis=block_axis, fill_value=fill_value 

9400 ) 

9401 else: 

9402 return self.tshift(periods, freq) 

9403 

9404 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self)

9406 def slice_shift(self, periods=1, axis=0): 

9407 """ 

9408 Equivalent to `shift` without copying data. The shifted data will 

9409 not include the dropped periods and the shifted axis will be smaller 

9410 than the original. 

9411 

9412 Parameters 

9413 ---------- 

9414 periods : int 

9415 Number of periods to move, can be positive or negative 

9416 

9417 Returns 

9418 ------- 

9419 shifted : same type as caller 

9420 

9421 Notes 

9422 ----- 

9423 While the `slice_shift` is faster than `shift`, you may pay for it 

9424 later during alignment. 

9425 """ 

9426 if periods == 0: 

9427 return self 

9428 

9429 if periods > 0: 

9430 vslicer = slice(None, -periods) 

9431 islicer = slice(periods, None) 

9432 else: 

9433 vslicer = slice(-periods, None) 

9434 islicer = slice(None, periods) 

9435 

9436 new_obj = self._slice(vslicer, axis=axis) 

9437 shifted_axis = self._get_axis(axis)[islicer] 

9438 new_obj.set_axis(shifted_axis, axis=axis, inplace=True) 

9439 

9440 return new_obj.__finalize__(self) 

9441 

9442 def tshift(self, periods=1, freq=None, axis=0): 

9443 """ 

9444 Shift the time index, using the index's frequency if available. 

9445 

9446 Parameters 

9447 ---------- 

9448 periods : int 

9449 Number of periods to move, can be positive or negative 

9450 freq : DateOffset, timedelta, or time rule string, default None 

9451 Increment to use from the tseries module or time rule (e.g. 'EOM') 

9452 axis : int or basestring 

9453 Corresponds to the axis that contains the Index 

9454 

9455 Returns 

9456 ------- 

9457 shifted : Series/DataFrame 

9458 

9459 Notes 

9460 ----- 

9461 If freq is not specified then tries to use the freq or inferred_freq 

9462 attributes of the index. If neither of those attributes exist, a 

9463 ValueError is thrown 

9464 """ 

9465 

9466 index = self._get_axis(axis) 

9467 if freq is None: 

9468 freq = getattr(index, "freq", None) 

9469 

9470 if freq is None: 

9471 freq = getattr(index, "inferred_freq", None) 

9472 

9473 if freq is None: 

9474 msg = "Freq was not given and was not set in the index" 

9475 raise ValueError(msg) 

9476 

9477 if periods == 0: 

9478 return self 

9479 

9480 if isinstance(freq, str): 

9481 freq = to_offset(freq) 

9482 

9483 block_axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

9484 if isinstance(index, PeriodIndex): 

9485 orig_freq = to_offset(index.freq) 

9486 if freq == orig_freq: 

9487 new_data = self._data.copy() 

9488 new_data.axes[block_axis] = index.shift(periods) 

9489 else: 

9490 msg = "Given freq %s does not match PeriodIndex freq %s" % ( 

9491 freq.rule_code, 

9492 orig_freq.rule_code, 

9493 ) 

9494 raise ValueError(msg) 

9495 else: 

9496 new_data = self._data.copy() 

9497 new_data.axes[block_axis] = index.shift(periods, freq) 

9498 

9499 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self)
