9501 def truncate(self, before=None, after=None, axis=None, copy=True): 

9502 """ 

9503 Truncate a Series or DataFrame before and after some index value. 

9504 

9505 This is a useful shorthand for boolean indexing based on index 

9506 values above or below certain thresholds. 

9507 

9508 Parameters 

9509 ---------- 

9510 before : date, string, int 

9511 Truncate all rows before this index value. 

9512 after : date, string, int 

9513 Truncate all rows after this index value. 

9514 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, optional 

9515 Axis to truncate. Truncates the index (rows) by default. 

9516 copy : boolean, default is True, 

9517 Return a copy of the truncated section. 

9518 

9519 Returns 

9520 ------- 

9521 type of caller 

9522 The truncated Series or DataFrame. 

9523 

9524 See Also 

9525 -------- 

9526 DataFrame.loc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by label. 

9527 DataFrame.iloc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by position. 

9528 

9529 Notes 

9530 ----- 

9531 If the index being truncated contains only datetime values, 

9532 `before` and `after` may be specified as strings instead of 

9533 Timestamps. 

9534 

9535 Examples 

9536 -------- 

9537 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e'], 

9538 ... 'B': ['f', 'g', 'h', 'i', 'j'], 

9539 ... 'C': ['k', 'l', 'm', 'n', 'o']}, 

9540 ... index=[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]) 

9541 >>> df 

9542 A B C 

9543 1 a f k 

9544 2 b g l 

9545 3 c h m 

9546 4 d i n 

9547 5 e j o 

9548 

9549 >>> df.truncate(before=2, after=4) 

9550 A B C 

9551 2 b g l 

9552 3 c h m 

9553 4 d i n 

9554 

9555 The columns of a DataFrame can be truncated. 

9556 

9557 >>> df.truncate(before="A", after="B", axis="columns") 

9558 A B 

9559 1 a f 

9560 2 b g 

9561 3 c h 

9562 4 d i 

9563 5 e j 

9564 

9565 For Series, only rows can be truncated. 

9566 

9567 >>> df['A'].truncate(before=2, after=4) 

9568 2 b 

9569 3 c 

9570 4 d 

9571 Name: A, dtype: object 

9572 

9573 The index values in ``truncate`` can be datetimes or string 

9574 dates. 

9575 

9576 >>> dates = pd.date_range('2016-01-01', '2016-02-01', freq='s') 

9577 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(index=dates, data={'A': 1}) 

9578 >>> df.tail() 

9579 A 

9580 2016-01-31 23:59:56 1 

9581 2016-01-31 23:59:57 1 

9582 2016-01-31 23:59:58 1 

9583 2016-01-31 23:59:59 1 

9584 2016-02-01 00:00:00 1 

9585 

9586 >>> df.truncate(before=pd.Timestamp('2016-01-05'), 

9587 ... after=pd.Timestamp('2016-01-10')).tail() 

9588 A 

9589 2016-01-09 23:59:56 1 

9590 2016-01-09 23:59:57 1 

9591 2016-01-09 23:59:58 1 

9592 2016-01-09 23:59:59 1 

9593 2016-01-10 00:00:00 1 

9594 

9595 Because the index is a DatetimeIndex containing only dates, we can 

9596 specify `before` and `after` as strings. They will be coerced to 

9597 Timestamps before truncation. 

9598 

9599 >>> df.truncate('2016-01-05', '2016-01-10').tail() 

9600 A 

9601 2016-01-09 23:59:56 1 

9602 2016-01-09 23:59:57 1 

9603 2016-01-09 23:59:58 1 

9604 2016-01-09 23:59:59 1 

9605 2016-01-10 00:00:00 1 

9606 

9607 Note that ``truncate`` assumes a 0 value for any unspecified time 

9608 component (midnight). This differs from partial string slicing, which 

9609 returns any partially matching dates. 

9610 

9611 >>> df.loc['2016-01-05':'2016-01-10', :].tail() 

9612 A 

9613 2016-01-10 23:59:55 1 

9614 2016-01-10 23:59:56 1 

9615 2016-01-10 23:59:57 1 

9616 2016-01-10 23:59:58 1 

9617 2016-01-10 23:59:59 1 

9618 """ 

9619 

9620 if axis is None: 

9621 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

9622 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

9623 ax = self._get_axis(axis) 

9624 

9625 # GH 17935 

9626 # Check that index is sorted 

9627 if not ax.is_monotonic_increasing and not ax.is_monotonic_decreasing: 

9628 raise ValueError("truncate requires a sorted index") 

9629 

9630 # if we have a date index, convert to dates, otherwise 

9631 # treat like a slice 

9632 if ax.is_all_dates: 

9633 from pandas.core.tools.datetimes import to_datetime 

9634 

9635 before = to_datetime(before) 

9636 after = to_datetime(after) 

9637 

9638 if before is not None and after is not None: 

9639 if before > after: 

9640 raise ValueError("Truncate: %s must be after %s" % (after, before)) 

9641 

9642 slicer = [slice(None, None)] * self._AXIS_LEN 

9643 slicer[axis] = slice(before, after) 

9644 result = self.loc[tuple(slicer)] 

9645 

9646 if isinstance(ax, MultiIndex): 

9647 setattr(result, self._get_axis_name(axis), ax.truncate(before, after)) 

9648 

9649 if copy: 

9650 result = result.copy() 

9651 

9652 return result 

9653 

9654 def tz_convert(self, tz, axis=0, level=None, copy=True): 

9655 """ 

9656 Convert tz-aware axis to target time zone. 

9657 

9658 Parameters 

9659 ---------- 

9660 tz : string or pytz.timezone object 

9661 axis : the axis to convert 

9662 level : int, str, default None 

9663 If axis ia a MultiIndex, convert a specific level. Otherwise 

9664 must be None 

9665 copy : boolean, default True 

9666 Also make a copy of the underlying data 

9667 

9668 Returns 

9669 ------- 

9670 %(klass)s 

9671 Object with time zone converted axis. 

9672 

9673 Raises 

9674 ------ 

9675 TypeError 

9676 If the axis is tz-naive. 

9677 """ 

9678 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

9679 ax = self._get_axis(axis) 

9680 

9681 def _tz_convert(ax, tz): 

9682 if not hasattr(ax, "tz_convert"): 

9683 if len(ax) > 0: 

9684 ax_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

9685 raise TypeError( 

9686 "%s is not a valid DatetimeIndex or " "PeriodIndex" % ax_name 

9687 ) 

9688 else: 

9689 ax = DatetimeIndex([], tz=tz) 

9690 else: 

9691 ax = ax.tz_convert(tz) 

9692 return ax 

9693 

9694 # if a level is given it must be a MultiIndex level or 

9695 # equivalent to the axis name 

9696 if isinstance(ax, MultiIndex): 

9697 level = ax._get_level_number(level) 

9698 new_level = _tz_convert(ax.levels[level], tz) 

9699 ax = ax.set_levels(new_level, level=level) 

9700 else: 

9701 if level not in (None, 0, ax.name): 

9702 raise ValueError("The level {0} is not valid".format(level)) 

9703 ax = _tz_convert(ax, tz) 

9704 

9705 result = self._constructor(self._data, copy=copy) 

9706 result = result.set_axis(ax, axis=axis, inplace=False) 

9707 return result.__finalize__(self) 

9708 

9709 def tz_localize( 

9710 self, tz, axis=0, level=None, copy=True, ambiguous="raise", nonexistent="raise" 

9711 ): 

9712 """ 

9713 Localize tz-naive index of a Series or DataFrame to target time zone. 

9714 

9715 This operation localizes the Index. To localize the values in a 

9716 timezone-naive Series, use :meth:`Series.dt.tz_localize`. 

9717 

9718 Parameters 

9719 ---------- 

9720 tz : string or pytz.timezone object 

9721 axis : the axis to localize 

9722 level : int, str, default None 

9723 If axis ia a MultiIndex, localize a specific level. Otherwise 

9724 must be None 

9725 copy : boolean, default True 

9726 Also make a copy of the underlying data 

9727 ambiguous : 'infer', bool-ndarray, 'NaT', default 'raise' 

9728 When clocks moved backward due to DST, ambiguous times may arise. 

9729 For example in Central European Time (UTC+01), when going from 

9730 03:00 DST to 02:00 non-DST, 02:30:00 local time occurs both at 

9731 00:30:00 UTC and at 01:30:00 UTC. In such a situation, the 

9732 `ambiguous` parameter dictates how ambiguous times should be 

9733 handled. 

9734 

9735 - 'infer' will attempt to infer fall dst-transition hours based on 

9736 order 

9737 - bool-ndarray where True signifies a DST time, False designates 

9738 a non-DST time (note that this flag is only applicable for 

9739 ambiguous times) 

9740 - 'NaT' will return NaT where there are ambiguous times 

9741 - 'raise' will raise an AmbiguousTimeError if there are ambiguous 

9742 times 

9743 nonexistent : str, default 'raise' 

9744 A nonexistent time does not exist in a particular timezone 

9745 where clocks moved forward due to DST. Valid values are: 

9746 

9747 - 'shift_forward' will shift the nonexistent time forward to the 

9748 closest existing time 

9749 - 'shift_backward' will shift the nonexistent time backward to the 

9750 closest existing time 

9751 - 'NaT' will return NaT where there are nonexistent times 

9752 - timedelta objects will shift nonexistent times by the timedelta 

9753 - 'raise' will raise an NonExistentTimeError if there are 

9754 nonexistent times 

9755 

9756 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

9757 

9758 Returns 

9759 ------- 

9760 Series or DataFrame 

9761 Same type as the input. 

9762 

9763 Raises 

9764 ------ 

9765 TypeError 

9766 If the TimeSeries is tz-aware and tz is not None. 

9767 

9768 Examples 

9769 -------- 

9770 

9771 Localize local times: 

9772 

9773 >>> s = pd.Series([1], 

9774 ... index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-09-15 01:30:00'])) 

9775 >>> s.tz_localize('CET') 

9776 2018-09-15 01:30:00+02:00 1 

9777 dtype: int64 

9778 

9779 Be careful with DST changes. When there is sequential data, pandas 

9780 can infer the DST time: 

9781 

9782 >>> s = pd.Series(range(7), index=pd.DatetimeIndex([ 

9783 ... '2018-10-28 01:30:00', 

9784 ... '2018-10-28 02:00:00', 

9785 ... '2018-10-28 02:30:00', 

9786 ... '2018-10-28 02:00:00', 

9787 ... '2018-10-28 02:30:00', 

9788 ... '2018-10-28 03:00:00', 

9789 ... '2018-10-28 03:30:00'])) 

9790 >>> s.tz_localize('CET', ambiguous='infer') 

9791 2018-10-28 01:30:00+02:00 0 

9792 2018-10-28 02:00:00+02:00 1 

9793 2018-10-28 02:30:00+02:00 2 

9794 2018-10-28 02:00:00+01:00 3 

9795 2018-10-28 02:30:00+01:00 4 

9796 2018-10-28 03:00:00+01:00 5 

9797 2018-10-28 03:30:00+01:00 6 

9798 dtype: int64 

9799 

9800 In some cases, inferring the DST is impossible. In such cases, you can 

9801 pass an ndarray to the ambiguous parameter to set the DST explicitly 

9802 

9803 >>> s = pd.Series(range(3), index=pd.DatetimeIndex([ 

9804 ... '2018-10-28 01:20:00', 

9805 ... '2018-10-28 02:36:00', 

9806 ... '2018-10-28 03:46:00'])) 

9807 >>> s.tz_localize('CET', ambiguous=np.array([True, True, False])) 

9808 2018-10-28 01:20:00+02:00 0 

9809 2018-10-28 02:36:00+02:00 1 

9810 2018-10-28 03:46:00+01:00 2 

9811 dtype: int64 

9812 

9813 If the DST transition causes nonexistent times, you can shift these 

9814 dates forward or backwards with a timedelta object or `'shift_forward'` 

9815 or `'shift_backwards'`. 

9816 >>> s = pd.Series(range(2), index=pd.DatetimeIndex([ 

9817 ... '2015-03-29 02:30:00', 

9818 ... '2015-03-29 03:30:00'])) 

9819 >>> s.tz_localize('Europe/Warsaw', nonexistent='shift_forward') 

9820 2015-03-29 03:00:00+02:00 0 

9821 2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00 1 

9822 dtype: int64 

9823 >>> s.tz_localize('Europe/Warsaw', nonexistent='shift_backward') 

9824 2015-03-29 01:59:59.999999999+01:00 0 

9825 2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00 1 

9826 dtype: int64 

9827 >>> s.tz_localize('Europe/Warsaw', nonexistent=pd.Timedelta('1H')) 

9828 2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00 0 

9829 2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00 1 

9830 dtype: int64 

9831 """ 

9832 nonexistent_options = ("raise", "NaT", "shift_forward", "shift_backward") 

9833 if nonexistent not in nonexistent_options and not isinstance( 

9834 nonexistent, timedelta 

9835 ): 

9836 raise ValueError( 

9837 "The nonexistent argument must be one of 'raise'," 

9838 " 'NaT', 'shift_forward', 'shift_backward' or" 

9839 " a timedelta object" 

9840 ) 

9841 

9842 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

9843 ax = self._get_axis(axis) 

9844 

9845 def _tz_localize(ax, tz, ambiguous, nonexistent): 

9846 if not hasattr(ax, "tz_localize"): 

9847 if len(ax) > 0: 

9848 ax_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

9849 raise TypeError( 

9850 "%s is not a valid DatetimeIndex or " "PeriodIndex" % ax_name 

9851 ) 

9852 else: 

9853 ax = DatetimeIndex([], tz=tz) 

9854 else: 

9855 ax = ax.tz_localize(tz, ambiguous=ambiguous, nonexistent=nonexistent) 

9856 return ax 

9857 

9858 # if a level is given it must be a MultiIndex level or 

9859 # equivalent to the axis name 

9860 if isinstance(ax, MultiIndex): 

9861 level = ax._get_level_number(level) 

9862 new_level = _tz_localize(ax.levels[level], tz, ambiguous, nonexistent) 

9863 ax = ax.set_levels(new_level, level=level) 

9864 else: 

9865 if level not in (None, 0, ax.name): 

9866 raise ValueError("The level {0} is not valid".format(level)) 

9867 ax = _tz_localize(ax, tz, ambiguous, nonexistent) 

9868 

9869 result = self._constructor(self._data, copy=copy) 

9870 result = result.set_axis(ax, axis=axis, inplace=False) 

9871 return result.__finalize__(self) 

9872 

9873 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

9874 # Numeric Methods 

9875 def abs(self): 

9876 """ 

9877 Return a Series/DataFrame with absolute numeric value of each element. 

9878 

9879 This function only applies to elements that are all numeric. 

9880 

9881 Returns 

9882 ------- 

9883 abs 

9884 Series/DataFrame containing the absolute value of each element. 

9885 

9886 See Also 

9887 -------- 

9888 numpy.absolute : Calculate the absolute value element-wise. 

9889 

9890 Notes 

9891 ----- 

9892 For ``complex`` inputs, ``1.2 + 1j``, the absolute value is 

9893 :math:`\\sqrt{ a^2 + b^2 }`. 

9894 

9895 Examples 

9896 -------- 

9897 Absolute numeric values in a Series. 

9898 

9899 >>> s = pd.Series([-1.10, 2, -3.33, 4]) 

9900 >>> s.abs() 

9901 0 1.10 

9902 1 2.00 

9903 2 3.33 

9904 3 4.00 

9905 dtype: float64 

9906 

9907 Absolute numeric values in a Series with complex numbers. 

9908 

9909 >>> s = pd.Series([1.2 + 1j]) 

9910 >>> s.abs() 

9911 0 1.56205 

9912 dtype: float64 

9913 

9914 Absolute numeric values in a Series with a Timedelta element. 

9915 

9916 >>> s = pd.Series([pd.Timedelta('1 days')]) 

9917 >>> s.abs() 

9918 0 1 days 

9919 dtype: timedelta64[ns] 

9920 

9921 Select rows with data closest to certain value using argsort (from 

9922 `StackOverflow <https://stackoverflow.com/a/17758115>`__). 

9923 

9924 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({ 

9925 ... 'a': [4, 5, 6, 7], 

9926 ... 'b': [10, 20, 30, 40], 

9927 ... 'c': [100, 50, -30, -50] 

9928 ... }) 

9929 >>> df 

9930 a b c 

9931 0 4 10 100 

9932 1 5 20 50 

9933 2 6 30 -30 

9934 3 7 40 -50 

9935 >>> df.loc[(df.c - 43).abs().argsort()] 

9936 a b c 

9937 1 5 20 50 

9938 0 4 10 100 

9939 2 6 30 -30 

9940 3 7 40 -50 

9941 """ 

9942 return np.abs(self) 

9943 

9944 def describe(self, percentiles=None, include=None, exclude=None): 

9945 """ 

9946 Generate descriptive statistics that summarize the central tendency, 

9947 dispersion and shape of a dataset's distribution, excluding 

9948 ``NaN`` values. 

9949 

9950 Analyzes both numeric and object series, as well 

9951 as ``DataFrame`` column sets of mixed data types. The output 

9952 will vary depending on what is provided. Refer to the notes 

9953 below for more detail. 

9954 

9955 Parameters 

9956 ---------- 

9957 percentiles : list-like of numbers, optional 

9958 The percentiles to include in the output. All should 

9959 fall between 0 and 1. The default is 

9960 ``[.25, .5, .75]``, which returns the 25th, 50th, and 

9961 75th percentiles. 

9962 include : 'all', list-like of dtypes or None (default), optional 

9963 A white list of data types to include in the result. Ignored 

9964 for ``Series``. Here are the options: 

9965 

9966 - 'all' : All columns of the input will be included in the output. 

9967 - A list-like of dtypes : Limits the results to the 

9968 provided data types. 

9969 To limit the result to numeric types submit 

9970 ``numpy.number``. To limit it instead to object columns submit 

9971 the ``numpy.object`` data type. Strings 

9972 can also be used in the style of 

9973 ``select_dtypes`` (e.g. ``df.describe(include=['O'])``). To 

9974 select pandas categorical columns, use ``'category'`` 

9975 - None (default) : The result will include all numeric columns. 

9976 exclude : list-like of dtypes or None (default), optional, 

9977 A black list of data types to omit from the result. Ignored 

9978 for ``Series``. Here are the options: 

9979 

9980 - A list-like of dtypes : Excludes the provided data types 

9981 from the result. To exclude numeric types submit 

9982 ``numpy.number``. To exclude object columns submit the data 

9983 type ``numpy.object``. Strings can also be used in the style of 

9984 ``select_dtypes`` (e.g. ``df.describe(include=['O'])``). To 

9985 exclude pandas categorical columns, use ``'category'`` 

9986 - None (default) : The result will exclude nothing. 

9987 

9988 Returns 

9989 ------- 

9990 Series or DataFrame 

9991 Summary statistics of the Series or Dataframe provided. 

9992 

9993 See Also 

9994 -------- 

9995 DataFrame.count: Count number of non-NA/null observations. 

9996 DataFrame.max: Maximum of the values in the object. 

9997 DataFrame.min: Minimum of the values in the object. 

9998 DataFrame.mean: Mean of the values. 

9999 DataFrame.std: Standard deviation of the observations. 

10000 DataFrame.select_dtypes: Subset of a DataFrame including/excluding 

10001 columns based on their dtype. 

10002 

10003 Notes 

10004 ----- 

10005 For numeric data, the result's index will include ``count``, 

10006 ``mean``, ``std``, ``min``, ``max`` as well as lower, ``50`` and 

10007 upper percentiles. By default the lower percentile is ``25`` and the 

10008 upper percentile is ``75``. The ``50`` percentile is the 

10009 same as the median. 

10010 

10011 For object data (e.g. strings or timestamps), the result's index 

10012 will include ``count``, ``unique``, ``top``, and ``freq``. The ``top`` 

10013 is the most common value. The ``freq`` is the most common value's 

10014 frequency. Timestamps also include the ``first`` and ``last`` items. 

10015 

10016 If multiple object values have the highest count, then the 

10017 ``count`` and ``top`` results will be arbitrarily chosen from 

10018 among those with the highest count. 

10019 

10020 For mixed data types provided via a ``DataFrame``, the default is to 

10021 return only an analysis of numeric columns. If the dataframe consists 

10022 only of object and categorical data without any numeric columns, the 

10023 default is to return an analysis of both the object and categorical 

10024 columns. If ``include='all'`` is provided as an option, the result 

10025 will include a union of attributes of each type. 

10026 

10027 The `include` and `exclude` parameters can be used to limit 

10028 which columns in a ``DataFrame`` are analyzed for the output. 

10029 The parameters are ignored when analyzing a ``Series``. 

10030 

10031 Examples 

10032 -------- 

10033 Describing a numeric ``Series``. 

10034 

10035 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3]) 

10036 >>> s.describe() 

10037 count 3.0 

10038 mean 2.0 

10039 std 1.0 

10040 min 1.0 

10041 25% 1.5 

10042 50% 2.0 

10043 75% 2.5 

10044 max 3.0 

10045 dtype: float64 

10046 

10047 Describing a categorical ``Series``. 

10048 

10049 >>> s = pd.Series(['a', 'a', 'b', 'c']) 

10050 >>> s.describe() 

10051 count 4 

10052 unique 3 

10053 top a 

10054 freq 2 

10055 dtype: object 

10056 

10057 Describing a timestamp ``Series``. 

10058 

10059 >>> s = pd.Series([ 

10060 ... np.datetime64("2000-01-01"), 

10061 ... np.datetime64("2010-01-01"), 

10062 ... np.datetime64("2010-01-01") 

10063 ... ]) 

10064 >>> s.describe() 

10065 count 3 

10066 unique 2 

10067 top 2010-01-01 00:00:00 

10068 freq 2 

10069 first 2000-01-01 00:00:00 

10070 last 2010-01-01 00:00:00 

10071 dtype: object 

10072 

10073 Describing a ``DataFrame``. By default only numeric fields 

10074 are returned. 

10075 

10076 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'categorical': pd.Categorical(['d','e','f']), 

10077 ... 'numeric': [1, 2, 3], 

10078 ... 'object': ['a', 'b', 'c'] 

10079 ... }) 

10080 >>> df.describe() 

10081 numeric 

10082 count 3.0 

10083 mean 2.0 

10084 std 1.0 

10085 min 1.0 

10086 25% 1.5 

10087 50% 2.0 

10088 75% 2.5 

10089 max 3.0 

10090 

10091 Describing all columns of a ``DataFrame`` regardless of data type. 

10092 

10093 >>> df.describe(include='all') 

10094 categorical numeric object 

10095 count 3 3.0 3 

10096 unique 3 NaN 3 

10097 top f NaN c 

10098 freq 1 NaN 1 

10099 mean NaN 2.0 NaN 

10100 std NaN 1.0 NaN 

10101 min NaN 1.0 NaN 

10102 25% NaN 1.5 NaN 

10103 50% NaN 2.0 NaN 

10104 75% NaN 2.5 NaN 

10105 max NaN 3.0 NaN 

10106 

10107 Describing a column from a ``DataFrame`` by accessing it as 

10108 an attribute. 

10109 

10110 >>> df.numeric.describe() 

10111 count 3.0 

10112 mean 2.0 

10113 std 1.0 

10114 min 1.0 

10115 25% 1.5 

10116 50% 2.0 

10117 75% 2.5 

10118 max 3.0 

10119 Name: numeric, dtype: float64 

10120 

10121 Including only numeric columns in a ``DataFrame`` description. 

10122 

10123 >>> df.describe(include=[np.number]) 

10124 numeric 

10125 count 3.0 

10126 mean 2.0 

10127 std 1.0 

10128 min 1.0 

10129 25% 1.5 

10130 50% 2.0 

10131 75% 2.5 

10132 max 3.0 

10133 

10134 Including only string columns in a ``DataFrame`` description. 

10135 

10136 >>> df.describe(include=[np.object]) 

10137 object 

10138 count 3 

10139 unique 3 

10140 top c 

10141 freq 1 

10142 

10143 Including only categorical columns from a ``DataFrame`` description. 

10144 

10145 >>> df.describe(include=['category']) 

10146 categorical 

10147 count 3 

10148 unique 3 

10149 top f 

10150 freq 1 

10151 

10152 Excluding numeric columns from a ``DataFrame`` description. 

10153 

10154 >>> df.describe(exclude=[np.number]) 

10155 categorical object 

10156 count 3 3 

10157 unique 3 3 

10158 top f c 

10159 freq 1 1 

10160 

10161 Excluding object columns from a ``DataFrame`` description. 

10162 

10163 >>> df.describe(exclude=[np.object]) 

10164 categorical numeric 

10165 count 3 3.0 

10166 unique 3 NaN 

10167 top f NaN 

10168 freq 1 NaN 

10169 mean NaN 2.0 

10170 std NaN 1.0 

10171 min NaN 1.0 

10172 25% NaN 1.5 

10173 50% NaN 2.0 

10174 75% NaN 2.5 

10175 max NaN 3.0 

10176 """ 

10177 if self.ndim == 2 and self.columns.size == 0: 

10178 raise ValueError("Cannot describe a DataFrame without columns") 

10179 

10180 if percentiles is not None: 

10181 # explicit conversion of `percentiles` to list 

10182 percentiles = list(percentiles) 

10183 

10184 # get them all to be in [0, 1] 

10185 self._check_percentile(percentiles) 

10186 

10187 # median should always be included 

10188 if 0.5 not in percentiles: 

10189 percentiles.append(0.5) 

10190 percentiles = np.asarray(percentiles) 

10191 else: 

10192 percentiles = np.array([0.25, 0.5, 0.75]) 

10193 

10194 # sort and check for duplicates 

10195 unique_pcts = np.unique(percentiles) 

10196 if len(unique_pcts) < len(percentiles): 

10197 raise ValueError("percentiles cannot contain duplicates") 

10198 percentiles = unique_pcts 

10199 

10200 formatted_percentiles = format_percentiles(percentiles) 

10201 

10202 def describe_numeric_1d(series): 

10203 stat_index = ( 

10204 ["count", "mean", "std", "min"] + formatted_percentiles + ["max"] 

10205 ) 

10206 d = ( 

10207 [series.count(), series.mean(), series.std(), series.min()] 

10208 + series.quantile(percentiles).tolist() 

10209 + [series.max()] 

10210 ) 

10211 return pd.Series(d, index=stat_index, name=series.name) 

10212 

10213 def describe_categorical_1d(data): 

10214 names = ["count", "unique"] 

10215 objcounts = data.value_counts() 

10216 count_unique = len(objcounts[objcounts != 0]) 

10217 result = [data.count(), count_unique] 

10218 dtype = None 

10219 if result[1] > 0: 

10220 top, freq = objcounts.index[0], objcounts.iloc[0] 

10221 

10222 if is_datetime64_any_dtype(data): 

10223 tz = data.dt.tz 

10224 asint = data.dropna().values.view("i8") 

10225 top = Timestamp(top) 

10226 if top.tzinfo is not None and tz is not None: 

10227 # Don't tz_localize(None) if key is already tz-aware 

10228 top = top.tz_convert(tz) 

10229 else: 

10230 top = top.tz_localize(tz) 

10231 names += ["top", "freq", "first", "last"] 

10232 result += [ 

10233 top, 

10234 freq, 

10235 Timestamp(asint.min(), tz=tz), 

10236 Timestamp(asint.max(), tz=tz), 

10237 ] 

10238 else: 

10239 names += ["top", "freq"] 

10240 result += [top, freq] 

10241 

10242 # If the DataFrame is empty, set 'top' and 'freq' to None 

10243 # to maintain output shape consistency 

10244 else: 

10245 names += ["top", "freq"] 

10246 result += [np.nan, np.nan] 

10247 dtype = "object" 

10248 

10249 return pd.Series(result, index=names, name=data.name, dtype=dtype) 

10250 

10251 def describe_1d(data): 

10252 if is_bool_dtype(data): 

10253 return describe_categorical_1d(data) 

10254 elif is_numeric_dtype(data): 

10255 return describe_numeric_1d(data) 

10256 elif is_timedelta64_dtype(data): 

10257 return describe_numeric_1d(data) 

10258 else: 

10259 return describe_categorical_1d(data) 

10260 

10261 if self.ndim == 1: 

10262 return describe_1d(self) 

10263 elif (include is None) and (exclude is None): 

10264 # when some numerics are found, keep only numerics 

10265 data = self.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]) 

10266 if len(data.columns) == 0: 

10267 data = self 

10268 elif include == "all": 

10269 if exclude is not None: 

10270 msg = "exclude must be None when include is 'all'" 

10271 raise ValueError(msg) 

10272 data = self 

10273 else: 

10274 data = self.select_dtypes(include=include, exclude=exclude) 

10275 

10276 ldesc = [describe_1d(s) for _, s in data.items()] 

10277 # set a convenient order for rows 

10278 names = [] 

10279 ldesc_indexes = sorted((x.index for x in ldesc), key=len) 

10280 for idxnames in ldesc_indexes: 

10281 for name in idxnames: 

10282 if name not in names: 

10283 names.append(name) 

10284 

10285 d = pd.concat([x.reindex(names, copy=False) for x in ldesc], axis=1, sort=False) 

10286 d.columns = data.columns.copy() 

10287 return d 

10288 

10289 def _check_percentile(self, q): 

10290 """ 

10291 Validate percentiles (used by describe and quantile). 

10292 """ 

10293 

10294 msg = "percentiles should all be in the interval [0, 1]. " "Try {0} instead." 

10295 q = np.asarray(q) 

10296 if q.ndim == 0: 

10297 if not 0 <= q <= 1: 

10298 raise ValueError(msg.format(q / 100.0)) 

10299 else: 

10300 if not all(0 <= qs <= 1 for qs in q): 

10301 raise ValueError(msg.format(q / 100.0)) 

10302 return q

10307 Percentage change between the current and a prior element. 

10308 

10309 Computes the percentage change from the immediately previous row by 

10310 default. This is useful in comparing the percentage of change in a time

10312 

10313 Parameters 

10314 ----------

10321 freq : DateOffset, timedelta, or offset alias string, optional 

10322 Increment to use from time series API (e.g. 'M' or BDay()). 

10323 **kwargs 

10324 Additional keyword arguments are passed into 

10325 `DataFrame.shift` or `Series.shift`. 

10326 

10327 Returns

10330 The same type as the calling object. 

10331 

10332 See Also 

10333 --------

10335 DataFrame.diff : Compute the difference of two elements in a DataFrame. 

10336 Series.shift : Shift the index by some number of periods. 

10337 DataFrame.shift : Shift the index by some number of periods. 

10338

10421 @Appender(_shared_docs["pct_change"] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

10422 def pct_change(self, periods=1, fill_method="pad", limit=None, freq=None, **kwargs): 

10423 # TODO: Not sure if above is correct - need someone to confirm. 

10424 axis = self._get_axis_number(kwargs.pop("axis", self._stat_axis_name)) 

10425 if fill_method is None: 

10426 data = self 

10427 else: 

10428 data = self.fillna(method=fill_method, limit=limit, axis=axis) 

10429 

10430 rs = data.div(data.shift(periods=periods, freq=freq, axis=axis, **kwargs)) - 1 

10431 rs = rs.reindex_like(data) 

10432 if freq is None: 

10433 mask = isna(com.values_from_object(data)) 

10434 np.putmask(rs.values, mask, np.nan) 

10435 return rs

10437 def _agg_by_level(self, name, axis=0, level=0, skipna=True, **kwargs): 

10438 if axis is None: 

10439 raise ValueError("Must specify 'axis' when aggregating by level.") 

10440 grouped = self.groupby(level=level, axis=axis, sort=False) 

10441 if hasattr(grouped, name) and skipna: 

10442 return getattr(grouped, name)(**kwargs) 

10443 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

10444 method = getattr(type(self), name) 

10445 applyf = lambda x: method(x, axis=axis, skipna=skipna, **kwargs) 

10446 return grouped.aggregate(applyf)

10491 @Appender(_num_doc) 

10492 def mad(self, axis=None, skipna=None, level=None): 

10493 if skipna is None: 

10494 skipna = True 

10495 if axis is None: 

10496 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

10497 if level is not None: 

10498 return self._agg_by_level("mad", axis=axis, level=level, skipna=skipna) 

10499 

10500 data = self._get_numeric_data() 

10501 if axis == 0: 

10502 demeaned = data - data.mean(axis=0) 

10503 else: 

10504 demeaned = data.sub(data.mean(axis=1), axis=0) 

10505 return np.abs(demeaned).mean(axis=axis, skipna=skipna)

10811 def transform(self, func, *args, **kwargs): 

10812 result = self.agg(func, *args, **kwargs)

10821 _shared_docs[ 

10822 "valid_index" 

10823 ] = """ 

10824 Return index for %(position)s non-NA/null value. 

10825 

10826 Returns 

10827 ------- 

10828 scalar : type of index 

10829 

10830 Notes 

10831 ----- 

10832 If all elements are non-NA/null, returns None. 

10833 Also returns None for empty %(klass)s. 

10834 """ 

10835 

10836 def _find_valid_index(self, how): 

10837 """ 

10838 Retrieves the index of the first valid value. 

10839 

10840 Parameters 

10841 ---------- 

10842 how : {'first', 'last'} 

10843 Use this parameter to change between the first or last valid index. 

10844 

10845 Returns 

10846 ------- 

10847 idx_first_valid : type of index 

10848 """ 

10849 assert how in ["first", "last"] 

10850 

10851 if len(self) == 0: # early stop 

10852 return None 

10853 is_valid = ~self.isna() 

10854 

10855 if self.ndim == 2: 

10856 is_valid = is_valid.any(1) # reduce axis 1 

10857 

10858 if how == "first": 

10859 idxpos = is_valid.values[::].argmax() 

10860 

10861 if how == "last": 

10862 idxpos = len(self) - 1 - is_valid.values[::-1].argmax() 

10863 

10864 chk_notna = is_valid.iat[idxpos] 

10865 idx = self.index[idxpos] 

10866 

10867 if not chk_notna: 

10868 return None 

10869 return idx 

10870 

10871 @Appender( 

10872 _shared_docs["valid_index"] % {"position": "first", "klass": "Series/DataFrame"} 

10873 ) 

10874 def first_valid_index(self): 

10875 return self._find_valid_index("first") 

10876 

10877 @Appender( 

10878 _shared_docs["valid_index"] % {"position": "last", "klass": "Series/DataFrame"} 

10879 ) 

10880 def last_valid_index(self): 

10881 return self._find_valid_index("last")

10884def _doc_parms(cls): 

10885 """Return a tuple of the doc parms.""" 

10886 axis_descr = "{%s}" % ", ".join( 

10887 "{0} ({1})".format(a, i) for i, a in enumerate(cls._AXIS_ORDERS) 

10888 ) 

10889 name = cls._constructor_sliced.__name__ if cls._AXIS_LEN > 1 else "scalar" 

10890 name2 = cls.__name__ 

10891 return axis_descr, name, name2

10960skipna : bool, default True

10965level : int or level name, default None 

10966 If the axis is a MultiIndex (hierarchical), count along a 

10967 particular level, collapsing into a %(name1)s. 

10968**kwargs : any, default None 

10969 Additional keywords have no effect but might be accepted for 

10970 compatibility with NumPy. 

10971

10976 is returned.

11564 ):

11571 if skipna is None:

11646def _make_cum_function( 

11647 cls, 

11648 name, 

11649 name1, 

11650 name2, 

11651 axis_descr, 

11652 desc, 

11653 accum_func, 

11654 accum_func_name, 

11655 mask_a, 

11656 mask_b, 

11657 examples, 

11658): 

11659 @Substitution( 

11660 desc=desc, 

11661 name1=name1, 

11662 name2=name2, 

11663 axis_descr=axis_descr, 

11664 accum_func_name=accum_func_name, 

11665 examples=examples, 

11666 ) 

11667 @Appender(_cnum_doc) 

11668 def cum_func(self, axis=None, skipna=True, *args, **kwargs): 

11669 skipna = nv.validate_cum_func_with_skipna(skipna, args, kwargs, name) 

11670 if axis is None: 

11671 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

11672 else: 

11673 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

11674 

11675 y = com.values_from_object(self).copy() 

11676 

11677 if skipna and issubclass(y.dtype.type, (np.datetime64, np.timedelta64)): 

11678 result = accum_func(y, axis) 

11679 mask = isna(self) 

11680 np.putmask(result, mask, iNaT) 

11681 elif skipna and not issubclass(y.dtype.type, (np.integer, np.bool_)): 

11682 mask = isna(self) 

11683 np.putmask(y, mask, mask_a) 

11684 result = accum_func(y, axis) 

11685 np.putmask(result, mask, mask_b) 

11686 else: 

11687 result = accum_func(y, axis) 

11688 

11689 d = self._construct_axes_dict() 

11690 d["copy"] = False 

11691 return self._constructor(result, **d).__finalize__(self) 

11692 

11693 return set_function_name(cum_func, name, cls)

11698): 

11699 @Substitution(
